{"title_page": "Sree Indilayappan Temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Sree Indilayappan Temple, Marayikkodu\n| image              = \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02.jpg\n| caption            = Sree Indilayappan Temple\n| map_type        = Kerala\n| coordinates        = {{coord|8|59|36|N|76|48|29|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption        = Location in Kerala\n| native_name        = \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02, \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d\n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Kerala]]\n| district           = [[Kollam]]\n| locale             = [[Kottarakkara]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = [[Lord Shiva|Shiva]] and [[Lord Vishnu|Vishnu]]\n| festivals= \n| architecture       = [[South Indian]]\n| temple_quantity  = 2\n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = \n| creator            = The Temple\n| website            = http://marayikkodu.org\n}}\n'''Marayikkodu Sree Indilayappan Kshethram''' (\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d3e\u0d33\u0d02:[[:ml:\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02|\u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02]], \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d)  is a powerful 1500-year-old [[Hindu]] temple in [[South India]]. Non-Hindus are permitted in the temple. It is in Karickom, 5&nbsp;km from [[Kottarakara]].\n\n==Temple==\n[[Shiva]] ([[Shiva Lingam]]), [[Parvati|Devi Parvathy]] and [[Vishnu]] are the main [[deities]] of this temple. The sub-deities of the temple are [[Lord Ganesh]], [[Nagaraja|Nagarajavu & Nagayakshi]], Brahmarakshas and Yakshi.\n\nHere devotees are considering the temple as two. One is [[Lord Shiva Temples in Kerala|Lord Shiva Temple]] and the other is [[Lord Vishnu Temples in Kerala|Lord Vishnu Temple]]. The Lord Shiva temple has two separate sanctum sanctorums, one devoted to Lord Shiva (Shivalingam), looking to the east, and the other for Devi Parvathy looking to the west. The Lord Vishnu temple has one sanctum sanctorum for Lord Vishnu, looking to the east.\n\nThe [[Lord Ganesha]] shrine has one separate sanctum sanctorum. As per [[vastu]], the sanctum sanctorum is located on the \"Kanni mula\" (south-west corner) of [[Lord Shiva Temples in Kerala|Lord Shiva temple]]. [[Nagaraja|Sri Nagaraj & Nagayakshi]] and Brahmarakshas are worshipping devotees on the \"Kanni mula\" of Lord Ganesha. Yakshi have the place beneath the Strychine tree (Kanjirum) near the Lord Vishnu's sanctum sanctorum.<ref name=Temple>{{Cite web|url=http://marayikkodu.org |title= The Official Website - Marayikkodu Sree Indilayappan Temple| accessdate=10 July 2011| publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Kerala|Sree Indilayappan Temple}}\n{{Kollam district}}\n\n[[Category:Ganesha temples]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Kollam district]]\n\n\n{{Kollam-geo-stub}}\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Sree Indilayappan Temple, Marayikkodu\n| image              = \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02.jpg\n| caption            = Sree Indilayappan Temple\n| map_type        = Kerala\n| coordinates        = {{coord|8|59|36|N|76|48|29|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption        = Location in Kerala\n| native_name        = \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02, \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d\n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Kerala]]\n| district           = [[Kollam]]\n| locale             = [[Kottarakkara]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = [[Lord Shiva|Shiva]] and [[Lord Vishnu|Vishnu]]\n| festivals= \n| architecture       = [[South Indian]]\n| temple_quantity  = 2\n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = \n| creator            = The Temple\n| website            = http://marayikkodu.org\n}}\n'''Marayikkodu Sree Indilayappan Kshethram''' (\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d3e\u0d33\u0d02:[[:ml:\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02|\u0d07\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02]], \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d)  is a powerful 1500-year-old [[Hindu]] temple in [[South India]]. Non-Hindus are permitted in the temple. It is in Karickom, 5&nbsp;km from [[Kottarakara]].\n\n==Temple==\n[[Lord Shiva]] ([[Shiva Lingam]]), [[Parvati|Devi Parvathy]] and [[Lord Vishnu]] are the main [[deities]] of this temple. The sub-deities of the temple are [[Lord Ganesh]], [[Nagaraja|Nagarajavu & Nagayakshi]], Brahmarakshas and Yakshi.\n\nHere devotees are considering the temple as two. One is [[Lord Shiva Temples in Kerala|Lord Shiva Temple]] and the other is [[Lord Vishnu Temples in Kerala|Lord Vishnu Temple]]. The Lord Shiva temple has two separate sanctum sanctorums, one devoted to Lord Shiva (Shivalingam), looking to the east, and the other for Devi Parvathy looking to the west. The Lord Vishnu temple has one sanctum sanctorum for Lord Vishnu, looking to the east.\n\nThe [[Lord Ganesha]] shrine has one separate sanctum sanctorum. As per [[vastu]], the sanctum sanctorum is located on the \"Kanni mula\" (south-west corner) of [[Lord Shiva Temples in Kerala|Lord Shiva temple]]. [[Nagaraja|Sri Nagaraj & Nagayakshi]] and Brahmarakshas are worshipping devotees on the \"Kanni mula\" of Lord Ganesha. Yakshi have the place beneath the Strychine tree (Kanjirum) near the Lord Vishnu's sanctum sanctorum.<ref name=Temple>{{Cite web|url=http://marayikkodu.org |title= The Official Website - Marayikkodu Sree Indilayappan Temple| accessdate=10 July 2011| publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Kerala|Sree Indilayappan Temple}}\n{{Kollam district}}\n\n[[Category:Ganesha temples]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Kollam district]]\n\n\n{{Kollam-geo-stub}}\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTemple:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sree_Indilayappan_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Hart Island (Bronx)", "text_new": "{{short description|Small island, part of the Pelham Islands, in the Bronx, New York}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Hart Island\n| image_name       = Hart Island, Bronx, 2012 (cropped).JPG\n| image_alt        = Aerial view of Hart Island\n| image_caption    = Aerial view of Hart Island, in 2012\n| image_size       = \n| image_map        = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.735|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.8525|-73.7700}}}}\n| map_alt          =  \n| map_size         =\n| map_caption      = Location in New York City\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_link =\n| nickname         =\n| location         = [[Long Island Sound]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|40|51|9|N|73|46|12|W|display=inline, title}}\n| archipelago      = [[Pelham Islands]]\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_acre         = 131.22     <!-- | area             = {{convert|131.22|acre|km2|abbr=on}} -->\n| length_mi        = 1.0\n| width_mi         = 0.33\n| highest_mount    =\n| elevation_ft     =\n| country          =\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[City]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[New York City]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = [[The Bronx|Bronx]]\n| population       =\n| population_as_of =\n| density_sqmi     =\n| ethnic_groups    =\n}}\n'''Hart Island''', sometimes referred to as '''Hart's Island''',{{efn|See, for instance:<ref name=\"hunter\"/><ref>{{cite fednyc}}</ref>}} is located at the western end of [[Long Island Sound]], in the northeast [[the Bronx|Bronx]], [[New York City]]. Measuring approximately {{convert|1|mi|km}} long by {{convert|0.33|mi|km|abbr=}} wide, Hart Island is part of the [[Pelham Islands]] archipelago, to the east of [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]].\n\nThe island's first public use was as a training ground for the [[United States Colored Troops]] in 1864. Since then, Hart Island has been the location of a [[American Civil War prison camps|Union Civil War prison camp]], a [[psychiatric institution]], a [[tuberculosis sanatorium]], a [[potter's field]] with mass burials, a homeless shelter, a boys' [[reformatory]], a jail, and a drug rehabilitation center. Several other structures, such as an amusement park, were planned for Hart Island but not built. During the [[Cold War (1953\u20131962)|Cold War]], [[Nike missile|Nike defense missiles]] were stationed on Hart Island. The island was intermittently used as a prison and a homeless shelter until 1967, and the last inhabited structures were abandoned in 1977. The island now serves as the city's potter's field, run by the [[New York City Department of Correction]] until 2019, when the [[New York City Council]] voted to transfer jurisdiction to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]].\n\nThe remains of more than one million people are buried on Hart Island, though since the first decade of the 21st century, there are fewer than 1,500 burials a year. Burials on Hart Island include individuals who were not claimed by their families or did not have private funerals; the homeless and the indigent; and mass burials of disease victims, including those who died from [[AIDS]. There is no confirmation that victims of COVID-19 have been buried there. \n\nAccess to the island is restricted by the Department of Correction, which operates an infrequent ferryboat service and imposes strict visitation quotas. Burials are conducted by inmates at the [[Rikers Island]] jail. The Hart Island Project, a public charity founded by visual artist Melinda Hunt, has tried to improve access to the island and make burial records more easily available. Prior to 2019, several laws to transfer jurisdiction to the Parks Department had been proposed to ease public access to Hart Island.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThere are numerous theories about the possible origins for the island's name. In one, British [[Cartographers#18th century|cartographers]] named it \"Heart Island\" in 1775 due to its organ-like shape but the 'e' was dropped shortly after.<ref name=\"fascinates\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/27/nyregion/an-island-of-the-dead-fascinates-the-living.html|title=An Island Of the Dead Fascinates The Living|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=January 27, 2003|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111023538/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/27/nyregion/an-island-of-the-dead-fascinates-the-living.html|archive-date=November 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} A map drawn in 1777 and subsequent maps refer to the island as \"Hart Island\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} Other names given to the island during the late 18th century were \"Little Minneford Island\" and \"Spectacle Island\", the latter because the island's shape was thought to resemble [[Glasses|spectacles]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}\n\nAnother theory, based on the meaning of the English word \"[[Hart (deer)|hart]]\", which means \"stag\", is that the island was named when it was used as a game preserve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=11613|title=The Islands of Pelham Bay|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=November 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309172413/http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=11613|archive-date=March 9, 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> Another version holds that it was named in reference to deer that migrated from the mainland during periods when ice covered that part of Long Island Sound.<ref name=\"hunt\">{{cite book | last=Hunt | first=Melinda | title=Hart Island | publisher=Scalo | year=1998 | isbn=978-3-931141-90-5 | oclc=40373838 |first2=Joel |last2=Sternfeld }}</ref>{{rp|19}}<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zRjMPZW4heMC|title=The Other Islands of New York City: A History and Guide (Third Edition)|last=Seitz|first=Sharon|last2=Miller|first2=Stuart|year=2011|publisher=The Countryman Press|isbn=978-1-58157-886-7|location=|pages=138\u2013144|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|140}}\n\n== Geography ==\nHart Island is approximately {{convert|1|mi|km}} long by {{convert|0.33|mi|km|abbr=}} wide at its widest point. It lies about {{convert|0.33|mi|km}} off the eastern shore of City Island.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WeVTP3GyFH0C&pg=PA77|title=The Bronx, in Bits and Pieces|last=Twomey|first=Bill|publisher=Rooftop Publishing|year=2007|isbn=978-1-60008-062-3|location=|pages=74\u201379|access-date=}}</ref>{{Rp|75}}<ref name=\":4\" /> The island's area is disputed; according to some sources, it is {{Convert|101|acre|ha|abbr=}},<ref name=\"fascinates\" /><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/hart.html|title=Hart Island|publisher=New York Correction History Society|access-date=December 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009002256/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/hart.html|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> while others state that it is {{Convert|131|acre|ha|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2017/05/09/inside-the-mysteries-of-hart-island-in-the-bronx-the-cemetery-of-the-unknown/|title=Inside the mysteries of Hart Island in the Bronx, the cemetery of the unknown|first=Dan|last=Mannarino|date=May 9, 2017|publisher=[[WPIX]]|access-date=December 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101002846/https://pix11.com/2017/05/09/inside-the-mysteries-of-hart-island-in-the-bronx-the-cemetery-of-the-unknown/|archive-date=January 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-potters-idUSKCN0ZD2T7|title=New York allows rare glimpse of its potter's field cemetery|date=June 27, 2016|publisher=Reuters|access-date=December 31, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101002821/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-potters-idUSKCN0ZD2T7|archive-date=January 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hart Island is isolated from the rest of the city: there is no electricity and the only means of access is via ferryboat.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"News 12 The Bronx 2017\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:USCGS Chart number 361 (1884).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A nautical chart of the island from 1884|1884 Nautical Chart]]\n\n=== Early history ===\n\nBefore European colonization, Hart Island was occupied by the [[Siwanoy]] tribe of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]], who were indigenous to the area. In 1654, English physician [[Thomas Pell]] purchased the island from the Siwanoy as part of a {{Convert|9,166|acres|km2|adj=mid}} property.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|140}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Lustenberger |first=Anita A. |year=2000 |url=http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=64 |title=A Short Genealogy of Hart Island |publisher=[[New York Genealogical and Biographical Society]] |access-date=November 5, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007100410/http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=64 |archive-date=October 7, 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Pell died in 1669 and ownership passed to his nephew Sir John Pell, the son of British mathematician [[John Pell]]. The island remained in the Pell family until 1774, when it was sold to [[Oliver De Lancey (British Army officer, died 1822)|Oliver De Lancey]]. It was later sold to the Rodman, Haight, and Hunter families, in that order.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} According to Elliott Gorn, Hart Island had become \"a favorite pugilistic hideaway\" by the early 19th century. Bouts of [[bare-knuckle boxing]] held on the island could draw thousands of spectators.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|140}}\n\nThe first public use of Hart Island was training the [[31st United States Colored Infantry Regiment|31st Infantry Regiment]] of the [[United States Colored Troops]] beginning in 1864.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/usct01.html|title=Civil War Colored Troops on DOC islands|publisher=New York Correction History Society|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512114740/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/usct01.html|archive-date=May 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\">{{cite web |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/1773.pdf |title=Phase IA - Documentary Study and Archaeological Assessment for the Hart Island, Bronx (Bronx County), New York \u2013 Shoreline Stabilization Project |date=September 2017 |first=Alyssa |last=Loorya |first2=Eileen |last2=Kao |editor-first=Christopher |editor-last=Ricciardi |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318135010/http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/1773.pdf |archive-date=March 18, 2019 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|15}} A [[steamboat]] called ''John Romer'' shuttled recruits to the island from [[The Battery (Manhattan)|the Battery]] at the southern tip of Manhattan. A commander's house and a recruits' barracks were built; the barracks included a library and a concert room;<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} it could house 2,000 to 3,000 recruits at a time, and over 50,000 men were ultimately trained there.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|76}}\n\nIn November 1864, construction of a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] on Hart Island with room for 5,000 prisoners started.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} The camp was used for four months in 1865 during the [[American Civil War]]. The island housed 3,413 captured [[Confederate States Army|Confederate Army]] soldiers.<ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\"/>{{rp|16}} Of these, 235 died in the camp and were buried in [[Cypress Hills Cemetery]]. Following the Civil War, indigent veterans were buried on the island in soldier's plots, which were separate from the potter's field and at the same location. Some of these soldiers were moved to [[West Farms Soldiers Cemetery]] in 1916 and others were removed to Cypress Hills Cemetery in 1941.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/cw_pows/html/cwpows7.html |title=Hart Island: City's Concentration Camp|publisher=New York Correction History Society|date= |access-date=April 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716031443/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/cw_pows/html/cwpows7.html |archive-date=July 16, 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Addition of cemetery===\n<!--[[File:A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by Jacob Riis.jpg|thumb|alt=A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, seen circa 1890|A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by [[Jacob Riis]]]]-->\n\nThe first burials on Hart Island were those of 20 [[Union Army]] soldiers during the American Civil War.<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1869/02/27/archives/purchase-of-harts-island.html|title=Purchase of Hart's Island|date=February 27, 1869|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705003808/https://www.nytimes.com/1869/02/27/archives/purchase-of-harts-island.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 27, 1868, New York City purchased the island from Edward Hunter, who also owned nearby [[Hunter Island (Bronx)|Hunter Island]], for $75,000.<ref name=\"hunter\" /><ref name=\"fascinates\" /><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}}<ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\"/>{{rp|18}} City burials started shortly afterward.<ref name=\"hunter\" /> In 1869, a 24-year-old woman named Louisa Van Slyke, who died in [[City Hospital (Roosevelt Island)|Charity Hospital]], was the first person to be buried in the island's {{convert|45|acre|m2|adj=on}} public graveyard.<ref name=\"hunt\"/><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Brady |title=A Chance to Be Mourned|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|date=November 12, 2006|access-date=August 23, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/12/nyregion/thecity/12home.html?pagewanted=all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731045249/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/12/nyregion/thecity/12home.html?pagewanted=all |archive-date=July 31, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The cemetery then became known as \"City Cemetery\" and \"Potter's Field\".<ref>{{cite web | title=In The Potter's Field.; Burying The City's Pauper Dead | work=The New York Times | language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 | date=March 3, 1878 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1878/03/03/archives/in-the-potters-field-burying-the-citys-pauper-dead-the-voyage-of.html | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020001/https://www.nytimes.com/1878/03/03/archives/in-the-potters-field-burying-the-citys-pauper-dead-the-voyage-of.html | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 1880, ''The New York Times'' described the island as \"the [[Green-Wood Cemetery|Green-Wood]] of [[Five Points, Manhattan|Five Points]]\", comparing an expansive cemetery in Brooklyn with a historically poor neighborhood in Manhattan. The newspaper also said of Hart Island, \"This is where the rough pine boxes go that come from Blackwell's Island\", in reference to the influx of corpses being transported from the hospitals on modern-day [[Roosevelt Island]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1880/11/21/archives/islands-about-newyork-in-the-upper-bay-and-in-the-east-river.html|title=Islands About New-York; in the Upper Bay and in the East River.|date=November 21, 1880|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210807/https://www.nytimes.com/1880/11/21/archives/islands-about-newyork-in-the-upper-bay-and-in-the-east-river.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The potter's field on Hart Island replaced two previous potter's fields on the current sites of [[Washington Square Park]] and [[New York Public Library Main Branch]] in Manhattan. The number of burials on Hart Island exceeded 500,000 by 1958.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/22/archives/about-new-york-citys-unclaimed-dead-lie-on-lonely-tip-of-hart.html|title=About New York; City's Unclaimed Dead Lie on Lonely Tip of Hart Island Off the Bronx|last=Robertson|first=Nan|date=September 22, 1958|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232532/https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/22/archives/about-new-york-citys-unclaimed-dead-lie-on-lonely-tip-of-hart.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Juxtaposition of uses ===\n\nHart Island was used as a [[quarantine station]] during the 1870 [[yellow fever]] epidemic. In that period, the island contained a women's [[psychiatric hospital]] called The Pavilion, which was built 1885, as well as a [[Tuberculosis|tubercularium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/11/10/archives/criticises-a-city-hospital-grand-jury-says-harts-island.html|title=Grand Jury Says Hart's Island Tuberculosis Ward is Unsuitable|date=November 10, 1917|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|page=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705005207/https://www.nytimes.com/1917/11/10/archives/criticises-a-city-hospital-grand-jury-says-harts-island.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> There was also an industrial school with 300 students on the island.<ref name=\":2\" /> After an 1892 investigation found the city's asylums were overcrowded, it was proposed to expand those on Hart Island from 1,100 to 1,500 beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1893/06/27/archives/overcrowding-the-insane-new-buildings-soon-to-give-relief-to-city.html|title=Overcrowding The Insane; New Buildings Soon To Give Relief To City Patients|date=June 27, 1893|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103212337/https://www.nytimes.com/1893/06/27/archives/overcrowding-the-insane-new-buildings-soon-to-give-relief-to-city.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-on-yellow sketch showing the Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island|Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island, 1877]]\nIn the late 19th century, Hart Island became the location of a boys' [[workhouse]], which was an extension of the prison and almshouse on Blackwell Island. A workhouse for men was established in 1895, and was followed by a workhouse for young boys ten years later.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}} By the early 20th century, Hart Island housed about 2,000 delinquent boys as well as elderly male prisoners from Blackwell's [[Prison|penitentiary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/10/03/104655426.pdf|title=Likes Life in Workhouse: Inmates Writes of 'Good Eats, No Work, and Bum Arguments'|date=October 3, 1915|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 4, 2018}}</ref> The prison on Hart Island grew; it had its own band and a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] prison chapel.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|77}} The cornerstone for the $60,000 chapel was laid in 1931<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/26/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-prison-chapel-mgr-lavelle-addresses-1800-at.html|title=Cornerstone Laid For Prison Chapel; Mgr. Lavelle Addresses 1,800 at Hart's Island\u2014Building to Cost $60,000.|date=October 26, 1931|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114044329/https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/26/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-prison-chapel-mgr-lavelle-addresses-1800-at.html|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and it was opened the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/05/01/archives/cardinal-to-dedicate-prison-chapel-today-ceremony-on-harts-island.html|title=Cardinal To Dedicate Prison Chapel Today; Ceremony on Harts Island to Be Held at 10:30 A.M. \u2013 Drive On for Building Funds.|date=May 1, 1932|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232619/https://www.nytimes.com/1932/05/01/archives/cardinal-to-dedicate-prison-chapel-today-ceremony-on-harts-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, John Hunter sold his {{Convert|4|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} tract of land on Hart Island's west side to Solomon Riley, a millionaire real estate speculator from [[Barbados]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/01/nyregion/fyi-771465.html|title=F.y.i.|last=Schneider|first=Daniel B.|date=March 1, 1998|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210932/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/01/nyregion/fyi-771465.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Riley subsequently proposed to build an amusement park on Hart Island, which would have served the primarily black community of [[Harlem]] in Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141\u2013142}} It was referred to as the \"Negro [[Coney Island]]\"<ref name=\":3\" /> because at the time, African Americans were banned from the [[Playland (New York)|Rye Playland]] and [[Dobbs Ferry, New York|Dobbs Ferry]] amusement parks in the New York City area.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":3\" /> Riley had started building a dance hall, boardinghouses, and a boardwalk, and purchased sixty steamboats for the operation.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":3\" /> The state government raised concerns about the proposed park's proximity to a jail and hospital,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/07/archives/opposes-resort-on-harts-island-state-prison-commission-tells-mayor.html|title=Opposes Resort on Hart's Island; State Prison Commission Tells Mayor Hylan City Should Acquire Property.|date=May 7, 1925|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210805/https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/07/archives/opposes-resort-on-harts-island-state-prison-commission-tells-mayor.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the city condemned the land in 1925.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/17/archives/city-decides-to-take-harts-island-coney-will-get-pleasure-resort-by.html|title=City Decides To Take Hart's Island 'Coney'; Will Get Pleasure Resort by Condemnation \u2013 Valued at $20,000 in 1922, Now $160,000.|date=June 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210734/https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/17/archives/city-decides-to-take-harts-island-coney-will-get-pleasure-resort-by.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Riley was later paid $144,000 for the seizure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/26/archives/city-must-pay-144015-negroes-win-big-award-for-land-seized-near.html|title=City Must Pay $144,015; Negroes Win Big Award for Land Seized Near Reformatory.|date=November 26, 1927|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210853/https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/26/archives/city-must-pay-144015-negroes-win-big-award-for-land-seized-near.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== After World War II ===\nThe prison population of Hart Island was moved to [[Rikers Island]] during [[World War II]], and Hart Island's former workhouse was used as a disciplinary barracks by the [[United States Armed Forces]]. Rikers Island soon became overcrowded with prisoners.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The [[New York City Department of Correction]] reopened Hart Island as a prison following the war, but the facilities were considered inadequate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/03/31/archives/800000-project-urged-planning-body-calls-for-funds-for-rikers.html|title=$800,000 Project Urged; Planning Body Calls for Funds for Rikers Island Unit|date=March 31, 1949|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108003115/https://www.nytimes.com/1949/03/31/archives/800000-project-urged-planning-body-calls-for-funds-for-rikers.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The New York City Board of Estimate approved the construction of a homeless shelter on the island in 1950; it was intended to serve 2,000 people.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}} The homeless shelter operated from 1951 to 1954;<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} it was also used to house [[Alcoholism|alcoholics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27166768/|first=John|last=Webster|title=Alcoholism a Disease Not a Crime|date=March 26, 1954|work=New York Daily News|access-date=January 13, 2019|page=148|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Residents of nearby City Island opposed the inclusion of the homeless shelter.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/22/archives/assail-hart-island-plan-city-islanders-object-to-housing-of.html|title=Assail Hart Island Plan; City Islanders Object to Housing of Homeless Men Nearby|date=February 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108045723/https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/22/archives/assail-hart-island-plan-city-islanders-object-to-housing-of.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The New York City Welfare Department closed the homeless shelter and the Department of Correction regained control of the island.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}} The Department of Correction opened an alcoholism treatment center on Hart Island in 1955.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/11/16/archives/citys-aid-to-alcoholics-hailed-harts-island-project-is-inspected.html|title=City's Aid to Alcoholics Hailed; Harts Island Project Is Inspected|date=November 16, 1955|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> A courthouse, which ruled on cases involving the homeless, was opened on Hart Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/25/archives/new-court-to-aid-derelicts-of-city-hart-island-setup-to-relieve.html|title=New Court to Aid Derelicts of City; Hart Island Set-Up to Relieve 'Disgraceful' Detention Pens After Sept. 5|date=June 25, 1955|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108003114/https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/25/archives/new-court-to-aid-derelicts-of-city-hart-island-setup-to-relieve.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The island housed between 1,200 and 1,800 prisoners serving short sentences of between 10 days and two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27705314/|title=He's The Burying Kind|date=December 2, 1963|work=New York Daily News|access-date=January 27, 2019|page=177|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the island was retrofitted with [[Nike Ajax]] [[missile silo]]s. Battery NY-15, as the silos were known, were part of the [[United States Army]] base [[Fort Slocum (New York)|Fort Slocum]] from 1956 to 1961 and were operated by the army's 66th Antiaircraft Artillery Missile Battalion. The silos were underground and were powered by large generators.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\"nyt1\" /> Some silos were also built on [[Davids' Island (New York)|Davids' Island]]. The integrated fire control system that tracked the targets and directed missiles was at Fort Slocum. The last components of the missile system were closed in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/05/nyregion/city-lore-when-nike-meant-more-than-just-do-it.html|title=When Nike Meant More Than 'Just Do It'|last=Vanderbilt|first=Tom|date=March 5, 2000|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=August 25, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111023545/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/05/nyregion/city-lore-when-nike-meant-more-than-just-do-it.html|archive-date=November 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of a new $7 million workhouse on Hart Island to replace the existing facility was announced in 1959.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/05/13/archives/7000000-workhouse-set-for-rikers-island.html|title=$7,000,000 Workhouse Set for Rikers Island|date=May 13, 1959|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232541/https://www.nytimes.com/1959/05/13/archives/7000000-workhouse-set-for-rikers-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A baseball field was dedicated at the Hart Island prison the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/05/27/archives/stadium-opened-for-hart-island-prisoners-fill-600-seats-from-ebbets.html|title=Stadium Opened for Hart Island; Prisoners Fill 600 Seats From Ebbets Field Given by Apartment Builder|date=May 27, 1960|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232546/https://www.nytimes.com/1960/05/27/archives/stadium-opened-for-hart-island-prisoners-fill-600-seats-from-ebbets.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was named Kratter Field, after [[Marvin Kratter]], a businessman who had donated 2,200 seats saved from the demolished [[Ebbets Field]] stadium.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The seats deteriorated after being outdoors for several years, and by 2000, had been donated to various people and organizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/27/nyregion/ebbets-lights-dimmed-again-in-city-prizing-relics-link-to-dodgers-needs-a-home.html|title=Ebbets Lights Dimmed Again; In City Prizing Relics, Link to Dodgers Needs a Home|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=September 27, 2000|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232607/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/27/nyregion/ebbets-lights-dimmed-again-in-city-prizing-relics-link-to-dodgers-needs-a-home.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe island continued to be used as a prison until 1966, when the prison was closed due to changes in the penal code.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|79}}<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} After it closed, a [[drug rehabilitation]] center was proposed for Hart Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/02/16/archives/hart-island-site-for-addicts-home-former-users-will-offer-only-help.html|title=Hart Island Site For Addicts' Home; Former Users Will Offer Only Help at Center City Will Operate It|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=February 16, 1967|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107233232/https://www.nytimes.com/1967/02/16/archives/hart-island-site-for-addicts-home-former-users-will-offer-only-help.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The center became [[Phoenix House]], which opened in 1967; it quickly grew into a settlement with 350 residents and a vegetable garden. Phoenix House hosted festivals that sometimes attracted crowds of more than 10,000 people.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}} Phoenix House published a newsletter known as ''The Hart Beat'' and organized baseball games against other organizations such as City Island's and [[NBC]]'s teams.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|79}} In 1977, after regular ferry service to Hart Island ended, Phoenix House moved from the island to a building in Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/03/19/archives/hart-island-full-of-possibilitiesand-not-much-else-hart-island-a.html|title=Hart Island Full of Possibilities\u2010and Not Much Else|last=Goodwin|first=Michael|date=March 19, 1978|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108000035/https://www.nytimes.com/1978/03/19/archives/hart-island-full-of-possibilitiesand-not-much-else-hart-island-a.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/05/02/archives/phoenix-house-marks-10-years-with-a-new-home.html|title=Phoenix House Marks 10 Years With a New Home|date=May 2, 1977|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108000023/https://www.nytimes.com/1977/05/02/archives/phoenix-house-marks-10-years-with-a-new-home.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince then, proposals to re-inhabit the island have failed. In 1972, the city considered converting it into a residential resort but the plan abandoned.<ref name=\":4\" /> New York City mayor [[Ed Koch]] created a workhouse on the island for persons charged with misdemeanors in 1982 but not enough prisoners were sent there. Six years later, another proposal called for a homeless shelter and a workhouse to be built on Hart Island, but this plan was abandoned because of opposition from residents of City Island.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n=== Abandonment of structures and use as cemetery ===\n[[File:Hart Island, Bronx, 1966 (cropped).png|thumb|Map from 1966]]Originally, City Cemetery occupied {{convert|45|acre|ha}} on the northern and southern tips of Hart Island, while the center two-thirds of the island was habitable.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1985, sixteen bodies infected with [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] were buried at the southern tip of Hart Island, away from the rest of the corpses, because it was believed that the dead AIDS victims would contaminate the other corpses with the disease.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/03/nyregion/hart-island-aids-new-york.html|title=Dead of AIDS and Forgotten in Potter's Field|date=July 3, 2018|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703103050/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/03/nyregion/hart-island-aids-new-york.html|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The first pediatric AIDS victim to die in New York City is buried in the only single grave on Hart Island with a concrete marker that reads SC (special child) B1 (Baby 1) 1985.<ref name=\"hunt\" />{{rp|83}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" /> Since then, thousands of AIDS victims have been buried on Hart Island, but the precise number of AIDS victims buried on the island is unknown.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" />\n\nFrom 1991 to 1993, New York artist Melinda Hunt and photographer Joel Sternfeld photographed Hart Island for their book of the same name,<ref name=\"Chan 2007\">{{cite web|url=//cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|title=Searching for Names on an Island of Graves|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 26, 2007|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924032526/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|archive-date=September 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which was published in 1998.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Grundberg 1998\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/books/photography.html|title=Photography|last=Grundberg|first=Andy|date=December 6, 1998|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114210637/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/books/photography.html|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hunt subsequently founded the [[Hart Island (Bronx)#The Hart Island Project|Hart Island Project]] organization in 1994 to help the families and friends of those buried on Hart Island.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Owen 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9bzx85/a-virtual-grave-for-new-york-citys-forgotten-dead-219|title=The Isolated Island Where New York's Unknown and Unclaimed Are Buried|last=Owen|first=Tess A.|date=February 20, 2015|work=Vice|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023057/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9bzx85/a-virtual-grave-for-new-york-citys-forgotten-dead-219|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another media work, the 2018 documentary ''One Million American Dreams'', documents the history of Hart Island and delves briefly into the lives of various individuals buried there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/movies/one-million-american-dreams-review.html|title='One Million American Dreams' Review: Stories From New York's Potter's Field|last=Kenny|first=Glenn|date=February 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403112043/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/movies/one-million-american-dreams-review.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|access-date=May 19, 2019|8=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/one-million-american-dreams-1184286|title='One Million American Dreams': Film Review|last=Scheck|first=Frank|date=February 8, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is a section of old wooden houses and masonry institutional structures dating back to the late 19th and early 20th centuries that have fallen into disrepair. Military barracks from the Civil War period were used prior to the construction of workhouse and hospital facilities.<ref name=\"kilgannon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/17/nyregion/on-hart-island-new-yorks-potters-field.html?pagewanted=all|title=Visiting the Island of the Dead. A Rare Visit to New York's Potter's Field on Hart Island|first=Corey|last=Kilgannon|date=November 15, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=November 17, 2013|quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118031450/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/17/nyregion/on-hart-island-new-yorks-potters-field.html?pagewanted=all|archive-date=November 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In the late 2010s, the Hart Island Project and City Island Historical Society started petitioning for Hart Island to be listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2018/18/18-hartisland-2018-05-04-bx.html|title=A bone of contention/Erosion exposes human remains on Hart Island|first=Patrick|last=Rocchio|date=May 4, 2018|work=Bronx Times|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155948/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2018/18/18-hartisland-2018-05-04-bx.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]] labeled the island a \"site of historical significance\" in 2016, given that Hart Island met three of the four criteria for being listed on the NRHP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2016/43/43-hartisland-2016-10-21-bx.html|title='Hart Island Historic District' recognized by New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation|first=Patrick|last=Rocchio|date=October 21, 2016|work=Bronx Times|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155948/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2016/43/43-hartisland-2016-10-21-bx.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe island was significantly affected by [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, and some of the shoreline was eroded, which exposed many of the skeletons buried on the island.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://daily.jstor.org/burying-nycs-forgotten-dead-at-hart-island/|title=Burying NYC's Forgotten Dead at Hart Island|last=Lovejoy|first=Bess|date=May 22, 2018|publisher=JSTOR Daily|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162103/https://daily.jstor.org/burying-nycs-forgotten-dead-at-hart-island/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/02/bones-emerge-on-hart-island-where-inmates-bury-new-york-paupers-396123|title=Bones emerge on Hart Island, where inmates bury New York paupers|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|date=May 2, 2018|work=Politico|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162109/https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/02/bones-emerge-on-hart-island-where-inmates-bury-new-york-paupers-396123|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the city announced a restoration of the shoreline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hart-island-cemetery-erosion-human-bones-new-york-city/|title=Erosion at New York's Hart Island graveyard unearths human bones|date=April 25, 2018|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162101/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hart-island-cemetery-erosion-human-bones-new-york-city/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal government gave $13.2 million toward the shoreline project in 2015, but the work was delayed for several years. The start of restoration was initially slated for 2020, but in August 2019, the city announced that shoreline work would begin the following month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-to-start-cleanup-of-cemetery-damaged-in-superstorm-sandy-11564833600|title=New York City to Start Cleanup of Cemetery Damaged in Superstorm Sandy|last=Riski|first=Tess|date=August 3, 2019|website=Wall Street Journal|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826041108/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-to-start-cleanup-of-cemetery-damaged-in-superstorm-sandy-11564833600|archive-date=August 26, 2019|access-date=August 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That December, control of the island passed to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]].<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-hart-island-access-access-expanded-20191204-g6ieajiayvb23meh5u4ynbcma4-story.html|title=De Blasio signs law expanding ferry service access to Hart Island burial ground|last=Sanders|first=Anna|date=December 4, 2019|website=New York Daily News|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/hart-island-mayor-bill-de-blasio-1.39228959|title=Hart Island, NYC's 'potter's field' now a public park|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|date=December 4, 2019|website=Newsday|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/12/04/hart-island-transferred-to-parks-department/|title=Hart Island Transferred To Parks Department As Part Of Plan To Improve Access|date=December 4, 2019|website=CBS New York \u2013 Breaking News, Sports, Weather, Traffic And The Best of NY|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cemetery ==\nHart Island contains New York City's {{convert|131|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[potter's field]], or public cemetery. The potter's field is variously described as the largest tax-funded cemetery in the United States,<ref name=\"Public Radio International\">{{cite web |first=Alina |last=Simone | title=Is your family member buried on Hart Island, off the coast of New York? Sorry, you can't visit | work=Public Radio International | date=February 17, 2015 | url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2015-02-17/uncovering-lost-names-and-stories-people-buried-new-yorks-hart-island-cemetary | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021021/https://www.pri.org/stories/2015-02-17/uncovering-lost-names-and-stories-people-buried-new-yorks-hart-island-cemetary | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> the largest-such in the world,<ref name=\"Owen 2015\"/><ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\">{{cite web | title=This tiny New York island is actually the world's largest mass burial site |first=Soo |last=Kim | work=The Telegraph | date=October 23, 2017 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/united-states/new-york/articles/hart-island-cemetery-biggest-us-burial-site/ | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020000/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/united-states/new-york/articles/hart-island-cemetery-biggest-us-burial-site/ | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> and one of the largest mass graves in the United States.<ref name=\"Verrill 2016\">{{cite web | last=Verrill | first=Courtney | title=Over 1 million unclaimed bodies are buried on a little-known island in New York City \u2013 here's the story behind the massive graveyard | work=Business Insider | date=June 29, 2016 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/story-of-potters-field-on-hart-island-2016-6 | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021022/https://www.businessinsider.com/story-of-potters-field-on-hart-island-2016-6 | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Segar | first=Mike | title=Mass graves in the heart of New York | work=The Wider Image | date=June 27, 2016 | url=https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/mass-graves-in-the-heart-of-new-york | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021022/https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/mass-graves-in-the-heart-of-new-york | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> More than one million dead are buried on the island, though since the 2000s, the burial rate has declined to fewer than 1,500 a year.<ref name=\"hunt\" /><ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/><ref name=\"Verrill 2016\"/><ref name=\"FExits\">{{cite book | last=Largo | first=Michael | title=Final exits : the illustrated encyclopedia of how we die | publisher=Harper | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-06-081741-1 | oclc=64592196 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/finalexitsillust00larg_0/page/407 407\u2013408] | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/finalexitsillust00larg_0/page/407 }}</ref> One-third of annual burials are infants and stillborn babies, which has been reduced from a proportion of one-half since the [[Children's Health Insurance Program]] began to cover all pregnant women in New York State in 1997.<ref name=\"FExits\"/> According to a 2006 ''New York Times'' article, there had been 1,419 burials at the potter's field during the previous year: of these, 826 were adults, 546 were infants and stillborn babies, and 47 were dismembered body parts.<ref name=\"nyt1\" />\n\n=== Burials ===\nThe dead are buried in trenches. Babies are placed in coffins, which are stacked in groups of 1,000, measuring five coffins deep and usually in twenty rows.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> Adults are placed in larger pine boxes placed according to size, and are stacked in sections of 150, measuring three coffins deep in two rows.<ref name=\"hunt\" /><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref name=\"News 12 The Bronx 2017\">{{cite web | title=News 12 gets rare look at Hart Island, Potter's Field | work=News 12 The Bronx | date=May 11, 2017 | url=http://bronx.news12.com/story/35407858/news-12-gets-rare-look-at-hart-island-potters-field | access-date=April 3, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403124611/http://bronx.news12.com/story/35407858/news-12-gets-rare-look-at-hart-island-potters-field | archive-date=April 3, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> There are seven sizes of coffins, which range from {{Convert|1|to|7|ft|abbr=|m}} long.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/14/archives/about-new-york-last-ride-to-harts-island.html|title=About New York|last=Ferretti|first=Fred|date=August 14, 1974|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232517/https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/14/archives/about-new-york-last-ride-to-harts-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Each box is labeled with an identification number, the person's age, ethnicity, and the place where the body was found, if applicable.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Trebay|first=Guy|date=1992|title=The Last Place|journal=[[Grand Street (magazine)|Grand Street]]|language=en|issue=42|pages=118\u2013131|doi=10.2307/25007564|jstor=25007564}}</ref> Inmates from the [[Rikers Island]] jail are paid $0.50 per hour to bury bodies on Hart Island.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe bodies of adults are frequently disinterred when families are able to locate their relatives through DNA, photographs and fingerprints kept on file at the Office of the Medical Examiner.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> There were an average of 72 disinterments per year from 2007 to 2009. As a result, the adults' coffins are staggered to expedite removal.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}} Children, mostly infants, are rarely disinterred.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> Regulations stipulate that the coffins generally must remain untouched for 25 years, except in cases of disinterment.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}}\n\nApproximately half of the burials are of children under five who are identified and died in New York City's hospitals, where the mothers signed papers authorizing a \"City Burial.\" The mothers were generally unaware of what the phrase meant. Many other interred have families who live abroad or out of state and whose relatives search extensively; these searches are made more difficult because burial records are currently kept within the prison system. An investigation into the handling of the infant burials was opened in response to a criminal complaint made to the New York State Attorney General's Office in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Deutzman|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/investigative/090523_Hart_Island_Babies|title=Hart Island Babies|work=Fox 5 NY|publisher=[[WNYW]]; [[Fox Television]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605211222/http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/investigative/090523_Hart_Island_Babies|archivedate=June 5, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBurial records on microfilm at the Municipal Archives indicate that until 1913, burials of unknowns were in single plots, and identified adults and children were buried in mass graves.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/05/15/nyregion/new-york-mass-graves-hart-island.html|title=Unearthing the Secrets of New York's Mass Graves|date=May 15, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515213259/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/05/15/nyregion/new-york-mass-graves-hart-island.html|archive-date=May 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1874/02/01/archives/local-miscellany-where-the-unknown-dead-rest.html|title=Where the Unknown Dead Rest|date=February 1, 1874|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|page=8|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623033021/https://www.nytimes.com/1874/02/01/archives/local-miscellany-where-the-unknown-dead-rest.html|archive-date=June 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1913, the trenches became separate to facilitate the more frequent disinterment of adults. The potter's field is also used to dispose of amputated body parts, which are placed in boxes labeled \"limbs\". Ceremonies have not been conducted at the burial site since the 1950s.<ref name=\"hunt\" />{{rp|83}} In the past, burial trenches were re-used after 25\u201350 years, allowing for sufficient decomposition of the remains. Since then, however, historic buildings have been demolished to make room for new burials.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|139}} Because of the number of weekly interments made at the potter's field at the expense of taxpayers, these mass burials are straightforward and are conducted by [[Rikers Island]] inmates, who stack the coffins in two rows, three high and 25 across, and each plot is marked with a concrete marker. A tall, white, peace monument was erected by New York City prison inmates at the top of a hill that was known as \"Cemetery Hill\" following World War II<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/09/09/archives/prisoners-build-memorial-to-dead-inmates-of-city-penitentiary-on.html|title=Prisoners Build Memorial To Dead; Inmates of City Penitentiary on Hart Island Erecting Potter's Field Monument|date=September 9, 1948|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107234815/https://www.nytimes.com/1948/09/09/archives/prisoners-build-memorial-to-dead-inmates-of-city-penitentiary-on.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was dedicated in October 1948.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/10/11/archives/city-shaft-honors-unclaimed-dead-30foot-monument-dedicated-on-hart.html|title=City Shaft Honors Unclaimed Dead; 30-Foot Monument Dedicated On Hart Island to Memory of 450,000 in Potter's Field|date=October 11, 1948|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107234825/https://www.nytimes.com/1948/10/11/archives/city-shaft-honors-unclaimed-dead-30foot-monument-dedicated-on-hart.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Disease victims' burials====\nDuring the 1980s, those who had died from [[AIDS]] were the only people to be buried in separate graves. The first AIDS victims' bodies were delivered in body bags and buried by inmate workers wearing protective jumpsuits. When it was later discovered that the corpses could not spread HIV, the city started burying AIDS victims in the mass graves.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" /> In 2008, the island was selected as a site for mass burials during a particularly extreme flu pandemic, available for up to 20,000 bodies.<ref name=\"WTSP-20200402\">{{Cite news|last=Greenstein|first=Dale |url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/new-york-city-coronavirus-mass-graves-hart-island/67-df417271-adbd-4715-8588-f3e80f556473 |title=Prisoners are digging mass graves in New York City|date=April 2, 2020|work=|access-date=April 9, 2020 |url-status=live|publisher=WTSP}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City]], Hart Island was designated as the temporary burial site for victims of [[COVID-19]] if deaths overwhelmed the capacity of mortuaries; this option was chosen in lieu of using city parks for such a purpose.<ref name=\"NYDN-20200406\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-new-city-parks-burial-20200406-4vxvowhtk5f45brouqd32s7iau-story.html |title= NYC considers temporary burials on Hart Island amid mounting coronavirus death toll |first= Chris|last=Sommerfeldt |first2=Shant|last2=Shahrigian |date= April 6, 2020 |newspaper= New York Daily News |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC-20200406\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/06/new-york-city-weighs-temporary-burials-as-coronavirus-deaths-overwhelm-mortuary-system.html |title= New York City may have to bury coronavirus victims on public lands as deaths overwhelm mortuaries |first= William |last=Feuer |first2=Noah |last2=Higgins-Dunn |date= April 6, 2020 |publisher= CNBC }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/drone-video-shows-inmates-digging-mass-burial-graves-on-new-york-s-hart-island-1.4888134|title=Drone video shows inmates digging mass burial graves on New York's Hart Island|first=Jackie|last=Vandinther|date=April 8, 2020|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Deaths at home within the city had increased significantly, though the corpses were not tested for COVID-19.<ref name=gothamist1>{{Cite web  |access-date=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408012523/https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live |title=Staggering Surge Of NYers Dying In Their Homes Suggests City Is Undercounting Coronavirus Fatalities |first=Gwynne |last=Hogan |url=https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |website=Gothamist |language=en |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Preparations for mass graves began at the end of March 2020.<ref name=\"WTSP-20200402\" /> On April 9, 2020, [[Reuters]] reported that private contractors were hired to replace inmate labor for mass grave burials,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Lucas |title=New York City hires laborers to bury dead in Hart Island potter's field amid coronavirus surge |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-hart-island/new-york-city-hires-laborers-to-bury-dead-in-hart-island-potters-field-amid-coronavirus-surge-idUSL2N2BX1O5 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Reuters |date=April 9, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and burials began.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York digging mass graves amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52241221 |website=BBC News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=gothamist2>{{cite web |title=Mass Burials On Hart Island Increase Fivefold As COVID-19 Death Toll Skyrockets |first=Christopher |last=Robbins|first2=Sydney|last2=Pereira|first3=Gwynne|last=Hogan|url=https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |website=Gothamist |language=en |date=April 9, 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200410110654/https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |archivedate=April 10, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Records ===\nMany burial records were destroyed by arson in late July 1977. Remaining records of burials before 1977 were transferred to the [[New York City Municipal Archives|Municipal Archives]] in Manhattan; while records after that date are still kept in handwritten ledgers, these are now transcribed into a digital database that is partially available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doc/downloads/pdf/Hart_Island%20_FAQs%202017.07.25.pdf|title=FAQs: Hart Island Burials; What is Hart Island?|date=July 25, 2017|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201024159/https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doc/downloads/pdf/Hart_Island%20_FAQs%202017.07.25.pdf|archive-date=December 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=//cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/online-searching-for-those-buried-and-often-forgotten-on-hart-island/|title=City Introduces Online Database for Its Potter's Field|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=April 11, 2013|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922101540/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/online-searching-for-those-buried-and-often-forgotten-on-hart-island/|archive-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOI) request for 50,000 burial records was granted to the Hart Island Project in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/24/nyregion/24hart.html|title=Finding Names for Hart Island's Forgotten|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=March 24, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314064418/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/24/nyregion/24hart.html|archive-date=March 14, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|title=Searching for Names on an Island of Graves|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 26, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|authorlink=Sewell Chan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922143000/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|archive-date=September 22, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><!--The 1,403 pages provided by the Department of Correction contain lists of all burials from 1985 to 2007. A second Freedom of Information request for records from September 1, 1977, to December 31, 1984, was submitted to the Department of Correction on June 2, 2008, and New York City has located 502 pages from that period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartisland.net/|title=About \u2013 Home Page|date=|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=April 11, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517080156/http://hartisland.net/|archive-date=May 17, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>--> A lawsuit concerning \"place of death\" information redacted from the Hart Island burial records was filed against New York City in July 2008 and was settled out of court in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web | last=Duke | first=Nathan | title=Poets honor Potter's Field dead in Flushing | work=Queens Courier | date=May 19, 2010 | url=https://qns.com/story/2010/05/19/poets-honor-potters-field-dead-in-flushing/ | access-date=April 17, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417030615/https://qns.com/story/2010/05/19/poets-honor-potters-field-dead-in-flushing/ | archive-date=April 17, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Notable people buried ===\nThose interred on Hart Island are not necessarily homeless or indigent. Many of the dead either had families who could not afford the expenses of private funerals or were not claimed by relatives within a month of death. Notable burials include the playwright, film screenwriter, and director [[Leo Birinski]], who died alone and in poverty, was buried there in 1951.<ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/> The American novelist [[Dawn Powell]] was buried on Hart Island in 1970, five years after her death, when the executor of her estate refused to reclaim her remains after being used for medical studies. Academy Award winner [[Bobby Driscoll]], who was found dead in 1968 in an [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] tenement, was buried on Hart Island because his remains could not be identified in a timely fashion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themorningnews.org/article/hart-island|title=Hart Island|first=Clay|last=Risen|date=October 10, 2002|work=The Morning News|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612041811/http://www.themorningnews.org/archives/new_york_new_york/hart_island.php|archive-date=June 12, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[T-Bone Slim]], the [[labor activist]], [[songwriter]], and [[Industrial Workers of the World|wobbly]], was buried on Hart Island after his body was found floating in the [[Hudson River]].<ref name=\"Writings 1993\">{{cite book | editor-last=Rosemont |editor-first=Franklin | title=Juice is stranger than friction : selected writings of t-bone slim | publisher=Charles H. Kerr| year=1985 | isbn=978-0-88286-070-1 | oclc=1001785717 }}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|City Island and Hart Island, Bronx NY.jpg|600px|Aerial view showing Hart Island (lower right) and [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]] (left) in 2010}}\n\n==Public engagement==\n==={{anchor|The Hart Island Project}}Hart Island Project===\n\nFounded by New York artist Melinda Hunt in 1994,<ref name=\"Owen 2015\"/>{{efn|According to the project's website, it was not [[incorporation (business)|incorporated]] as a charity until 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=Mission |publisher=The Hart Island Project | url=https://www.hartisland.net/mission | access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>}} the Hart Island Project is a [[nonprofit organization]] devoted to improving access to the island and its burial data.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Owen 2015\" /> The organization helps families obtain copies of public burial records; arranges visits to grave sites; and operates a website to help people find relatives interred on the island.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Yorker helps people track down loved ones who died unknown |first=Leigh |last=Remizowski |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/03/10/us/new-york-hart-island/ |publisher=CNN |date=March 11, 2012 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820040301/http://www.cnn.com/2012/03/10/us/new-york-hart-island |archive-date=August 20, 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Melinda Hunt Follows NYC's Lonely Dead To Hart Island |first=Alex |last=Silverman |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/11/14/melinda-hunt-follows-nycs-lonely-dead-to-hart-island/ |publisher=[[WCBS-TV]] |date=November 14, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413125433/http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/11/14/melinda-hunt-follows-nycs-lonely-dead-to-hart-island/ |archive-date=April 13, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Hansi Lo|last=Wang|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/02/04/465588689/relatives-of-deceased-push-for-more-access-to-n-y-c-potter-s-field|title=Relatives Of Deceased Push For More Access To NYC Potter's Field|date=February 4, 2016|publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505120945/http://www.npr.org/2016/02/04/465588689/relatives-of-deceased-push-for-more-access-to-n-y-c-potter-s-field|archive-date=May 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Historian [[Thomas Laqueur]] writes:\n\n{{quote|[[Woody Guthrie]]'s song about the unnamed Mexican migrant dead has had a long resonant history. Hunt, in an emotionally related gesture, has researched, for years, in order to publish the names of as many as 850,000 paupers who lie in 101 acres of Hart Island where the city buries its anonymous dead.<ref>{{cite book | last=Laqueur | first=Thomas | title=The Work of the Dead: A Cultural History of Mortal Remains |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHFqCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA419 | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-0-691-15778-8 | oclc=908084082 | page=419}}</ref>}}\n\nSince 2009, the city has given burial records for the island to the Hart Island Project. In turn, the organization maintains an online database of burial records from 1980 onward.<ref name=\"WSJ Burials 2019\">{{cite web | last=Riski | first=Tess | title=New York City Has Been Releasing Burial Records of Fetal Remains\u2014and Names of Women Linked to Them | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=August 21, 2019 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-has-been-releasing-burial-records-of-fetal-remainsand-names-of-women-linked-to-them-11566420004 | access-date=August 26, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825223818/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-has-been-releasing-burial-records-of-fetal-remainsand-names-of-women-linked-to-them-11566420004 | archive-date=August 25, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The project has led to reforms of access to Hart Island such as opening the island monthly to everyone<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/cityrecord/CITY%20COUNCIL%20SUPPLEMENTS/NEW%20SUPPLEMENTS%20RECIEVED%20ON%20MARCH%205,%202014%20by%20email/FINAL%2011x17%20121013-revised.pdf|title=Supplement to the City Record the Council \u2014 Stated Meeting of Tuesday, December 10, 2013|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|date=December 10, 2013|access-date=March 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230033744/http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/cityrecord/CITY%20COUNCIL%20SUPPLEMENTS/NEW%20SUPPLEMENTS%20RECIEVED%20ON%20MARCH%205,%202014%20by%20email/FINAL%2011x17%20121013-revised.pdf|archive-date=December 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and legislation that requires the Department of Correction to publish burial records online.<ref name=\"DNAInfo-LaunchesDatabase-2013\">{{cite web | last=Zimmer | first=Amy | title=City Launches Online Database for Massive Hart Island Potter's Field | website=DNAinfo New York | date=April 11, 2013 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130411/city-island/city-launches-online-database-for-massive-hart-island-potters-field |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109181602/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130411/city-island/city-launches-online-database-for-massive-hart-island-potters-field|archivedate=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=April 29, 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe Hart Island Project has digitally mapped grave trenches using [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS) data. In 2014, an interactive map with GPS burial data and storytelling software \"clocks of anonymity\" was released as the \"Traveling Cloud Museum\", which collects publicly submitted stories of those who are listed in the burial records.<ref name=\"Public Radio International\"/> Traveling Cloud Museum was updated in 2018 to include a map created with [[GeoTIFF]] images collected by a drone. The map displays nearly 69,000 intact burials and allows people who knew the deceased to add stories, photographs, epitaphs, songs and videos linked to a personal profile, as well as identify AIDS victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlasofthefuture.org/project/traveling-cloud-museum/|title=Traveling Cloud Museum\u2014Atlas of the Future|publisher=Atlas of the Future|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515115127/http://atlasofthefuture.org/project/traveling-cloud-museum/|archive-date=May 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Making Hart Island's graves easier to visit | work=Fox 5 NY | publisher=[[WNYW]]; [[Fox Television]] | date=May 8, 2018 | url=http://www.fox5ny.com/news/hart-island-graves-accessible | first=Liz | last=Dahlem | access-date=August 23, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823220808/http://www.fox5ny.com/news/hart-island-graves-accessible | archive-date=August 23, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Westchester Community College]] hosted an art exhibition of people whose graves were located through the Hart Island Project with Hunt's help.<ref>{{cite news |title=Giving Voice to the Legions Buried in a Potter's Field |first=Susan |last=Hodara |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/01/nyregion/the-hart-island-project-at-westchester-community-college-in-peekskill.html |newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 |date=December 30, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707101100/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/01/nyregion/the-hart-island-project-at-westchester-community-college-in-peekskill.html |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Art of the Forgotten |first=Jay |last=Blotcher |url=http://www.chronogram.com/hudsonvalley/the-art-of-the-forgotten/Content?oid=2175700 |date=November 30, 2011 |work=Chronogram Magazine |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119112924/http://www.chronogram.com/hudsonvalley/the-art-of-the-forgotten/Content?oid=2175700 |archive-date=November 19, 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Peekskill artist helps families find those buried at Hart Island |first=Marcela |last=Rojas |url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20111112/NEWS01/111120340/Peekskill-artist-helps-families-find-those-buried-Hart-Island |newspaper=The Journal News |date=November 12, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707150030/http://www.lohud.com/article/20111112/NEWS01/111120340/Peekskill-artist-helps-families-find-those-buried-Hart-Island |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The Hart Island Project also collaborated with British landscape architects Ann Sharrock and Ian Fisher to present a landscape strategy to the New York City Council and the Parks Department.<ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/> Sharrock introduced the concept that Hart Island is a natural burial facility and outlined a growing interest in [[green burial]]s in urban settings.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n=== Legislation ===\nOn October 28, 2011, the New York City Council Committee on Fire and Criminal Justice held a hearing titled \"Oversight: Examining the Operation of Potter's Field by the N.Y.C., Department of Correction on Hart Island\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/oct/28/council-looking-city-cemetery/|title=Council Looking Into City Cemetery|last=Hennelly|first=Bob|date=October 28, 2011|publisher=[[WNYC]]|access-date=August 25, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427021944/http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/oct/28/council-looking-city-cemetery/|archivedate=April 27, 2012|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/30/hart-island_n_1066391.html|title=Hart Island Cemetery: City Council Reviews Operations Of New York's Potter's Field (VIDEO)|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=October 30, 2011|work=Huffington Post|access-date=November 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104014101/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/30/hart-island_n_1066391.html|archive-date=November 4, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Legislation passed in 2013 requires the Department of Correction to make two sets of documents available on the Internet: a database of burials and a visitation policy.<ref name=\"WSJ Burials 2019\"/><ref>*{{cite web | title=Requiring the Dept of Correction to make its electronic database of people buried at Hart\u2019s Island, since 1977, available on its website |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]] | url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1082204&GUID=F673F220-DC2A-44D7-B5E3-0D1F61FB9F9A&Options=&Search= |date=December 17, 2013 | access-date=August 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=Requiring the Dept of Correction to put its Hart's Island visitation policy in writing, post it on its website, and make it available to anyone who requests a copy |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]] | url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1082205&GUID=33965E29-A7DE-4192-BDED-5EDF6E0200E9&Options=&Search= |date=December 17, 2013 | access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> In April 2013, the Department of Correction published an online database of burials on the island.<ref name=\"DNAInfo-LaunchesDatabase-2013\" /> The database contains data about all persons buried on the island since 1977 and is composed of 66,000 entries.<ref name=\"Owen 2015\" /><ref name=\"kilgannon\" />\n\n==== Transfer to Parks Department ====\nA bill to transfer jurisdiction to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] was introduced on April 30, 2012.<ref name=\"NYC.gov ferry law\">{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1681005&GUID=D615F227-5431-4FF0-9AEE-92F704CDD16E&Options=ID%7CText%7C&Search=Hart+Island|date=March 12, 2014|title=A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to ferry service to Hart's Island|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192122/http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1681005&GUID=D615F227-5431-4FF0-9AEE-92F704CDD16E&Options=ID%7CText%7C&Search=Hart+Island|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2014/46/46-hart-2014-11-14-bx_2014_46.html|title=City Island Civic Association, Chamber visit Hart Island and take tour|last=Rocchio|first=Patrick|date=November 14, 2014|work=Bronx Times|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705070031/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2014/46/46-hart-2014-11-14-bx_2014_46.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Hart Island Project testified in favor of this bill on September 27, 2012, but the bill was not passed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2012/09/hart-island/|title=An Open Hart Island: Off the Coast of the Bronx Lie 850,000 Lost Souls\u2014the City Council Hopes to Pay Its Respects|last=Velsey|first=Kim|date=September 28, 2012|newspaper=New York Observer|access-date=August 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701022844/http://observer.com/2012/09/hart-island/|archive-date=July 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe bill was reintroduced in March 2014,<ref name=\":8\"/> and Bill 0134 had a public hearing on January 20, 2016.<ref name=\":8\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/20/city-discusses-turning-hart-island-into-a-park.html|title=NYC Discusses Turning Hart Island Into a Park|work=Al Jazeera America|date=January 20, 2016|first=Lisa|last=De Bode|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413073501/http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/20/city-discusses-turning-hart-island-into-a-park.html|archive-date=April 13, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amny.com/news/nyc-council-hears-plan-to-turn-island-of-forgotten-into-park-1.11346723|title=NYC Council hears plan to turn island of forgotten into park |first=Maria |last=Alvarez|date=January 20, 2016|work=am New York|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122163306/http://www.amny.com/news/nyc-council-hears-plan-to-turn-island-of-forgotten-into-park-1.11346723|archive-date=January 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/01/20/hart_island_doc.php|title=Who Should Control Hart Island, NYC's \"Prison For The Dead\"?|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 20, 2016|first=Emma|last=Whitford|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503162012/http://gothamist.com/2016/01/20/hart_island_doc.php|archivedate=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=April 29, 2016|df=}}</ref> The bill ultimately failed because neither the Parks Department nor the Department of Correction supported the move. The Parks Department stated that the operation of an active cemetery was outside its purview while the Department of Correction preferred that another city agency take control of Hart Island.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/21/nyregion/officials-object-to-plan-to-turn-potters-field-over-to-parks-dept.html|title=Officials Object to Plan to Turn Hart Island Burial Site Over to Parks Dept.|last=Bernstein|first=Nina|date=January 20, 2016|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403180525/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/21/nyregion/officials-object-to-plan-to-turn-potters-field-over-to-parks-dept.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, City Council member [[Ydanis Rodr\u00edguez]] and three colleagues re-introduced the bill a second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3498510&GUID=DB8FADA8-30C5-4731-8B71-875D9A65C1FA|title=Transfer of jurisdiction over Hart Island from the DOC to the dept of parks and recreation|date=May 9, 2018|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403174758/https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3498510&GUID=DB8FADA8-30C5-4731-8B71-875D9A65C1FA|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In supporting the bill, Rodriguez stated that he wanted relatives of Hart Island's deceased to be able to access their loved ones' graves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/09/council-members-take-up-the-cause-of-the-hart-island-bereaved-408468|title=Council members take up the cause of the Hart Island bereaved|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|date=May 9, 2018|work=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162102/https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/09/council-members-take-up-the-cause-of-the-hart-island-bereaved-408468|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Anthony M.|last=DeStefano|url=https://www.amny.com/news/hart-island-erosion-bones-1.18441360|title=Bill would shift control of Hart Island to NYC Parks|date=May 9, 2018|work=am New York|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162059/https://www.amny.com/news/hart-island-erosion-bones-1.18441360|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill was passed in the New York City Council in November 2019, with most council members voting in favor of transferring jurisdiction to the Parks Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-hart-island-access-20191115-2dv2khnlxzh2nbm4vmqvzbqlgm-story.html|title=NYC Council passes laws aimed at making Hart Island more accessible|last=Shahrigian|first=Shant|date=November 14, 2019|website=New York Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/11/13/hart-island-cemetery-nyc-parks-department-city-council/|title=Hart Island, Final Resting Place Of 1 Million, On Verge Of Becoming NYC Parks Property|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2019|website=CBS News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> The following month, mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] signed the legislation, as well as three other bills, including one that would allow the ferry service to be operated by the [[New York City Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/12/04/hart-island-transferred-to-parks-department/|title=Hart Island Transferred To Parks Department As Part Of Plan To Improve Access|date=December 4, 2019|publisher=CBS New York|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/hart-island-mayor-bill-de-blasio-1.39228959|title=De Blasio signs law making Hart Island, NYC's potter's field, a public park|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|website=Newsday|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\n[[File:Pier and Ferry to Hart Island.JPG|thumb|alt=A ferry pier jutting into the water from the left-hand side of the image|Hart Island ferry pier]]\nThe only access to Hart Island is by ferryboat.<ref name=\":4\" /> Hart Island and the pier on Fordham Street on City Island are restricted areas under the jurisdiction of the New York City Department of Correction. Family members who wish to visit the island must request a visit ahead of time with the Department of Correction. New York City's government offers no provisions for individuals who want to visit Hart Island without contacting the prison system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hartisland.net/contact|title=Contact Information|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402041634/https://www.hartisland.net/contact|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCDOC\">{{cite web | title=Hart Island | website=nyc.gov | publisher=New York City Department of Correction | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doc/about/hart-island.page | access-date=September 3, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807205315/https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doc/about/hart-island.page | archive-date=August 7, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The city government allows family members to visit the island and leave mementos at grave sites, and maintains an online and telephone system for family members to schedule grave site visits.<ref name=\"NYCLU\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyclu.org/files/releases/LuserovCityofNY_settlement_07082015.pdf|title=Stipulation and Order of Settlement: Rosaria Cortes Lusero, Marie Cruz Garcia, and Michelle Caner, On Behalf of Themselves and All Others Similarly Situated, Plaintiffs, Against the City Of New York, Defendant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201041051/http://www.nyclu.org/files/releases/LuserovCityofNY_settlement_07082015.pdf|archivedate=December 1, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=July 29, 2015|df=}}</ref> Other members of the public are permitted to visit by prior appointment only.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hartisland.net/faq|title=FAQ|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705033007/https://www.hartisland.net/faq|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly operated a [[24/7 service|24/7]] ferry service between City and Hart Islands, which ran every forty-five minutes during the day and less frequently at night.<ref name=\":5\" /> The ferries also transported corpses. By the 1960s, two ferryboats were used for the Hart Island ferry service; the ''Michael Cosgrove'' (built 1961) and the ''Fordham'' (in service 1922\u20131982).<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/timeline/html/hartline.html|title=Hart Island Timeline|last=|first=|date=|publisher=New York Correction History Society|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225202006/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/timeline/html/hartline.html|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The service was extremely expensive to operate; in 1967, about 1,500 people per month used the service and the city spent $300,000 per year to keep it running.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/01/31/archives/city-may-end-hart-island-ferry-1500-a-month-use-the-service-to.html|title=City May End Hart Island Ferry; 1,500 a Month Use the Service to Potter's Field Running the 2 Boats Costs More Than $300,000 a Year|last=Knowles|first=Clayton|date=January 31, 1967|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107232907/https://www.nytimes.com/1967/01/31/archives/city-may-end-hart-island-ferry-1500-a-month-use-the-service-to.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> By 1977, the city had discontinued frequent ferry service and provided seven trips a day.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Department of Correction offered one guided tour of the island in 2000.<ref>{{cite web| title=Hart Island| publisher=New York Correction History Society| date=June 15, 2000| url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/harling/| access-date=August 13, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924032515/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/harling/| archive-date=September 24, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Following the signing of a bill in 2019, the ferry was to be operated at a higher frequency by the New York City Department of Transportation.<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\" /><!-- and a few other visits were offered to members of the [[City Island Civics Association]] and [[Bronx Community Board 10]] in 2014.-->\n\nThe process of visiting the island has been improved due to efforts by the Hart Island Project and the [[New York Civil Liberties Union]].<ref name=\"NYCLU\"/> An [[Ecumenism|ecumenical]] group named the Interfaith Friends of Potter's Field and another organization called Picture the Homeless has also advocated for making the island more accessible.<ref name=\":1\"/>{{rp|144}} In July 2015, the Department of Correction instituted a new policy, wherein up to five family members and their guests were allowed to visit grave sites on one weekend per month.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/nyregion/new-york-city-to-allow-visits-to-grave-sites-on-hart-island.html|title=New York City to Allow Relatives to Visit Grave Sites at Potter's Field|last=Kilgannon|first=Corey|date=July 9, 2015|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027064823/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/nyregion/new-york-city-to-allow-visits-to-grave-sites-on-hart-island.html|archive-date=October 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The first visit took place on July 19, 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|first=Nina|last=Bernstein|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/nyregion/mourners-make-first-visit-to-new-yorks-potters-field.html|title=Mourners Make First Visit to New York's Potter's Field|date=July 20, 2015|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516144138/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/nyregion/mourners-make-first-visit-to-new-yorks-potters-field.html|archive-date=May 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Visits to individual graves, which take place twice a month, are restricted to individuals who had a close relationship with the deceased. Visits to Hart Island's gazebo, which occur once a month, are available to the general public.<ref name=\"NYCDOC\"/> The ferry leaves from a restricted dock on City Island. In 2017, the city government increased the maximum number of visitors per month from 50 to 70.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/24/hart_island_graves_access.php|first=Emma|last=Whitford|title=City Agrees To Increase Mourners' Access To Mass Graves On Hart Island|work=[[Gothamist]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126203703/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/24/hart_island_graves_access.php|date=January 24, 2017|archivedate=January 26, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=January 24, 2017|df=}}</ref> The Department of Correction has opposed further loosening of restrictions on accessing Hart Island; a ''The New York Times'' article quoted a Corrections official as saying: \"As long as D.O.C. runs the facility, we are going to run it with the D.O.C. mentality\".<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Davids' Island (New York)]]\n* [[Geography and environment of New York City]]\n* [[Postage stamps and postal history of the Confederate States#Prisoner of war prisons and camps]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://anglicanhistory.org/academic/kempton2006.pdf|title=In Essentials, Unity; In Non-Essentials, Liberty; and in All Things Charity: Historical Account of the Mission of the Diocese of New York of the Protestant Episcopal Church to the Institutions and the Potter's Field on Hart Island|first=Wayne|last=Kempton|publisher=[[Episcopal Diocese of New York]]|date=2006}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hart Island, Bronx}}\n* {{official|http://hartisland.net}}\n\n{{New York City Islands}}{{Protected areas of New York City}}\n[[Category:Islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Long Island Sound]]\n[[Category:American Civil War prison camps|Hart Island]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in New York City]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Mass graves]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Bronx]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Small island, part of the Pelham Islands, in the Bronx, New York}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Hart Island\n| image_name       = Hart Island, Bronx, 2012 (cropped).JPG\n| image_alt        = Aerial view of Hart Island\n| image_caption    = Aerial view of Hart Island, in 2012\n| image_size       = \n| image_map        = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-lat=40.735|frame-long=-73.975|zoom=9|type=point|coord={{coord|40.8525|-73.7700}}}}\n| map_alt          =  \n| map_size         =\n| map_caption      = Location in New York City\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_link =\n| nickname         =\n| location         = [[Long Island Sound]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|40|51|9|N|73|46|12|W|display=inline, title}}\n| archipelago      = [[Pelham Islands]]\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_acre         = 131.22     <!-- | area             = {{convert|131.22|acre|km2|abbr=on}} -->\n| length_mi        = 1.0\n| width_mi         = 0.33\n| highest_mount    =\n| elevation_ft     =\n| country          =\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[City]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[New York City]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Borough (New York City)|Borough]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = [[The Bronx|Bronx]]\n| population       =\n| population_as_of =\n| density_sqmi     =\n| ethnic_groups    =\n}}\n'''Hart Island''', sometimes referred to as '''Hart's Island''',{{efn|See, for instance:<ref name=\"hunter\"/><ref>{{cite fednyc}}</ref>}} is located at the western end of [[Long Island Sound]], in the northeast [[the Bronx|Bronx]], [[New York City]]. Measuring approximately {{convert|1|mi|km}} long by {{convert|0.33|mi|km|abbr=}} wide, Hart Island is part of the [[Pelham Islands]] archipelago, to the east of [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]].\n\nThe island's first public use was as a training ground for the [[United States Colored Troops]] in 1864. Since then, Hart Island has been the location of a [[American Civil War prison camps|Union Civil War prison camp]], a [[psychiatric institution]], a [[tuberculosis sanatorium]], a [[potter's field]] with mass burials, a homeless shelter, a boys' [[reformatory]], a jail, and a drug rehabilitation center. Several other structures, such as an amusement park, were planned for Hart Island but not built. During the [[Cold War (1953\u20131962)|Cold War]], [[Nike missile|Nike defense missiles]] were stationed on Hart Island. The island was intermittently used as a prison and a homeless shelter until 1967, and the last inhabited structures were abandoned in 1977. The island now serves as the city's potter's field, run by the [[New York City Department of Correction]] until 2019, when the [[New York City Council]] voted to transfer jurisdiction to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]].\n\nThe remains of more than one million people are buried on Hart Island, though since the first decade of the 21st century, there are fewer than 1,500 burials a year. Burials on Hart Island include individuals who were not claimed by their families or did not have private funerals; the homeless and the indigent; and mass burials of disease victims, including those who died from [[AIDS]] and [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. \n\nAccess to the island is restricted by the Department of Correction, which operates an infrequent ferryboat service and imposes strict visitation quotas. Burials are conducted by inmates at the [[Rikers Island]] jail. The Hart Island Project, a public charity founded by visual artist Melinda Hunt, has tried to improve access to the island and make burial records more easily available. Prior to 2019, several laws to transfer jurisdiction to the Parks Department had been proposed to ease public access to Hart Island.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThere are numerous theories about the possible origins for the island's name. In one, British [[Cartographers#18th century|cartographers]] named it \"Heart Island\" in 1775 due to its organ-like shape but the 'e' was dropped shortly after.<ref name=\"fascinates\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/27/nyregion/an-island-of-the-dead-fascinates-the-living.html|title=An Island Of the Dead Fascinates The Living|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=January 27, 2003|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111023538/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/27/nyregion/an-island-of-the-dead-fascinates-the-living.html|archive-date=November 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} A map drawn in 1777 and subsequent maps refer to the island as \"Hart Island\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} Other names given to the island during the late 18th century were \"Little Minneford Island\" and \"Spectacle Island\", the latter because the island's shape was thought to resemble [[Glasses|spectacles]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}\n\nAnother theory, based on the meaning of the English word \"[[Hart (deer)|hart]]\", which means \"stag\", is that the island was named when it was used as a game preserve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=11613|title=The Islands of Pelham Bay|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=November 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309172413/http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=11613|archive-date=March 9, 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> Another version holds that it was named in reference to deer that migrated from the mainland during periods when ice covered that part of Long Island Sound.<ref name=\"hunt\">{{cite book | last=Hunt | first=Melinda | title=Hart Island | publisher=Scalo | year=1998 | isbn=978-3-931141-90-5 | oclc=40373838 |first2=Joel |last2=Sternfeld }}</ref>{{rp|19}}<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zRjMPZW4heMC|title=The Other Islands of New York City: A History and Guide (Third Edition)|last=Seitz|first=Sharon|last2=Miller|first2=Stuart|year=2011|publisher=The Countryman Press|isbn=978-1-58157-886-7|location=|pages=138\u2013144|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|140}}\n\n== Geography ==\nHart Island is approximately {{convert|1|mi|km}} long by {{convert|0.33|mi|km|abbr=}} wide at its widest point. It lies about {{convert|0.33|mi|km}} off the eastern shore of City Island.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WeVTP3GyFH0C&pg=PA77|title=The Bronx, in Bits and Pieces|last=Twomey|first=Bill|publisher=Rooftop Publishing|year=2007|isbn=978-1-60008-062-3|location=|pages=74\u201379|access-date=}}</ref>{{Rp|75}}<ref name=\":4\" /> The island's area is disputed; according to some sources, it is {{Convert|101|acre|ha|abbr=}},<ref name=\"fascinates\" /><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/hart.html|title=Hart Island|publisher=New York Correction History Society|access-date=December 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009002256/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/hart.html|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> while others state that it is {{Convert|131|acre|ha|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2017/05/09/inside-the-mysteries-of-hart-island-in-the-bronx-the-cemetery-of-the-unknown/|title=Inside the mysteries of Hart Island in the Bronx, the cemetery of the unknown|first=Dan|last=Mannarino|date=May 9, 2017|publisher=[[WPIX]]|access-date=December 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101002846/https://pix11.com/2017/05/09/inside-the-mysteries-of-hart-island-in-the-bronx-the-cemetery-of-the-unknown/|archive-date=January 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-potters-idUSKCN0ZD2T7|title=New York allows rare glimpse of its potter's field cemetery|date=June 27, 2016|publisher=Reuters|access-date=December 31, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101002821/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-potters-idUSKCN0ZD2T7|archive-date=January 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hart Island is isolated from the rest of the city: there is no electricity and the only means of access is via ferryboat.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"News 12 The Bronx 2017\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:USCGS Chart number 361 (1884).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A nautical chart of the island from 1884|1884 Nautical Chart]]\n\n=== Early history ===\n\nBefore European colonization, Hart Island was occupied by the [[Siwanoy]] tribe of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]], who were indigenous to the area. In 1654, English physician [[Thomas Pell]] purchased the island from the Siwanoy as part of a {{Convert|9,166|acres|km2|adj=mid}} property.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}}<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|140}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Lustenberger |first=Anita A. |year=2000 |url=http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=64 |title=A Short Genealogy of Hart Island |publisher=[[New York Genealogical and Biographical Society]] |access-date=November 5, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007100410/http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=64 |archive-date=October 7, 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Pell died in 1669 and ownership passed to his nephew Sir John Pell, the son of British mathematician [[John Pell]]. The island remained in the Pell family until 1774, when it was sold to [[Oliver De Lancey (British Army officer, died 1822)|Oliver De Lancey]]. It was later sold to the Rodman, Haight, and Hunter families, in that order.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} According to Elliott Gorn, Hart Island had become \"a favorite pugilistic hideaway\" by the early 19th century. Bouts of [[bare-knuckle boxing]] held on the island could draw thousands of spectators.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|140}}\n\nThe first public use of Hart Island was training the [[31st United States Colored Infantry Regiment|31st Infantry Regiment]] of the [[United States Colored Troops]] beginning in 1864.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/usct01.html|title=Civil War Colored Troops on DOC islands|publisher=New York Correction History Society|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512114740/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/nycdoc/html/usct01.html|archive-date=May 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\">{{cite web |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/1773.pdf |title=Phase IA - Documentary Study and Archaeological Assessment for the Hart Island, Bronx (Bronx County), New York \u2013 Shoreline Stabilization Project |date=September 2017 |first=Alyssa |last=Loorya |first2=Eileen |last2=Kao |editor-first=Christopher |editor-last=Ricciardi |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318135010/http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/1773.pdf |archive-date=March 18, 2019 |access-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{rp|15}} A [[steamboat]] called ''John Romer'' shuttled recruits to the island from [[The Battery (Manhattan)|the Battery]] at the southern tip of Manhattan. A commander's house and a recruits' barracks were built; the barracks included a library and a concert room;<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} it could house 2,000 to 3,000 recruits at a time, and over 50,000 men were ultimately trained there.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|76}}\n\nIn November 1864, construction of a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] on Hart Island with room for 5,000 prisoners started.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|75}} The camp was used for four months in 1865 during the [[American Civil War]]. The island housed 3,413 captured [[Confederate States Army|Confederate Army]] soldiers.<ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\"/>{{rp|16}} Of these, 235 died in the camp and were buried in [[Cypress Hills Cemetery]]. Following the Civil War, indigent veterans were buried on the island in soldier's plots, which were separate from the potter's field and at the same location. Some of these soldiers were moved to [[West Farms Soldiers Cemetery]] in 1916 and others were removed to Cypress Hills Cemetery in 1941.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/cw_pows/html/cwpows7.html |title=Hart Island: City's Concentration Camp|publisher=New York Correction History Society|date= |access-date=April 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716031443/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/cw_pows/html/cwpows7.html |archive-date=July 16, 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Addition of cemetery===\n<!--[[File:A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by Jacob Riis.jpg|thumb|alt=A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, seen circa 1890|A trench at the potter's field on Hart Island, circa 1890 by [[Jacob Riis]]]]-->\n\nThe first burials on Hart Island were those of 20 [[Union Army]] soldiers during the American Civil War.<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1869/02/27/archives/purchase-of-harts-island.html|title=Purchase of Hart's Island|date=February 27, 1869|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705003808/https://www.nytimes.com/1869/02/27/archives/purchase-of-harts-island.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 27, 1868, New York City purchased the island from Edward Hunter, who also owned nearby [[Hunter Island (Bronx)|Hunter Island]], for $75,000.<ref name=\"hunter\" /><ref name=\"fascinates\" /><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}}<ref name=\"NYCL Hart Island\"/>{{rp|18}} City burials started shortly afterward.<ref name=\"hunter\" /> In 1869, a 24-year-old woman named Louisa Van Slyke, who died in [[City Hospital (Roosevelt Island)|Charity Hospital]], was the first person to be buried in the island's {{convert|45|acre|m2|adj=on}} public graveyard.<ref name=\"hunt\"/><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Brady |title=A Chance to Be Mourned|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|date=November 12, 2006|access-date=August 23, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/12/nyregion/thecity/12home.html?pagewanted=all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731045249/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/12/nyregion/thecity/12home.html?pagewanted=all |archive-date=July 31, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The cemetery then became known as \"City Cemetery\" and \"Potter's Field\".<ref>{{cite web | title=In The Potter's Field.; Burying The City's Pauper Dead | work=The New York Times | language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 | date=March 3, 1878 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1878/03/03/archives/in-the-potters-field-burying-the-citys-pauper-dead-the-voyage-of.html | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020001/https://www.nytimes.com/1878/03/03/archives/in-the-potters-field-burying-the-citys-pauper-dead-the-voyage-of.html | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 1880, ''The New York Times'' described the island as \"the [[Green-Wood Cemetery|Green-Wood]] of [[Five Points, Manhattan|Five Points]]\", comparing an expansive cemetery in Brooklyn with a historically poor neighborhood in Manhattan. The newspaper also said of Hart Island, \"This is where the rough pine boxes go that come from Blackwell's Island\", in reference to the influx of corpses being transported from the hospitals on modern-day [[Roosevelt Island]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1880/11/21/archives/islands-about-newyork-in-the-upper-bay-and-in-the-east-river.html|title=Islands About New-York; in the Upper Bay and in the East River.|date=November 21, 1880|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210807/https://www.nytimes.com/1880/11/21/archives/islands-about-newyork-in-the-upper-bay-and-in-the-east-river.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The potter's field on Hart Island replaced two previous potter's fields on the current sites of [[Washington Square Park]] and [[New York Public Library Main Branch]] in Manhattan. The number of burials on Hart Island exceeded 500,000 by 1958.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/22/archives/about-new-york-citys-unclaimed-dead-lie-on-lonely-tip-of-hart.html|title=About New York; City's Unclaimed Dead Lie on Lonely Tip of Hart Island Off the Bronx|last=Robertson|first=Nan|date=September 22, 1958|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232532/https://www.nytimes.com/1958/09/22/archives/about-new-york-citys-unclaimed-dead-lie-on-lonely-tip-of-hart.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Juxtaposition of uses ===\n\nHart Island was used as a [[quarantine station]] during the 1870 [[yellow fever]] epidemic. In that period, the island contained a women's [[psychiatric hospital]] called The Pavilion, which was built 1885, as well as a [[Tuberculosis|tubercularium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/11/10/archives/criticises-a-city-hospital-grand-jury-says-harts-island.html|title=Grand Jury Says Hart's Island Tuberculosis Ward is Unsuitable|date=November 10, 1917|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|page=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705005207/https://www.nytimes.com/1917/11/10/archives/criticises-a-city-hospital-grand-jury-says-harts-island.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> There was also an industrial school with 300 students on the island.<ref name=\":2\" /> After an 1892 investigation found the city's asylums were overcrowded, it was proposed to expand those on Hart Island from 1,100 to 1,500 beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1893/06/27/archives/overcrowding-the-insane-new-buildings-soon-to-give-relief-to-city.html|title=Overcrowding The Insane; New Buildings Soon To Give Relief To City Patients|date=June 27, 1893|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103212337/https://www.nytimes.com/1893/06/27/archives/overcrowding-the-insane-new-buildings-soon-to-give-relief-to-city.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island.jpg|thumb|alt=A black-on-yellow sketch showing the Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island|Convalescent Hospital on Hart Island, 1877]]\nIn the late 19th century, Hart Island became the location of a boys' [[workhouse]], which was an extension of the prison and almshouse on Blackwell Island. A workhouse for men was established in 1895, and was followed by a workhouse for young boys ten years later.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}} By the early 20th century, Hart Island housed about 2,000 delinquent boys as well as elderly male prisoners from Blackwell's [[Prison|penitentiary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/10/03/104655426.pdf|title=Likes Life in Workhouse: Inmates Writes of 'Good Eats, No Work, and Bum Arguments'|date=October 3, 1915|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 4, 2018}}</ref> The prison on Hart Island grew; it had its own band and a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] prison chapel.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|77}} The cornerstone for the $60,000 chapel was laid in 1931<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/26/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-prison-chapel-mgr-lavelle-addresses-1800-at.html|title=Cornerstone Laid For Prison Chapel; Mgr. Lavelle Addresses 1,800 at Hart's Island\u2014Building to Cost $60,000.|date=October 26, 1931|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114044329/https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/26/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-prison-chapel-mgr-lavelle-addresses-1800-at.html|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and it was opened the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/05/01/archives/cardinal-to-dedicate-prison-chapel-today-ceremony-on-harts-island.html|title=Cardinal To Dedicate Prison Chapel Today; Ceremony on Harts Island to Be Held at 10:30 A.M. \u2013 Drive On for Building Funds.|date=May 1, 1932|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232619/https://www.nytimes.com/1932/05/01/archives/cardinal-to-dedicate-prison-chapel-today-ceremony-on-harts-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, John Hunter sold his {{Convert|4|acre|ha|abbr=|adj=on}} tract of land on Hart Island's west side to Solomon Riley, a millionaire real estate speculator from [[Barbados]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/01/nyregion/fyi-771465.html|title=F.y.i.|last=Schneider|first=Daniel B.|date=March 1, 1998|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210932/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/01/nyregion/fyi-771465.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Riley subsequently proposed to build an amusement park on Hart Island, which would have served the primarily black community of [[Harlem]] in Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141\u2013142}} It was referred to as the \"Negro [[Coney Island]]\"<ref name=\":3\" /> because at the time, African Americans were banned from the [[Playland (New York)|Rye Playland]] and [[Dobbs Ferry, New York|Dobbs Ferry]] amusement parks in the New York City area.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":3\" /> Riley had started building a dance hall, boardinghouses, and a boardwalk, and purchased sixty steamboats for the operation.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":3\" /> The state government raised concerns about the proposed park's proximity to a jail and hospital,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/07/archives/opposes-resort-on-harts-island-state-prison-commission-tells-mayor.html|title=Opposes Resort on Hart's Island; State Prison Commission Tells Mayor Hylan City Should Acquire Property.|date=May 7, 1925|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210805/https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/07/archives/opposes-resort-on-harts-island-state-prison-commission-tells-mayor.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the city condemned the land in 1925.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/17/archives/city-decides-to-take-harts-island-coney-will-get-pleasure-resort-by.html|title=City Decides To Take Hart's Island 'Coney'; Will Get Pleasure Resort by Condemnation \u2013 Valued at $20,000 in 1922, Now $160,000.|date=June 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210734/https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/17/archives/city-decides-to-take-harts-island-coney-will-get-pleasure-resort-by.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Riley was later paid $144,000 for the seizure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/26/archives/city-must-pay-144015-negroes-win-big-award-for-land-seized-near.html|title=City Must Pay $144,015; Negroes Win Big Award for Land Seized Near Reformatory.|date=November 26, 1927|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103210853/https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/26/archives/city-must-pay-144015-negroes-win-big-award-for-land-seized-near.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== After World War II ===\nThe prison population of Hart Island was moved to [[Rikers Island]] during [[World War II]], and Hart Island's former workhouse was used as a disciplinary barracks by the [[United States Armed Forces]]. Rikers Island soon became overcrowded with prisoners.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The [[New York City Department of Correction]] reopened Hart Island as a prison following the war, but the facilities were considered inadequate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/03/31/archives/800000-project-urged-planning-body-calls-for-funds-for-rikers.html|title=$800,000 Project Urged; Planning Body Calls for Funds for Rikers Island Unit|date=March 31, 1949|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108003115/https://www.nytimes.com/1949/03/31/archives/800000-project-urged-planning-body-calls-for-funds-for-rikers.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The New York City Board of Estimate approved the construction of a homeless shelter on the island in 1950; it was intended to serve 2,000 people.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}} The homeless shelter operated from 1951 to 1954;<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} it was also used to house [[Alcoholism|alcoholics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27166768/|first=John|last=Webster|title=Alcoholism a Disease Not a Crime|date=March 26, 1954|work=New York Daily News|access-date=January 13, 2019|page=148|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Residents of nearby City Island opposed the inclusion of the homeless shelter.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/22/archives/assail-hart-island-plan-city-islanders-object-to-housing-of.html|title=Assail Hart Island Plan; City Islanders Object to Housing of Homeless Men Nearby|date=February 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108045723/https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/22/archives/assail-hart-island-plan-city-islanders-object-to-housing-of.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The New York City Welfare Department closed the homeless shelter and the Department of Correction regained control of the island.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}} The Department of Correction opened an alcoholism treatment center on Hart Island in 1955.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/11/16/archives/citys-aid-to-alcoholics-hailed-harts-island-project-is-inspected.html|title=City's Aid to Alcoholics Hailed; Harts Island Project Is Inspected|date=November 16, 1955|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> A courthouse, which ruled on cases involving the homeless, was opened on Hart Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/25/archives/new-court-to-aid-derelicts-of-city-hart-island-setup-to-relieve.html|title=New Court to Aid Derelicts of City; Hart Island Set-Up to Relieve 'Disgraceful' Detention Pens After Sept. 5|date=June 25, 1955|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108003114/https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/25/archives/new-court-to-aid-derelicts-of-city-hart-island-setup-to-relieve.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The island housed between 1,200 and 1,800 prisoners serving short sentences of between 10 days and two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27705314/|title=He's The Burying Kind|date=December 2, 1963|work=New York Daily News|access-date=January 27, 2019|page=177|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the island was retrofitted with [[Nike Ajax]] [[missile silo]]s. Battery NY-15, as the silos were known, were part of the [[United States Army]] base [[Fort Slocum (New York)|Fort Slocum]] from 1956 to 1961 and were operated by the army's 66th Antiaircraft Artillery Missile Battalion. The silos were underground and were powered by large generators.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\"nyt1\" /> Some silos were also built on [[Davids' Island (New York)|Davids' Island]]. The integrated fire control system that tracked the targets and directed missiles was at Fort Slocum. The last components of the missile system were closed in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/05/nyregion/city-lore-when-nike-meant-more-than-just-do-it.html|title=When Nike Meant More Than 'Just Do It'|last=Vanderbilt|first=Tom|date=March 5, 2000|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=August 25, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111023545/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/05/nyregion/city-lore-when-nike-meant-more-than-just-do-it.html|archive-date=November 11, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of a new $7 million workhouse on Hart Island to replace the existing facility was announced in 1959.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/05/13/archives/7000000-workhouse-set-for-rikers-island.html|title=$7,000,000 Workhouse Set for Rikers Island|date=May 13, 1959|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232541/https://www.nytimes.com/1959/05/13/archives/7000000-workhouse-set-for-rikers-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A baseball field was dedicated at the Hart Island prison the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/05/27/archives/stadium-opened-for-hart-island-prisoners-fill-600-seats-from-ebbets.html|title=Stadium Opened for Hart Island; Prisoners Fill 600 Seats From Ebbets Field Given by Apartment Builder|date=May 27, 1960|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232546/https://www.nytimes.com/1960/05/27/archives/stadium-opened-for-hart-island-prisoners-fill-600-seats-from-ebbets.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was named Kratter Field, after [[Marvin Kratter]], a businessman who had donated 2,200 seats saved from the demolished [[Ebbets Field]] stadium.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The seats deteriorated after being outdoors for several years, and by 2000, had been donated to various people and organizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/27/nyregion/ebbets-lights-dimmed-again-in-city-prizing-relics-link-to-dodgers-needs-a-home.html|title=Ebbets Lights Dimmed Again; In City Prizing Relics, Link to Dodgers Needs a Home|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=September 27, 2000|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232607/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/27/nyregion/ebbets-lights-dimmed-again-in-city-prizing-relics-link-to-dodgers-needs-a-home.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe island continued to be used as a prison until 1966, when the prison was closed due to changes in the penal code.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|79}}<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} After it closed, a [[drug rehabilitation]] center was proposed for Hart Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/02/16/archives/hart-island-site-for-addicts-home-former-users-will-offer-only-help.html|title=Hart Island Site For Addicts' Home; Former Users Will Offer Only Help at Center City Will Operate It|last=Schumach|first=Murray|date=February 16, 1967|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107233232/https://www.nytimes.com/1967/02/16/archives/hart-island-site-for-addicts-home-former-users-will-offer-only-help.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The center became [[Phoenix House]], which opened in 1967; it quickly grew into a settlement with 350 residents and a vegetable garden. Phoenix House hosted festivals that sometimes attracted crowds of more than 10,000 people.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|141}} Phoenix House published a newsletter known as ''The Hart Beat'' and organized baseball games against other organizations such as City Island's and [[NBC]]'s teams.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|79}} In 1977, after regular ferry service to Hart Island ended, Phoenix House moved from the island to a building in Manhattan.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/03/19/archives/hart-island-full-of-possibilitiesand-not-much-else-hart-island-a.html|title=Hart Island Full of Possibilities\u2010and Not Much Else|last=Goodwin|first=Michael|date=March 19, 1978|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108000035/https://www.nytimes.com/1978/03/19/archives/hart-island-full-of-possibilitiesand-not-much-else-hart-island-a.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/05/02/archives/phoenix-house-marks-10-years-with-a-new-home.html|title=Phoenix House Marks 10 Years With a New Home|date=May 2, 1977|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108000023/https://www.nytimes.com/1977/05/02/archives/phoenix-house-marks-10-years-with-a-new-home.html|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince then, proposals to re-inhabit the island have failed. In 1972, the city considered converting it into a residential resort but the plan abandoned.<ref name=\":4\" /> New York City mayor [[Ed Koch]] created a workhouse on the island for persons charged with misdemeanors in 1982 but not enough prisoners were sent there. Six years later, another proposal called for a homeless shelter and a workhouse to be built on Hart Island, but this plan was abandoned because of opposition from residents of City Island.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n=== Abandonment of structures and use as cemetery ===\n[[File:Hart Island, Bronx, 1966 (cropped).png|thumb|Map from 1966]]Originally, City Cemetery occupied {{convert|45|acre|ha}} on the northern and southern tips of Hart Island, while the center two-thirds of the island was habitable.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1985, sixteen bodies infected with [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] were buried at the southern tip of Hart Island, away from the rest of the corpses, because it was believed that the dead AIDS victims would contaminate the other corpses with the disease.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/03/nyregion/hart-island-aids-new-york.html|title=Dead of AIDS and Forgotten in Potter's Field|date=July 3, 2018|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703103050/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/03/nyregion/hart-island-aids-new-york.html|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The first pediatric AIDS victim to die in New York City is buried in the only single grave on Hart Island with a concrete marker that reads SC (special child) B1 (Baby 1) 1985.<ref name=\"hunt\" />{{rp|83}}<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" /> Since then, thousands of AIDS victims have been buried on Hart Island, but the precise number of AIDS victims buried on the island is unknown.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" />\n\nFrom 1991 to 1993, New York artist Melinda Hunt and photographer Joel Sternfeld photographed Hart Island for their book of the same name,<ref name=\"Chan 2007\">{{cite web|url=//cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|title=Searching for Names on an Island of Graves|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 26, 2007|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924032526/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|archive-date=September 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which was published in 1998.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Grundberg 1998\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/books/photography.html|title=Photography|last=Grundberg|first=Andy|date=December 6, 1998|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114210637/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/books/photography.html|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hunt subsequently founded the [[Hart Island (Bronx)#The Hart Island Project|Hart Island Project]] organization in 1994 to help the families and friends of those buried on Hart Island.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Owen 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9bzx85/a-virtual-grave-for-new-york-citys-forgotten-dead-219|title=The Isolated Island Where New York's Unknown and Unclaimed Are Buried|last=Owen|first=Tess A.|date=February 20, 2015|work=Vice|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023057/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9bzx85/a-virtual-grave-for-new-york-citys-forgotten-dead-219|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another media work, the 2018 documentary ''One Million American Dreams'', documents the history of Hart Island and delves briefly into the lives of various individuals buried there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/movies/one-million-american-dreams-review.html|title='One Million American Dreams' Review: Stories From New York's Potter's Field|last=Kenny|first=Glenn|date=February 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403112043/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/07/movies/one-million-american-dreams-review.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|access-date=May 19, 2019|8=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/one-million-american-dreams-1184286|title='One Million American Dreams': Film Review|last=Scheck|first=Frank|date=February 8, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is a section of old wooden houses and masonry institutional structures dating back to the late 19th and early 20th centuries that have fallen into disrepair. Military barracks from the Civil War period were used prior to the construction of workhouse and hospital facilities.<ref name=\"kilgannon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/17/nyregion/on-hart-island-new-yorks-potters-field.html?pagewanted=all|title=Visiting the Island of the Dead. A Rare Visit to New York's Potter's Field on Hart Island|first=Corey|last=Kilgannon|date=November 15, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=November 17, 2013|quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118031450/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/17/nyregion/on-hart-island-new-yorks-potters-field.html?pagewanted=all|archive-date=November 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In the late 2010s, the Hart Island Project and City Island Historical Society started petitioning for Hart Island to be listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2018/18/18-hartisland-2018-05-04-bx.html|title=A bone of contention/Erosion exposes human remains on Hart Island|first=Patrick|last=Rocchio|date=May 4, 2018|work=Bronx Times|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155948/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2018/18/18-hartisland-2018-05-04-bx.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]] labeled the island a \"site of historical significance\" in 2016, given that Hart Island met three of the four criteria for being listed on the NRHP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2016/43/43-hartisland-2016-10-21-bx.html|title='Hart Island Historic District' recognized by New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation|first=Patrick|last=Rocchio|date=October 21, 2016|work=Bronx Times|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155948/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2016/43/43-hartisland-2016-10-21-bx.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe island was significantly affected by [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, and some of the shoreline was eroded, which exposed many of the skeletons buried on the island.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://daily.jstor.org/burying-nycs-forgotten-dead-at-hart-island/|title=Burying NYC's Forgotten Dead at Hart Island|last=Lovejoy|first=Bess|date=May 22, 2018|publisher=JSTOR Daily|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162103/https://daily.jstor.org/burying-nycs-forgotten-dead-at-hart-island/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/02/bones-emerge-on-hart-island-where-inmates-bury-new-york-paupers-396123|title=Bones emerge on Hart Island, where inmates bury New York paupers|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|date=May 2, 2018|work=Politico|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162109/https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/02/bones-emerge-on-hart-island-where-inmates-bury-new-york-paupers-396123|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the city announced a restoration of the shoreline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hart-island-cemetery-erosion-human-bones-new-york-city/|title=Erosion at New York's Hart Island graveyard unearths human bones|date=April 25, 2018|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162101/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hart-island-cemetery-erosion-human-bones-new-york-city/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal government gave $13.2 million toward the shoreline project in 2015, but the work was delayed for several years. The start of restoration was initially slated for 2020, but in August 2019, the city announced that shoreline work would begin the following month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-to-start-cleanup-of-cemetery-damaged-in-superstorm-sandy-11564833600|title=New York City to Start Cleanup of Cemetery Damaged in Superstorm Sandy|last=Riski|first=Tess|date=August 3, 2019|website=Wall Street Journal|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826041108/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-to-start-cleanup-of-cemetery-damaged-in-superstorm-sandy-11564833600|archive-date=August 26, 2019|access-date=August 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That December, control of the island passed to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]].<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-hart-island-access-access-expanded-20191204-g6ieajiayvb23meh5u4ynbcma4-story.html|title=De Blasio signs law expanding ferry service access to Hart Island burial ground|last=Sanders|first=Anna|date=December 4, 2019|website=New York Daily News|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/hart-island-mayor-bill-de-blasio-1.39228959|title=Hart Island, NYC's 'potter's field' now a public park|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|date=December 4, 2019|website=Newsday|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/12/04/hart-island-transferred-to-parks-department/|title=Hart Island Transferred To Parks Department As Part Of Plan To Improve Access|date=December 4, 2019|website=CBS New York \u2013 Breaking News, Sports, Weather, Traffic And The Best of NY|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cemetery ==\nHart Island contains New York City's {{convert|131|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[potter's field]], or public cemetery. The potter's field is variously described as the largest tax-funded cemetery in the United States,<ref name=\"Public Radio International\">{{cite web |first=Alina |last=Simone | title=Is your family member buried on Hart Island, off the coast of New York? Sorry, you can't visit | work=Public Radio International | date=February 17, 2015 | url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2015-02-17/uncovering-lost-names-and-stories-people-buried-new-yorks-hart-island-cemetary | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021021/https://www.pri.org/stories/2015-02-17/uncovering-lost-names-and-stories-people-buried-new-yorks-hart-island-cemetary | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> the largest-such in the world,<ref name=\"Owen 2015\"/><ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\">{{cite web | title=This tiny New York island is actually the world's largest mass burial site |first=Soo |last=Kim | work=The Telegraph | date=October 23, 2017 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/united-states/new-york/articles/hart-island-cemetery-biggest-us-burial-site/ | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020000/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/united-states/new-york/articles/hart-island-cemetery-biggest-us-burial-site/ | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> and one of the largest mass graves in the United States.<ref name=\"Verrill 2016\">{{cite web | last=Verrill | first=Courtney | title=Over 1 million unclaimed bodies are buried on a little-known island in New York City \u2013 here's the story behind the massive graveyard | work=Business Insider | date=June 29, 2016 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/story-of-potters-field-on-hart-island-2016-6 | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021022/https://www.businessinsider.com/story-of-potters-field-on-hart-island-2016-6 | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Segar | first=Mike | title=Mass graves in the heart of New York | work=The Wider Image | date=June 27, 2016 | url=https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/mass-graves-in-the-heart-of-new-york | access-date=April 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021022/https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/mass-graves-in-the-heart-of-new-york | archive-date=April 4, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> More than one million dead are buried on the island, though since the 2000s, the burial rate has declined to fewer than 1,500 a year.<ref name=\"hunt\" /><ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/><ref name=\"Verrill 2016\"/><ref name=\"FExits\">{{cite book | last=Largo | first=Michael | title=Final exits : the illustrated encyclopedia of how we die | publisher=Harper | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-06-081741-1 | oclc=64592196 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/finalexitsillust00larg_0/page/407 407\u2013408] | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/finalexitsillust00larg_0/page/407 }}</ref> One-third of annual burials are infants and stillborn babies, which has been reduced from a proportion of one-half since the [[Children's Health Insurance Program]] began to cover all pregnant women in New York State in 1997.<ref name=\"FExits\"/> According to a 2006 ''New York Times'' article, there had been 1,419 burials at the potter's field during the previous year: of these, 826 were adults, 546 were infants and stillborn babies, and 47 were dismembered body parts.<ref name=\"nyt1\" />\n\n=== Burials ===\nThe dead are buried in trenches. Babies are placed in coffins, which are stacked in groups of 1,000, measuring five coffins deep and usually in twenty rows.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> Adults are placed in larger pine boxes placed according to size, and are stacked in sections of 150, measuring three coffins deep in two rows.<ref name=\"hunt\" /><ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}}<ref name=\"News 12 The Bronx 2017\">{{cite web | title=News 12 gets rare look at Hart Island, Potter's Field | work=News 12 The Bronx | date=May 11, 2017 | url=http://bronx.news12.com/story/35407858/news-12-gets-rare-look-at-hart-island-potters-field | access-date=April 3, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403124611/http://bronx.news12.com/story/35407858/news-12-gets-rare-look-at-hart-island-potters-field | archive-date=April 3, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> There are seven sizes of coffins, which range from {{Convert|1|to|7|ft|abbr=|m}} long.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/14/archives/about-new-york-last-ride-to-harts-island.html|title=About New York|last=Ferretti|first=Fred|date=August 14, 1974|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113232517/https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/14/archives/about-new-york-last-ride-to-harts-island.html|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Each box is labeled with an identification number, the person's age, ethnicity, and the place where the body was found, if applicable.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Trebay|first=Guy|date=1992|title=The Last Place|journal=[[Grand Street (magazine)|Grand Street]]|language=en|issue=42|pages=118\u2013131|doi=10.2307/25007564|jstor=25007564}}</ref> Inmates from the [[Rikers Island]] jail are paid $0.50 per hour to bury bodies on Hart Island.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe bodies of adults are frequently disinterred when families are able to locate their relatives through DNA, photographs and fingerprints kept on file at the Office of the Medical Examiner.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> There were an average of 72 disinterments per year from 2007 to 2009. As a result, the adults' coffins are staggered to expedite removal.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|138}} Children, mostly infants, are rarely disinterred.<ref name=\"hunt\" /> Regulations stipulate that the coffins generally must remain untouched for 25 years, except in cases of disinterment.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}}\n\nApproximately half of the burials are of children under five who are identified and died in New York City's hospitals, where the mothers signed papers authorizing a \"City Burial.\" The mothers were generally unaware of what the phrase meant. Many other interred have families who live abroad or out of state and whose relatives search extensively; these searches are made more difficult because burial records are currently kept within the prison system. An investigation into the handling of the infant burials was opened in response to a criminal complaint made to the New York State Attorney General's Office in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Deutzman|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/investigative/090523_Hart_Island_Babies|title=Hart Island Babies|work=Fox 5 NY|publisher=[[WNYW]]; [[Fox Television]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605211222/http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/investigative/090523_Hart_Island_Babies|archivedate=June 5, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBurial records on microfilm at the Municipal Archives indicate that until 1913, burials of unknowns were in single plots, and identified adults and children were buried in mass graves.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/05/15/nyregion/new-york-mass-graves-hart-island.html|title=Unearthing the Secrets of New York's Mass Graves|date=May 15, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515213259/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/05/15/nyregion/new-york-mass-graves-hart-island.html|archive-date=May 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1874/02/01/archives/local-miscellany-where-the-unknown-dead-rest.html|title=Where the Unknown Dead Rest|date=February 1, 1874|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|page=8|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623033021/https://www.nytimes.com/1874/02/01/archives/local-miscellany-where-the-unknown-dead-rest.html|archive-date=June 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1913, the trenches became separate to facilitate the more frequent disinterment of adults. The potter's field is also used to dispose of amputated body parts, which are placed in boxes labeled \"limbs\". Ceremonies have not been conducted at the burial site since the 1950s.<ref name=\"hunt\" />{{rp|83}} In the past, burial trenches were re-used after 25\u201350 years, allowing for sufficient decomposition of the remains. Since then, however, historic buildings have been demolished to make room for new burials.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|139}} Because of the number of weekly interments made at the potter's field at the expense of taxpayers, these mass burials are straightforward and are conducted by [[Rikers Island]] inmates, who stack the coffins in two rows, three high and 25 across, and each plot is marked with a concrete marker. A tall, white, peace monument was erected by New York City prison inmates at the top of a hill that was known as \"Cemetery Hill\" following World War II<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/09/09/archives/prisoners-build-memorial-to-dead-inmates-of-city-penitentiary-on.html|title=Prisoners Build Memorial To Dead; Inmates of City Penitentiary on Hart Island Erecting Potter's Field Monument|date=September 9, 1948|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107234815/https://www.nytimes.com/1948/09/09/archives/prisoners-build-memorial-to-dead-inmates-of-city-penitentiary-on.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was dedicated in October 1948.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/10/11/archives/city-shaft-honors-unclaimed-dead-30foot-monument-dedicated-on-hart.html|title=City Shaft Honors Unclaimed Dead; 30-Foot Monument Dedicated On Hart Island to Memory of 450,000 in Potter's Field|date=October 11, 1948|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107234825/https://www.nytimes.com/1948/10/11/archives/city-shaft-honors-unclaimed-dead-30foot-monument-dedicated-on-hart.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Disease victims' burials====\nDuring the 1980s, those who had died from [[AIDS]] were the only people to be buried in separate graves. The first AIDS victims' bodies were delivered in body bags and buried by inmate workers wearing protective jumpsuits. When it was later discovered that the corpses could not spread HIV, the city started burying AIDS victims in the mass graves.<ref name=\"NYTimes-DeadofAIDS-2018\" /> In 2008, the island was selected as a site for mass burials during a particularly extreme flu pandemic, available for up to 20,000 bodies.<ref name=\"WTSP-20200402\">{{Cite news|last=Greenstein|first=Dale |url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/new-york-city-coronavirus-mass-graves-hart-island/67-df417271-adbd-4715-8588-f3e80f556473 |title=Prisoners are digging mass graves in New York City|date=April 2, 2020|work=|access-date=April 9, 2020 |url-status=live|publisher=WTSP}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City]], Hart Island was designated as the temporary burial site for victims of [[COVID-19]] if deaths overwhelmed the capacity of mortuaries; this option was chosen in lieu of using city parks for such a purpose.<ref name=\"NYDN-20200406\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-new-city-parks-burial-20200406-4vxvowhtk5f45brouqd32s7iau-story.html |title= NYC considers temporary burials on Hart Island amid mounting coronavirus death toll |first= Chris|last=Sommerfeldt |first2=Shant|last2=Shahrigian |date= April 6, 2020 |newspaper= New York Daily News |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC-20200406\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/06/new-york-city-weighs-temporary-burials-as-coronavirus-deaths-overwhelm-mortuary-system.html |title= New York City may have to bury coronavirus victims on public lands as deaths overwhelm mortuaries |first= William |last=Feuer |first2=Noah |last2=Higgins-Dunn |date= April 6, 2020 |publisher= CNBC }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/drone-video-shows-inmates-digging-mass-burial-graves-on-new-york-s-hart-island-1.4888134|title=Drone video shows inmates digging mass burial graves on New York's Hart Island|first=Jackie|last=Vandinther|date=April 8, 2020|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Deaths at home within the city had increased significantly, though the corpses were not tested for COVID-19.<ref name=gothamist1>{{Cite web  |access-date=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408012523/https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live |title=Staggering Surge Of NYers Dying In Their Homes Suggests City Is Undercounting Coronavirus Fatalities |first=Gwynne |last=Hogan |url=https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |website=Gothamist |language=en |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Preparations for mass graves began at the end of March 2020.<ref name=\"WTSP-20200402\" /> On April 9, 2020, [[Reuters]] reported that private contractors were hired to replace inmate labor for mass grave burials,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Lucas |title=New York City hires laborers to bury dead in Hart Island potter's field amid coronavirus surge |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-hart-island/new-york-city-hires-laborers-to-bury-dead-in-hart-island-potters-field-amid-coronavirus-surge-idUSL2N2BX1O5 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Reuters |date=April 9, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and burials began.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York digging mass graves amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52241221 |website=BBC News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=gothamist2>{{cite web |title=Mass Burials On Hart Island Increase Fivefold As COVID-19 Death Toll Skyrockets |first=Christopher |last=Robbins|first2=Sydney|last2=Pereira|first3=Gwynne|last=Hogan|url=https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |website=Gothamist |language=en |date=April 9, 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200410110654/https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |archivedate=April 10, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Records ===\nMany burial records were destroyed by arson in late July 1977. Remaining records of burials before 1977 were transferred to the [[New York City Municipal Archives|Municipal Archives]] in Manhattan; while records after that date are still kept in handwritten ledgers, these are now transcribed into a digital database that is partially available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doc/downloads/pdf/Hart_Island%20_FAQs%202017.07.25.pdf|title=FAQs: Hart Island Burials; What is Hart Island?|date=July 25, 2017|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201024159/https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doc/downloads/pdf/Hart_Island%20_FAQs%202017.07.25.pdf|archive-date=December 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=//cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/online-searching-for-those-buried-and-often-forgotten-on-hart-island/|title=City Introduces Online Database for Its Potter's Field|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=April 11, 2013|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922101540/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/online-searching-for-those-buried-and-often-forgotten-on-hart-island/|archive-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOI) request for 50,000 burial records was granted to the Hart Island Project in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/24/nyregion/24hart.html|title=Finding Names for Hart Island's Forgotten|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=March 24, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314064418/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/24/nyregion/24hart.html|archive-date=March 14, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|title=Searching for Names on an Island of Graves|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 26, 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 10, 2010|authorlink=Sewell Chan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922143000/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/11/26/searching-for-names-on-an-island-of-graves/|archive-date=September 22, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><!--The 1,403 pages provided by the Department of Correction contain lists of all burials from 1985 to 2007. A second Freedom of Information request for records from September 1, 1977, to December 31, 1984, was submitted to the Department of Correction on June 2, 2008, and New York City has located 502 pages from that period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartisland.net/|title=About \u2013 Home Page|date=|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=April 11, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517080156/http://hartisland.net/|archive-date=May 17, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>--> A lawsuit concerning \"place of death\" information redacted from the Hart Island burial records was filed against New York City in July 2008 and was settled out of court in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web | last=Duke | first=Nathan | title=Poets honor Potter's Field dead in Flushing | work=Queens Courier | date=May 19, 2010 | url=https://qns.com/story/2010/05/19/poets-honor-potters-field-dead-in-flushing/ | access-date=April 17, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417030615/https://qns.com/story/2010/05/19/poets-honor-potters-field-dead-in-flushing/ | archive-date=April 17, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Notable people buried ===\nThose interred on Hart Island are not necessarily homeless or indigent. Many of the dead either had families who could not afford the expenses of private funerals or were not claimed by relatives within a month of death. Notable burials include the playwright, film screenwriter, and director [[Leo Birinski]], who died alone and in poverty, was buried there in 1951.<ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/> The American novelist [[Dawn Powell]] was buried on Hart Island in 1970, five years after her death, when the executor of her estate refused to reclaim her remains after being used for medical studies. Academy Award winner [[Bobby Driscoll]], who was found dead in 1968 in an [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] tenement, was buried on Hart Island because his remains could not be identified in a timely fashion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themorningnews.org/article/hart-island|title=Hart Island|first=Clay|last=Risen|date=October 10, 2002|work=The Morning News|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612041811/http://www.themorningnews.org/archives/new_york_new_york/hart_island.php|archive-date=June 12, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[T-Bone Slim]], the [[labor activist]], [[songwriter]], and [[Industrial Workers of the World|wobbly]], was buried on Hart Island after his body was found floating in the [[Hudson River]].<ref name=\"Writings 1993\">{{cite book | editor-last=Rosemont |editor-first=Franklin | title=Juice is stranger than friction : selected writings of t-bone slim | publisher=Charles H. Kerr| year=1985 | isbn=978-0-88286-070-1 | oclc=1001785717 }}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|City Island and Hart Island, Bronx NY.jpg|600px|Aerial view showing Hart Island (lower right) and [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]] (left) in 2010}}\n\n==Public engagement==\n==={{anchor|The Hart Island Project}}Hart Island Project===\n\nFounded by New York artist Melinda Hunt in 1994,<ref name=\"Owen 2015\"/>{{efn|According to the project's website, it was not [[incorporation (business)|incorporated]] as a charity until 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=Mission |publisher=The Hart Island Project | url=https://www.hartisland.net/mission | access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>}} the Hart Island Project is a [[nonprofit organization]] devoted to improving access to the island and its burial data.<ref name=\"Chan 2007\" /><ref name=\"Owen 2015\" /> The organization helps families obtain copies of public burial records; arranges visits to grave sites; and operates a website to help people find relatives interred on the island.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Yorker helps people track down loved ones who died unknown |first=Leigh |last=Remizowski |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/03/10/us/new-york-hart-island/ |publisher=CNN |date=March 11, 2012 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820040301/http://www.cnn.com/2012/03/10/us/new-york-hart-island |archive-date=August 20, 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Melinda Hunt Follows NYC's Lonely Dead To Hart Island |first=Alex |last=Silverman |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/11/14/melinda-hunt-follows-nycs-lonely-dead-to-hart-island/ |publisher=[[WCBS-TV]] |date=November 14, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413125433/http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/11/14/melinda-hunt-follows-nycs-lonely-dead-to-hart-island/ |archive-date=April 13, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Hansi Lo|last=Wang|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/02/04/465588689/relatives-of-deceased-push-for-more-access-to-n-y-c-potter-s-field|title=Relatives Of Deceased Push For More Access To NYC Potter's Field|date=February 4, 2016|publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505120945/http://www.npr.org/2016/02/04/465588689/relatives-of-deceased-push-for-more-access-to-n-y-c-potter-s-field|archive-date=May 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Historian [[Thomas Laqueur]] writes:\n\n{{quote|[[Woody Guthrie]]'s song about the unnamed Mexican migrant dead has had a long resonant history. Hunt, in an emotionally related gesture, has researched, for years, in order to publish the names of as many as 850,000 paupers who lie in 101 acres of Hart Island where the city buries its anonymous dead.<ref>{{cite book | last=Laqueur | first=Thomas | title=The Work of the Dead: A Cultural History of Mortal Remains |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHFqCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA419 | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-0-691-15778-8 | oclc=908084082 | page=419}}</ref>}}\n\nSince 2009, the city has given burial records for the island to the Hart Island Project. In turn, the organization maintains an online database of burial records from 1980 onward.<ref name=\"WSJ Burials 2019\">{{cite web | last=Riski | first=Tess | title=New York City Has Been Releasing Burial Records of Fetal Remains\u2014and Names of Women Linked to Them | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=August 21, 2019 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-has-been-releasing-burial-records-of-fetal-remainsand-names-of-women-linked-to-them-11566420004 | access-date=August 26, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825223818/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-has-been-releasing-burial-records-of-fetal-remainsand-names-of-women-linked-to-them-11566420004 | archive-date=August 25, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The project has led to reforms of access to Hart Island such as opening the island monthly to everyone<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/cityrecord/CITY%20COUNCIL%20SUPPLEMENTS/NEW%20SUPPLEMENTS%20RECIEVED%20ON%20MARCH%205,%202014%20by%20email/FINAL%2011x17%20121013-revised.pdf|title=Supplement to the City Record the Council \u2014 Stated Meeting of Tuesday, December 10, 2013|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|date=December 10, 2013|access-date=March 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230033744/http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/cityrecord/CITY%20COUNCIL%20SUPPLEMENTS/NEW%20SUPPLEMENTS%20RECIEVED%20ON%20MARCH%205,%202014%20by%20email/FINAL%2011x17%20121013-revised.pdf|archive-date=December 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and legislation that requires the Department of Correction to publish burial records online.<ref name=\"DNAInfo-LaunchesDatabase-2013\">{{cite web | last=Zimmer | first=Amy | title=City Launches Online Database for Massive Hart Island Potter's Field | website=DNAinfo New York | date=April 11, 2013 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130411/city-island/city-launches-online-database-for-massive-hart-island-potters-field |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109181602/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130411/city-island/city-launches-online-database-for-massive-hart-island-potters-field|archivedate=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=April 29, 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe Hart Island Project has digitally mapped grave trenches using [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS) data. In 2014, an interactive map with GPS burial data and storytelling software \"clocks of anonymity\" was released as the \"Traveling Cloud Museum\", which collects publicly submitted stories of those who are listed in the burial records.<ref name=\"Public Radio International\"/> Traveling Cloud Museum was updated in 2018 to include a map created with [[GeoTIFF]] images collected by a drone. The map displays nearly 69,000 intact burials and allows people who knew the deceased to add stories, photographs, epitaphs, songs and videos linked to a personal profile, as well as identify AIDS victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlasofthefuture.org/project/traveling-cloud-museum/|title=Traveling Cloud Museum\u2014Atlas of the Future|publisher=Atlas of the Future|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515115127/http://atlasofthefuture.org/project/traveling-cloud-museum/|archive-date=May 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Making Hart Island's graves easier to visit | work=Fox 5 NY | publisher=[[WNYW]]; [[Fox Television]] | date=May 8, 2018 | url=http://www.fox5ny.com/news/hart-island-graves-accessible | first=Liz | last=Dahlem | access-date=August 23, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823220808/http://www.fox5ny.com/news/hart-island-graves-accessible | archive-date=August 23, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Westchester Community College]] hosted an art exhibition of people whose graves were located through the Hart Island Project with Hunt's help.<ref>{{cite news |title=Giving Voice to the Legions Buried in a Potter's Field |first=Susan |last=Hodara |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/01/nyregion/the-hart-island-project-at-westchester-community-college-in-peekskill.html |newspaper=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 |date=December 30, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707101100/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/01/nyregion/the-hart-island-project-at-westchester-community-college-in-peekskill.html |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Art of the Forgotten |first=Jay |last=Blotcher |url=http://www.chronogram.com/hudsonvalley/the-art-of-the-forgotten/Content?oid=2175700 |date=November 30, 2011 |work=Chronogram Magazine |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119112924/http://www.chronogram.com/hudsonvalley/the-art-of-the-forgotten/Content?oid=2175700 |archive-date=November 19, 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Peekskill artist helps families find those buried at Hart Island |first=Marcela |last=Rojas |url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20111112/NEWS01/111120340/Peekskill-artist-helps-families-find-those-buried-Hart-Island |newspaper=The Journal News |date=November 12, 2011 |access-date=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707150030/http://www.lohud.com/article/20111112/NEWS01/111120340/Peekskill-artist-helps-families-find-those-buried-Hart-Island |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The Hart Island Project also collaborated with British landscape architects Ann Sharrock and Ian Fisher to present a landscape strategy to the New York City Council and the Parks Department.<ref name=\"The Telegraph 2017\"/> Sharrock introduced the concept that Hart Island is a natural burial facility and outlined a growing interest in [[green burial]]s in urban settings.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n=== Legislation ===\nOn October 28, 2011, the New York City Council Committee on Fire and Criminal Justice held a hearing titled \"Oversight: Examining the Operation of Potter's Field by the N.Y.C., Department of Correction on Hart Island\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/oct/28/council-looking-city-cemetery/|title=Council Looking Into City Cemetery|last=Hennelly|first=Bob|date=October 28, 2011|publisher=[[WNYC]]|access-date=August 25, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427021944/http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/oct/28/council-looking-city-cemetery/|archivedate=April 27, 2012|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/30/hart-island_n_1066391.html|title=Hart Island Cemetery: City Council Reviews Operations Of New York's Potter's Field (VIDEO)|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=October 30, 2011|work=Huffington Post|access-date=November 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104014101/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/30/hart-island_n_1066391.html|archive-date=November 4, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Legislation passed in 2013 requires the Department of Correction to make two sets of documents available on the Internet: a database of burials and a visitation policy.<ref name=\"WSJ Burials 2019\"/><ref>*{{cite web | title=Requiring the Dept of Correction to make its electronic database of people buried at Hart\u2019s Island, since 1977, available on its website |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]] | url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1082204&GUID=F673F220-DC2A-44D7-B5E3-0D1F61FB9F9A&Options=&Search= |date=December 17, 2013 | access-date=August 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=Requiring the Dept of Correction to put its Hart's Island visitation policy in writing, post it on its website, and make it available to anyone who requests a copy |work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]] | url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1082205&GUID=33965E29-A7DE-4192-BDED-5EDF6E0200E9&Options=&Search= |date=December 17, 2013 | access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> In April 2013, the Department of Correction published an online database of burials on the island.<ref name=\"DNAInfo-LaunchesDatabase-2013\" /> The database contains data about all persons buried on the island since 1977 and is composed of 66,000 entries.<ref name=\"Owen 2015\" /><ref name=\"kilgannon\" />\n\n==== Transfer to Parks Department ====\nA bill to transfer jurisdiction to the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] was introduced on April 30, 2012.<ref name=\"NYC.gov ferry law\">{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1681005&GUID=D615F227-5431-4FF0-9AEE-92F704CDD16E&Options=ID%7CText%7C&Search=Hart+Island|date=March 12, 2014|title=A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to ferry service to Hart's Island|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192122/http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1681005&GUID=D615F227-5431-4FF0-9AEE-92F704CDD16E&Options=ID%7CText%7C&Search=Hart+Island|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2014/46/46-hart-2014-11-14-bx_2014_46.html|title=City Island Civic Association, Chamber visit Hart Island and take tour|last=Rocchio|first=Patrick|date=November 14, 2014|work=Bronx Times|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705070031/https://www.bxtimes.com/stories/2014/46/46-hart-2014-11-14-bx_2014_46.html|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Hart Island Project testified in favor of this bill on September 27, 2012, but the bill was not passed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2012/09/hart-island/|title=An Open Hart Island: Off the Coast of the Bronx Lie 850,000 Lost Souls\u2014the City Council Hopes to Pay Its Respects|last=Velsey|first=Kim|date=September 28, 2012|newspaper=New York Observer|access-date=August 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701022844/http://observer.com/2012/09/hart-island/|archive-date=July 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe bill was reintroduced in March 2014,<ref name=\":8\"/> and Bill 0134 had a public hearing on January 20, 2016.<ref name=\":8\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/20/city-discusses-turning-hart-island-into-a-park.html|title=NYC Discusses Turning Hart Island Into a Park|work=Al Jazeera America|date=January 20, 2016|first=Lisa|last=De Bode|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413073501/http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/20/city-discusses-turning-hart-island-into-a-park.html|archive-date=April 13, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amny.com/news/nyc-council-hears-plan-to-turn-island-of-forgotten-into-park-1.11346723|title=NYC Council hears plan to turn island of forgotten into park |first=Maria |last=Alvarez|date=January 20, 2016|work=am New York|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122163306/http://www.amny.com/news/nyc-council-hears-plan-to-turn-island-of-forgotten-into-park-1.11346723|archive-date=January 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/01/20/hart_island_doc.php|title=Who Should Control Hart Island, NYC's \"Prison For The Dead\"?|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 20, 2016|first=Emma|last=Whitford|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503162012/http://gothamist.com/2016/01/20/hart_island_doc.php|archivedate=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=April 29, 2016|df=}}</ref> The bill ultimately failed because neither the Parks Department nor the Department of Correction supported the move. The Parks Department stated that the operation of an active cemetery was outside its purview while the Department of Correction preferred that another city agency take control of Hart Island.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/21/nyregion/officials-object-to-plan-to-turn-potters-field-over-to-parks-dept.html|title=Officials Object to Plan to Turn Hart Island Burial Site Over to Parks Dept.|last=Bernstein|first=Nina|date=January 20, 2016|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403180525/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/21/nyregion/officials-object-to-plan-to-turn-potters-field-over-to-parks-dept.html|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, City Council member [[Ydanis Rodr\u00edguez]] and three colleagues re-introduced the bill a second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3498510&GUID=DB8FADA8-30C5-4731-8B71-875D9A65C1FA|title=Transfer of jurisdiction over Hart Island from the DOC to the dept of parks and recreation|date=May 9, 2018|work=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council]]|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403174758/https://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=3498510&GUID=DB8FADA8-30C5-4731-8B71-875D9A65C1FA|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In supporting the bill, Rodriguez stated that he wanted relatives of Hart Island's deceased to be able to access their loved ones' graves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/09/council-members-take-up-the-cause-of-the-hart-island-bereaved-408468|title=Council members take up the cause of the Hart Island bereaved|last=Rubinstein|first=Dana|date=May 9, 2018|work=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162102/https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2018/05/09/council-members-take-up-the-cause-of-the-hart-island-bereaved-408468|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Anthony M.|last=DeStefano|url=https://www.amny.com/news/hart-island-erosion-bones-1.18441360|title=Bill would shift control of Hart Island to NYC Parks|date=May 9, 2018|work=am New York|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403162059/https://www.amny.com/news/hart-island-erosion-bones-1.18441360|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill was passed in the New York City Council in November 2019, with most council members voting in favor of transferring jurisdiction to the Parks Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-hart-island-access-20191115-2dv2khnlxzh2nbm4vmqvzbqlgm-story.html|title=NYC Council passes laws aimed at making Hart Island more accessible|last=Shahrigian|first=Shant|date=November 14, 2019|website=New York Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/11/13/hart-island-cemetery-nyc-parks-department-city-council/|title=Hart Island, Final Resting Place Of 1 Million, On Verge Of Becoming NYC Parks Property|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2019|website=CBS News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> The following month, mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] signed the legislation, as well as three other bills, including one that would allow the ferry service to be operated by the [[New York City Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/12/04/hart-island-transferred-to-parks-department/|title=Hart Island Transferred To Parks Department As Part Of Plan To Improve Access|date=December 4, 2019|publisher=CBS New York|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/hart-island-mayor-bill-de-blasio-1.39228959|title=De Blasio signs law making Hart Island, NYC's potter's field, a public park|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|website=Newsday|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\n[[File:Pier and Ferry to Hart Island.JPG|thumb|alt=A ferry pier jutting into the water from the left-hand side of the image|Hart Island ferry pier]]\nThe only access to Hart Island is by ferryboat.<ref name=\":4\" /> Hart Island and the pier on Fordham Street on City Island are restricted areas under the jurisdiction of the New York City Department of Correction. Family members who wish to visit the island must request a visit ahead of time with the Department of Correction. New York City's government offers no provisions for individuals who want to visit Hart Island without contacting the prison system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hartisland.net/contact|title=Contact Information|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402041634/https://www.hartisland.net/contact|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCDOC\">{{cite web | title=Hart Island | website=nyc.gov | publisher=New York City Department of Correction | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doc/about/hart-island.page | access-date=September 3, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807205315/https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doc/about/hart-island.page | archive-date=August 7, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The city government allows family members to visit the island and leave mementos at grave sites, and maintains an online and telephone system for family members to schedule grave site visits.<ref name=\"NYCLU\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyclu.org/files/releases/LuserovCityofNY_settlement_07082015.pdf|title=Stipulation and Order of Settlement: Rosaria Cortes Lusero, Marie Cruz Garcia, and Michelle Caner, On Behalf of Themselves and All Others Similarly Situated, Plaintiffs, Against the City Of New York, Defendant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201041051/http://www.nyclu.org/files/releases/LuserovCityofNY_settlement_07082015.pdf|archivedate=December 1, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=July 29, 2015|df=}}</ref> Other members of the public are permitted to visit by prior appointment only.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hartisland.net/faq|title=FAQ|publisher=Hart Island Project|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705033007/https://www.hartisland.net/faq|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly operated a [[24/7 service|24/7]] ferry service between City and Hart Islands, which ran every forty-five minutes during the day and less frequently at night.<ref name=\":5\" /> The ferries also transported corpses. By the 1960s, two ferryboats were used for the Hart Island ferry service; the ''Michael Cosgrove'' (built 1961) and the ''Fordham'' (in service 1922\u20131982).<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|78}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/timeline/html/hartline.html|title=Hart Island Timeline|last=|first=|date=|publisher=New York Correction History Society|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225202006/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/timeline/html/hartline.html|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The service was extremely expensive to operate; in 1967, about 1,500 people per month used the service and the city spent $300,000 per year to keep it running.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/01/31/archives/city-may-end-hart-island-ferry-1500-a-month-use-the-service-to.html|title=City May End Hart Island Ferry; 1,500 a Month Use the Service to Potter's Field Running the 2 Boats Costs More Than $300,000 a Year|last=Knowles|first=Clayton|date=January 31, 1967|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107232907/https://www.nytimes.com/1967/01/31/archives/city-may-end-hart-island-ferry-1500-a-month-use-the-service-to.html|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> By 1977, the city had discontinued frequent ferry service and provided seven trips a day.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Department of Correction offered one guided tour of the island in 2000.<ref>{{cite web| title=Hart Island| publisher=New York Correction History Society| date=June 15, 2000| url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/harling/| access-date=August 13, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924032515/http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/hart/harling/| archive-date=September 24, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Following the signing of a bill in 2019, the ferry was to be operated at a higher frequency by the New York City Department of Transportation.<ref name=\"Sanders 2019\" /><!-- and a few other visits were offered to members of the [[City Island Civics Association]] and [[Bronx Community Board 10]] in 2014.-->\n\nThe process of visiting the island has been improved due to efforts by the Hart Island Project and the [[New York Civil Liberties Union]].<ref name=\"NYCLU\"/> An [[Ecumenism|ecumenical]] group named the Interfaith Friends of Potter's Field and another organization called Picture the Homeless has also advocated for making the island more accessible.<ref name=\":1\"/>{{rp|144}} In July 2015, the Department of Correction instituted a new policy, wherein up to five family members and their guests were allowed to visit grave sites on one weekend per month.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/nyregion/new-york-city-to-allow-visits-to-grave-sites-on-hart-island.html|title=New York City to Allow Relatives to Visit Grave Sites at Potter's Field|last=Kilgannon|first=Corey|date=July 9, 2015|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027064823/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/nyregion/new-york-city-to-allow-visits-to-grave-sites-on-hart-island.html|archive-date=October 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The first visit took place on July 19, 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|first=Nina|last=Bernstein|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/nyregion/mourners-make-first-visit-to-new-yorks-potters-field.html|title=Mourners Make First Visit to New York's Potter's Field|date=July 20, 2015|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516144138/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/nyregion/mourners-make-first-visit-to-new-yorks-potters-field.html|archive-date=May 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Visits to individual graves, which take place twice a month, are restricted to individuals who had a close relationship with the deceased. Visits to Hart Island's gazebo, which occur once a month, are available to the general public.<ref name=\"NYCDOC\"/> The ferry leaves from a restricted dock on City Island. In 2017, the city government increased the maximum number of visitors per month from 50 to 70.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/24/hart_island_graves_access.php|first=Emma|last=Whitford|title=City Agrees To Increase Mourners' Access To Mass Graves On Hart Island|work=[[Gothamist]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126203703/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/24/hart_island_graves_access.php|date=January 24, 2017|archivedate=January 26, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=January 24, 2017|df=}}</ref> The Department of Correction has opposed further loosening of restrictions on accessing Hart Island; a ''The New York Times'' article quoted a Corrections official as saying: \"As long as D.O.C. runs the facility, we are going to run it with the D.O.C. mentality\".<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Davids' Island (New York)]]\n* [[Geography and environment of New York City]]\n* [[Postage stamps and postal history of the Confederate States#Prisoner of war prisons and camps]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://anglicanhistory.org/academic/kempton2006.pdf|title=In Essentials, Unity; In Non-Essentials, Liberty; and in All Things Charity: Historical Account of the Mission of the Diocese of New York of the Protestant Episcopal Church to the Institutions and the Potter's Field on Hart Island|first=Wayne|last=Kempton|publisher=[[Episcopal Diocese of New York]]|date=2006}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hart Island, Bronx}}\n* {{official|http://hartisland.net}}\n\n{{New York City Islands}}{{Protected areas of New York City}}\n[[Category:Islands of New York City]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Long Island Sound]]\n[[Category:American Civil War prison camps|Hart Island]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in New York City]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Mass graves]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Bronx]]\n", "name_user": "24.173.143.46", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hart_Island_(Bronx)"}
{"title_page": "Yoodlee films", "text_new": "'''Yoodlee Films''' is the film division of [[Saregama|Saregama India Limited]], India's oldest music label. It started in 2017 and has headquarters in [[Mumbai]], India. This writer's studio believes in cinema that has bold themes and powerful stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/9lJtgixJIVWY21oxBk7ioO/Project-mayhem.html|title=Project mayhem|last=Chatterjee|first=Suprateek|date=2018-01-05|work=Mint|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> One of the main highlights of their films is that they are shot at real locations with sync sound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/saregama-gets-into-film-production-with-yoodlee-films/articleshow/59663479.cms|title=Saregama gets into film production with Yoodlee Films - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\nTheir first film was the critically acclaimed [[Ajji]] (2017) directed by [[Devashish Makhija]], starring Sushama Deshpande,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thereel.scroll.in/853372/sushma-deshpande-on-transforming-herself-into-a-vengeful-grandmother-for-ajji|title=The Reel (Scroll.in)}}</ref> Sharvani Suryavanshi, Abhishek Banerjee, [[Vikas Kumar]], [[Sadiya Siddiqui]], [[Sudhir Pandey]] and [[Smita Tambe]]. Their next film [[Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz]] (2018) was by National Award-winning director [[Onir]], starring Zain Khan Durrani, [[Geetanjali Thapa]], [[Shray Rai Tiwari]] and [[Mona Ambegaonkar]]. Their latest film was [[Abhiyum Anuvum|Abhi Anu]], a bilingual romantic drama in Tamil and Malayalam directed by [[B. R. Vijayalakshmi]] and starring [[Tovino Thomas]] and [[Piaa Bajpai]].\n\n== Films ==\n\nYoodlee's first film \u2018Ajji\u2019 released in November, 2017. It is a modern-day version of the European children's story [[Little Red Riding Hood]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/entertainment/yoodlee-films-ajji-wins-prestigious-awards-at-international-film-festivals/1265400|title=Yoodlee Films' 'Ajji' wins prestigious awards at international film festivals {{!}} Free Press Journal|date=2018-04-26|work=Free Press Journal|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en-GB}}</ref>  Ajji is now available on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netflix.com/in/title/80993495|title=Ajji {{!}} Netflix|website=www.netflix.com|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\nTheir second film Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz released in February, 2018. The film is a modern-day love story in the age of social media. It was the opening film at Indian Film Festival Stuttgart 2018 (28) and premiered at festivals like Newcastle International Film Festival 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newcastlefestival.co.uk/films/|title=Films \u2013 Newcastle International Film Festival|website=newcastlefestival.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> Edinburgh UK Asian Film Festival 2018, London UK Asian Film Festival 2018 and Leicester UK Asian Film Festival 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.meetup.com/LondonMuslimMeetup/events/248374733/|title=UK Asian Film Festival: Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz|work=Meetup|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAbhi & Anu released in May 2018. The film was shot in Tamil and Malayalam languages titled Abhiyum Anuvum and Abhiyude Kadha Anuvinteyum respectively.\n\n[[Brij Mohan Amar Rahe]] released on Netflix and garnered various praises for its nail-biting plot twists.\n\nHamid premiered at Mumbai Film Festival (MAMI) 2018 and continued to screen at various festivals like [[Dharamshala International Film Festival]] & [[Tallinn Black Nights Film Festival]]\n\nTheir upcoming projects<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/yoodlee-films-announces-the-line-up-of-upcoming-10-releases-117080200267_1.html|title=Yoodlee Films announces the line-up of upcoming 10 releases|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2017-08-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/yoodlee-films-announces-the-line-up-of-upcoming-10-releases-1008668-2017-08-02|title=Yoodlee Films announces the line-up of upcoming 10 releases|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> are [[Ascharya Fuck It]], [[Noblemen (film)|Noblemen]], Music Teacher, Chaman Bahaar,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/the-test-case-actor-to-play-wizard-in-film-118021600441_1.html|title='The Test Case' actor to play wizard in film|last=IANS|date=2018-02-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> Chhote Nawab,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2018/jul/9/14291/akshay-oberoi-plabita-borthakur-cast-in-yoodlee-films-chhote-nawab|title=Akshay Oberoi, Plabita Borthakur cast in Yoodlee Films\u2019 Chhote Nawab|last=Pandya|first=Sonal|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> KD, Habbadi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2018/may/14/13215/nachiket-samant-shoots-for-yoodlee-films-next-venture-habaddi|title=Nachiket Samant shoots for Yoodlee Films' next venture, Habaddi|last=Correspondent|first=Our|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> and Axone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/entertainment/vinay-pathak-sayani-gupta-come-together-for-bittersweet-comedy|title=Vinay Pathak, Sayani Gupta come together for bittersweet comedy {{!}} Free Press Journal|date=2018-06-21|work=Free Press Journal|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Film\n!Director\n!Cast\n|-\n|2017\n|''Ajji''\n|Devashish Makhija    \n|Sushama Deshpande, Sharvani Suryavanshi, Abhishek Banerjee, Vikas Kumar, Sadiya Siddiqui and Smita Tambe, Sudhir Pandey    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz''    \n|Onir\n|Zain Khan Durrani, Geetanjali Thapa, Shray Rai Tiwari and Mona Ambegaonkar    \n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Abhiyum Anuvum]]''    \n|B.R. Vijayalaxmi  \n|Tovino Thomas, Piaa Bajpai    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Brij Mohan Amar Rahe''    \n|Nikhil Bhat\n|Arjun Mathur, Manav Vij, Sheetal Thakur, Nidhi Singh, Yogender Tiku    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Ascharya Fuck It''    \n|Samit Kakkad\n|Priyanka Bose, Vaibhav Raj Gupta, Ankit Raaj, Anangsha Biswas, Santosh Juvekar    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Noblemen''    \n|Vandana Kataria \n|Kunal Kapoor, Ali Haji, Mohammad Ali Mir, Muskaan Jaferi, Shaan Groverr, Soni Razdan    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Music Teacher''  \n|Sarthak Dasgupta\n|Manav Kaul, Neena Gupta, Amrita Bagchi, Divya Dutta    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Hamid''  \n|Aijaz Khan\n|Rasika Duggal, Vikas Kumar, Talha Arshad Reshi, Sumit Kaul    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Chaman Bahaar''\n|Apurva Dhar Badgaiyann\n|Ritika Badiani, Jitendra Kumar, Bhuvan Arora, Alam Khan, Dhirendra Tiwari, Ashwani Kumar, cop, Yogendra Tiku    \n|-\n|2019\n|''[[K.D. (film)|K.D.]]''\n|Madhumita\n|[[Mu Ramaswamy]], Nagavishal, [[Yog Japee]]  \n|-\n|2019\n|''Chhote Nawab''   \n|Kumud Chaudhary\n|Akshay Oberoi, Plabita Borthakur, Svar Kamble, Ekavali Khanna, Ayush Tandon, Shataf Figar, Neeraj Sood, Sadiya Siddiqui, Sohaila Kapur    \n|-\n|2019\n|''Axone''\n|Nicholas Kharkongor\n|Vinay Pathak, Sayani Gupta, Lin Leshram, Lanuakum Aa, Rohan Joshi, Dolly Alhuwalia, Adil Hussain, Tenzen    \n|-\n|2019\n|''Habbadi''  \n|Nachiket Samant\n|Karan Dave, Vedshree Mahajan, Balakrishna Bajarang Shinde, Rupesh Bane, Mayur Vishnupant Khandge\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Chappad Phaad Ke]] ''  \n|Sameer Hemant Joshi\n|[[Vinay Pathak]], [[Siddharth Menon (actor)|Siddharth Menon]],[[Ayesha Raza]] and Seethal Thakur\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Kanpuriye]] ''  \n|Ashish Aryan\n|[[Aparshakti Khurana]], [[Divyenndu]],[[Harsh Mayar]], [[Vijay Raaz]], [[Rajshri Deshpande]] and [[Harshita Gaur]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film studios in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "'''Yoodlee Films''' is the film division of [[Saregama|Saregama India Limited]], India's oldest music label. It started in 2017 and has headquarters in [[Mumbai]], India. This writer's studio believes in cinema that has bold themes and powerful stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/9lJtgixJIVWY21oxBk7ioO/Project-mayhem.html|title=Project mayhem|last=Chatterjee|first=Suprateek|date=2018-01-05|work=Mint|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> One of the main highlights of their films is that they are shot at real locations with sync sound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/saregama-gets-into-film-production-with-yoodlee-films/articleshow/59663479.cms|title=Saregama gets into film production with Yoodlee Films - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\nTheir first film was the critically acclaimed [[Ajji]] (2017) directed by [[Devashish Makhija]], starring Sushama Deshpande,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thereel.scroll.in/853372/sushma-deshpande-on-transforming-herself-into-a-vengeful-grandmother-for-ajji|title=The Reel (Scroll.in)}}</ref> Sharvani Suryavanshi, Abhishek Banerjee, [[Vikas Kumar]], [[Sadiya Siddiqui]], [[Sudhir Pandey]] and [[Smita Tambe]]. Their next film [[Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz]] (2018) was by National Award-winning director [[Onir]], starring Zain Khan Durrani, [[Geetanjali Thapa]], [[Shray Rai Tiwari]] and [[Mona Ambegaonkar]]. Their latest film was [[Abhiyum Anuvum|Abhi Anu]], a bilingual romantic drama in Tamil and Malayalam directed by [[B. R. Vijayalakshmi]] and starring [[Tovino Thomas]] and [[Piaa Bajpai]].\n\n== Films ==\n\nYoodlee's first film \u2018Ajji\u2019 released in November, 2017. It is a modern-day version of the European children's story [[Little Red Riding Hood]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/entertainment/yoodlee-films-ajji-wins-prestigious-awards-at-international-film-festivals/1265400|title=Yoodlee Films' 'Ajji' wins prestigious awards at international film festivals {{!}} Free Press Journal|date=2018-04-26|work=Free Press Journal|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en-GB}}</ref>  Ajji is now available on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netflix.com/in/title/80993495|title=Ajji {{!}} Netflix|website=www.netflix.com|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\nTheir second film Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz released in February, 2018. The film is a modern-day love story in the age of social media. It was the opening film at Indian Film Festival Stuttgart 2018 (28) and premiered at festivals like Newcastle International Film Festival 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newcastlefestival.co.uk/films/|title=Films \u2013 Newcastle International Film Festival|website=newcastlefestival.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> Edinburgh UK Asian Film Festival 2018, London UK Asian Film Festival 2018 and Leicester UK Asian Film Festival 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.meetup.com/LondonMuslimMeetup/events/248374733/|title=UK Asian Film Festival: Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz|work=Meetup|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAbhi & Anu released in May 2018. The film was shot in Tamil and Malayalam languages titled Abhiyum Anuvum and Abhiyude Kadha Anuvinteyum respectively.\n\n[[Brij Mohan Amar Rahe]] released on Netflix and garnered various praises for its nail-biting plot twists.\n\nHamid premiered at Mumbai Film Festival (MAMI) 2018 and continued to screen at various festivals like [[Dharamshala International Film Festival]] & [[Tallinn Black Nights Film Festival]]\n\nTheir upcoming projects<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/yoodlee-films-announces-the-line-up-of-upcoming-10-releases-117080200267_1.html|title=Yoodlee Films announces the line-up of upcoming 10 releases|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2017-08-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/yoodlee-films-announces-the-line-up-of-upcoming-10-releases-1008668-2017-08-02|title=Yoodlee Films announces the line-up of upcoming 10 releases|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> are [[Ascharya Fuck It]], [[Noblemen (film)|Noblemen]], Music Teacher, Chaman Bahaar,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/the-test-case-actor-to-play-wizard-in-film-118021600441_1.html|title='The Test Case' actor to play wizard in film|last=IANS|date=2018-02-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> Chhote Nawab,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2018/jul/9/14291/akshay-oberoi-plabita-borthakur-cast-in-yoodlee-films-chhote-nawab|title=Akshay Oberoi, Plabita Borthakur cast in Yoodlee Films\u2019 Chhote Nawab|last=Pandya|first=Sonal|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> KD, Habbadi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2018/may/14/13215/nachiket-samant-shoots-for-yoodlee-films-next-venture-habaddi|title=Nachiket Samant shoots for Yoodlee Films' next venture, Habaddi|last=Correspondent|first=Our|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> and Axone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/entertainment/vinay-pathak-sayani-gupta-come-together-for-bittersweet-comedy|title=Vinay Pathak, Sayani Gupta come together for bittersweet comedy {{!}} Free Press Journal|date=2018-06-21|work=Free Press Journal|access-date=2018-07-18|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Film\n!Director\n!Cast\n|-\n|2017\n|''Ajji''\n|Devashish Makhija    \n|Sushama Deshpande, Sharvani Suryavanshi, Abhishek Banerjee, Vikas Kumar, Sadiya Siddiqui and Smita Tambe, Sudhir Pandey    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Kuchh Bheege Alfaaz''    \n|Onir\n|Zain Khan Durrani, Geetanjali Thapa, Shray Rai Tiwari and Mona Ambegaonkar    \n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Abhiyum Anuvum]]''    \n|B.R. Vijayalaxmi  \n|Tovino Thomas, Piaa Bajpai    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Brij Mohan Amar Rahe''    \n|Nikhil Bhat\n|Arjun Mathur, Manav Vij, Sheetal Thakur, Nidhi Singh, Yogender Tiku    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Ascharya Fuck It''    \n|Samit Kakkad\n|Priyanka Bose, Vaibhav Raj Gupta, Ankit Raaj, Anangsha Biswas, Santosh Juvekar    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Noblemen''    \n|Vandana Kataria \n|Kunal Kapoor, Ali Haji, Mohammad Ali Mir, Muskaan Jaferi, Shaan Groverr, Soni Razdan    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Music Teacher''  \n|Sarthak Dasgupta\n|Manav Kaul, Neena Gupta, Amrita Bagchi, Divya Dutta    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Hamid''  \n|Aijaz Khan\n|Rasika Duggal, Vikas Kumar, Talha Arshad Reshi, Sumit Kaul    \n|-\n|2018\n|''Chaman Bahaar''\n|Apurva Dhar Badgaiyann\n|Ritika Badiani, Jitendra Kumar, Bhuvan Arora, Alam Khan, Dhirendra Tiwari, Ashwani Kumar, cop, Yogendra Tiku    \n|-\n|2019\n|''[[K.D. (film)|K.D.]]''\n|Madhumita\n|[[Mu Ramaswamy]], Nagavishal , [[Yog Japee]]  \n|-\n|2019\n|''Chhote Nawab''   \n|Kumud Chaudhary\n|Akshay Oberoi, Plabita Borthakur, Svar Kamble, Ekavali Khanna, Ayush Tandon, Shataf Figar, Neeraj Sood, Sadiya Siddiqui, Sohaila Kapur    \n|-\n|2019\n|''Axone''\n|Nicholas Kharkongor\n|Vinay Pathak, Sayani Gupta, Lin Leshram, Lanuakum Aa, Rohan Joshi, Dolly Alhuwalia, Adil Hussain, Tenzen    \n|-\n|2019\n|''Habbadi''  \n|Nachiket Samant\n|Karan Dave, Vedshree Mahajan, Balakrishna Bajarang Shinde, Rupesh Bane, Mayur Vishnupant Khandge\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Chappad Phaad Ke]] ''  \n|Sameer Hemant Joshi\n|[[Vinay Pathak]], [[Siddharth Menon (actor)|Siddharth Menon]],[[Ayesha Raza]] and Seethal Thakur\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Kanpuriye]] ''  \n|Ashish Aryan\n|[[Aparshakti Khurana]], [[Divyenndu]],[[Harsh Mayar]], [[Vijay Raaz]], [[Rajshri Deshpande]] and [[Harshita Gaur]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film studios in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilms:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoodlee_films"}
{"title_page": "Protozoa", "text_new": "{{Short description|Diverse motile unicellular heterotrophic eukaryotic organisms}}\n[[File:Protozoa collage 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|Clockwise from top left: ''[[Blepharisma japonicum]]'', a [[ciliate]]; ''[[Giardia|Giardia muris]]'', a parasitic [[flagellate]]; ''[[Centropyxis aculeata]]'', a testate (shelled) [[amoeba]]; ''[[Peridinium willei]]'', a dinoflagellate; ''[[Chaos carolinense]]'', a naked amoebozoan; ''[[Desmerella moniliformis]]'', a [[choanoflagellate]] ]]\n\n'''Protozoa''' (also '''protozoan''', plural '''protozoans''') is an informal term for single-celled [[eukaryotes]], either free-living or [[Parasitism|parasitic]], which feed on organic matter such as other [[microorganism]]s or organic tissues and debris.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sYgKY6zz20YC&pg=PA130&lpg=PA130&dq=panno+the+cell#v=onepage&q=panno%20the%20cell&f=false|title=The Cell: Evolution of the First Organism|last=Panno|first=Joseph|date=14 May 2014|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9780816067367|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2zVqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&dq=bertrand+microbiology#v=snippet&q=endocytosis&f=false|title=Environmental Microbiology: Fundamentals and Applications: Microbial Ecology|last=Bertrand|first=Jean-Claude|last2=Caumette|first2=Pierre|last3=Lebaron|first3=Philippe|last4=Matheron|first4=Robert|last5=Normand|first5=Philippe|last6=Sime-Ngando|first6=T\u00e9lesphore|date=2015-01-26|publisher=Springer|isbn=9789401791182|language=en}}</ref> Historically, the protozoa were regarded as \"one-celled animals\", because they often possess [[animal]]-like behaviors, such as [[motility]] and [[predation]], and lack a [[cell wall]], as found in plants and many [[algae]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RawZTwEACAAJ&dq=brock+biology+of+microorganisms+13th|title=Brock Biology of Microorganisms |last=Madigan |first=Michael T. |date=2012 |publisher=Benjamin Cummings |isbn=9780321649638}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK8325/ |title=Protozoa: Structure, Classification, Growth, and Development |last=Yaeger |first=Robert G. |date=1996 |publisher=NCBI|pmid=21413323 |access-date=2018-03-23|isbn=9780963117212 }}</ref>  Although the traditional practice of grouping protozoa with animals is no longer considered valid, the term continues to be used in a loose way to identify single-celled organisms that can move independently and feed by [[heterotroph]]y.\n\nIn some systems of biological classification, '''Protozoa''' is a high-level [[Taxon|taxonomic group]]. When first introduced in 1818, Protozoa was erected as a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] [[Class (biology)|class]],<ref name = \"Goldfu\u00df\"/> but in later classification schemes it was elevated to a variety of higher ranks, including [[Phylum (biology)|phylum]], [[Subkingdom (biology)|subkingdom]] and [[Kingdom (biology)|kingdom]]. In a series of classifications proposed by [[Thomas Cavalier-Smith]] and his collaborators since 1981, Protozoa has been ranked as a [[Kingdom (biology)|kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=1981 |title=Eukaryote kingdoms: seven or nine? |journal=Bio Systems |volume=14 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=461\u2013481 |doi=10.1016/0303-2647(81)90050-2 |pmid=7337818}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=December 1993 |title=Kingdom protozoa and its 18 phyla |journal=Microbiological Reviews |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=953\u2013994 |pmc=372943 |pmid=8302218 |doi=10.1128/mmbr.57.4.953-994.1993}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=23 June 2010 |title=Kingdoms Protozoa and Chromista and the eozoan root of the eukaryotic tree |journal=Biology Letters |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=342\u2013345 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2009.0948 |pmc=2880060 |pmid=20031978}}</ref> The seven-kingdom scheme presented by Ruggiero et al. in 2015, places eight phyla under Kingdom Protozoa: [[Euglenozoa]], [[Amoebozoa]], [[Metamonada]], [[Choanozoa]] ''sensu'' Cavalier-Smith, [[Loukozoa]], [[Percolozoa]], [[Microsporidia]] and [[Sulcozoa]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Notably, this kingdom excludes several major groups of organisms traditionally placed among the protozoa, including the ciliates, [[dinoflagellate]]s, [[foraminifera]], and the parasitic [[apicomplexa]]ns, all of which are classified under Kingdom [[Chromista]]. Kingdom Protozoa, as defined in this scheme, does not form a natural group or [[clade]], but a [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] group or [[evolutionary grade]], within which the members of [[Fungi]], [[Animalia]] and Chromista are thought to have evolved.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Georg_August_Goldfuss_Protozoa_Infusoria_Monades.jpg|left|thumb|upright=1.35|Class Protozoa, order [[Infusoria]], family Monades by [[Georg August Goldfuss]], c. 1844]]\n\nThe word \"protozoa\" (singular ''protozoon'' or ''protozoan'') was coined in 1818 by [[zoologist]] [[Georg August Goldfuss]], as the Greek equivalent of the German ''{{lang|de|Urthiere}}'', meaning \"primitive, or original animals\" (''{{lang|de|{{linktext|ur-}}}}'' \u2018proto-\u2019 + ''{{lang|de|{{linktext|Thier}}}}'' \u2018animal\u2019).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rothschild|first=Lynn J.|date=1989|title=Protozoa, Protista, Protoctista: What's in a Name?|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/4331095|journal=Journal of the History of Biology|volume=22|issue=2|pages=277\u2013305|issn=0022-5010}}</ref> Goldfuss created Protozoa as a [[Class (biology)|class]] containing what he believed to be the simplest animals.<ref name = \"Goldfu\u00df\">{{cite journal |last1=Goldfu\u00df |title=Ueber die Classification der Zoophyten |journal=Isis, Oder, Encyclop\u00e4dische Zeitung von Oken |date=1818 |volume=2 |issue=6 |pages=1008\u20131019 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/47614#page/530/mode/1up |trans-title=On the classification of zoophytes |language=German}} From p. 1008:  ''\"Erste Klasse.  Urthiere.  Protozoa.\"''  (First class.  Primordial animals.  Protozoa.) [Note:  each column of each page of this journal is numbered; there are two columns per page.]</ref> Originally, the group included not only single-celled [[microorganism]]s but also some \"lower\" [[Multicellular organism|multicellular]] animals, such as [[rotifer]]s, [[coral]]s, [[sponge]]s, [[jellyfish]], [[bryozoa]] and [[Polychaete|polychaete worms]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goldfu\u00df |first1=Georg August |title=Handbuch der Zoologie. Erste Abtheilung. |trans-title=Handbook of Zoology. First Part. |date=1820 |publisher=Johann Leonhard Schrag |location=N\u00fcrnberg, (Germany) |pages=XI\u2013XIV |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015070878148;view=1up;seq=11 |language=German}}</ref> The term ''Protozoa'' is formed from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] words {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03c0\u03c1\u1ff6\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}} ({{grc-transl|\u03c0\u03c1\u1ff6\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}}), meaning \"first\", and {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03b1}} ({{grc-transl|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03b1}}), plural of {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03bf\u03bd}} ({{grc-transl|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03bf\u03bd}}), meaning \"animal\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Abr\u00e9g\u00e9 du dictionnaire grec fran\u00e7ais|last=Bailly|first=Anatole|date=1981-01-01|publisher=Hachette|isbn=978-2010035289|location=Paris|oclc=461974285}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tabularium.be/bailly/|title=Greek-french dictionary online|last=Bailly|first=Anatole|date=|website=www.tabularium.be|publisher=|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref> The use of Protozoa as a formal [[taxon]] has been discouraged by some researchers, mainly because the term implies kinship with animals (Metazoa)<ref name=\"Hogg\">{{Cite journal |last=Hogg |first=John |authorlink=John Hogg |date=1860 |title=On the distinctions of a plant and an animal, and on a fourth kingdom of nature |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044089575245;view=1up;seq=232 |journal=Edinburgh New Philosophical Journal | series=2nd series | volume=12 | pages=216\u2013225 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Scamardella |first=J. M. |date=December 1999 |title=Not plants or animals: a brief history of the origin of Kingdoms Protozoa, Protista and Protoctista |journal=International Microbiology |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=207\u2013216 |pmid=10943416}}</ref> and promotes an arbitrary separation of \"animal-like\" from \"plant-like\" organisms.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Copeland |first=Herbert F. |date=September\u2013October 1947 |title=Progress Report on Basic Classification |journal=The American Naturalist |volume=81 |issue=800 |pages=340\u2013361 |doi=10.1086/281531 |jstor=2458229|pmid=20267535 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1848, as a result of advancements in [[cell theory]] pioneered by [[Theodor Schwann]] and [[Matthias Jakob Schleiden|Matthias Schleiden]], the anatomist and zoologist [[Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold|C. T. von Siebold]] proposed that the bodies of protozoans such as [[ciliate]]s and [[amoeba]]e consisted of single cells, similar to those from which the [[Multicellular organism|multicellular]] tissues of plants and animals were constructed. Von Siebold redefined Protozoa to include only such [[Unicellular organism|unicellular]] forms, to the exclusion of all [[Animal|metazoa]] (animals).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siebold (vol. 1) |last2=Stannius (vol. 2) |title=Lehrbuch der vergleichenden Anatomie [Textbook of Comparative Anatomy] |date=1848 |publisher=Veit & Co. |location=Berlin, (Germany) |volume= vol. 1: ''Wirbellose Thiere'' (Invertebrate animals) |page=3 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/41783#page/21/mode/1up |language=German}}  From p. 3:  ''\"Erste Hauptgruppe.  Protozoa.  Thiere, in welchen die verschiedenen Systeme der Organe nicht scharf ausgeschieden sind, und deren unregelm\u00e4ssige Form und einfache Organisation sich auf eine Zelle reduziren lassen.\"''  (First principal group.  Protozoa.  Animals, in which the different systems of organs are not sharply separated, and whose irregular form and simple organization can be reduced to one cell.)</ref> At the same time, he raised the group to the level of a [[phylum]] containing two broad classes of microorganisms: [[Infusoria]] (mostly ciliates and flagellated [[algae]]), and Rhizopoda ([[Amoeba|amoeboid organisms]]). The definition of Protozoa as a phylum or sub-kingdom composed of \"unicellular animals\" was adopted by the zoologist [[Otto B\u00fctschli]]\u2014celebrated at his centenary as the \"architect of protozoology\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dobell|first=C.|date=April 1951|title=In memoriam Otto B\u00fctschli (1848-1920) \"architect of protozoology\"|journal=Isis; an International Review Devoted to the History of Science and Its Cultural Influences|volume=42|issue=127|pages=20\u201322 |pmid=14831973|doi=10.1086/349230}}</ref>\u2014and the term came into wide use.\n\n[[File:John_Hogg_--_Primigenum_or_Protoctista.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|[[John Hogg (biologist)|John Hogg]]'s illustration of the Four Kingdoms of Nature, showing \"Primigenal\" as a greenish haze at the base of the Animals and Plants, 1860]]\n\nAs a phylum under Animalia, the Protozoa were firmly rooted in the old \"two-kingdom\" classification of life, according to which all living beings were classified as either animals or plants. As long as this scheme remained dominant, the protozoa were understood to be animals and studied in departments of Zoology, while photosynthetic microorganisms and microscopic fungi\u2014the so-called Protophyta\u2014were assigned to the Plants, and studied in departments of Botany.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Taylor |first=F. J. R. 'Max' |date=11 January 2003 |title=The collapse of the two-kingdom system, the rise of protistology and the founding of the International Society for Evolutionary Protistology (ISEP) |url=http://ijs.sgmjournals.org/content/53/6/1707 |journal=International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology |volume=53 |issue=6 |pages=1707\u20131714 |doi=10.1099/ijs.0.02587-0 |pmid=14657097}}</ref>\n\nCriticism of this system began in the latter half of the 19th century, with the realization that many organisms met the criteria for inclusion among both plants and animals. For example, the algae ''[[Euglena]]'' and ''[[Dinobryon]]'' have [[chloroplast]]s for [[photosynthesis]], but can also feed on organic matter and are [[Motility|motile]]. In 1860, [[John Hogg (biologist)|John Hogg]] argued against the use of \"protozoa\", on the grounds that \"naturalists are divided in opinion\u2014and probably some will ever continue so\u2014whether many of these organisms, or living beings, are animals or plants.\"<ref name=\"Hogg\" /> As an alternative, he proposed a new kingdom called Primigenum, consisting of both the protozoa and unicellular algae (protophyta), which he combined together under the name \"Protoctista\". In Hoggs's conception, the animal and plant kingdoms were likened to two great \"pyramids\" blending at their bases in the Kingdom Primigenum.\n\nSix years later, [[Ernst Haeckel]] also proposed a third kingdom of life, which he named [[Protista]]. At first, Haeckel included a few multicellular organisms in this kingdom, but in later work he restricted the Protista to single-celled organisms, or simple colonies whose individual cells are not differentiated into different kinds of [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]].\n\nDespite these proposals, Protozoa emerged as the preferred taxonomic placement for [[Heterotrophic nutrition|heterotrophic]] microorganisms such as amoebae and ciliates, and remained so for more than a century. In the course of the 20th century, however, the old \"two kingdom\" system began to weaken, with the growing awareness that fungi did not belong among the plants, and that most of the unicellular protozoa were no more closely related to the animals than they were to the plants. By mid-century, some biologists, such as [[Herbert Copeland]], [[Robert H. Whittaker]] and [[Lynn Margulis]], advocated the revival of Haeckel's Protista or Hogg's Protoctista as a kingdom-level eukaryotic group, alongside Plants, Animals and Fungi.<ref name=\":0\" /> A variety of [[Kingdom (biology)|multi-kingdom systems]] were proposed, and Kingdoms Protista and Protoctista became well established in biology texts and curricula.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Whittaker |first=R. H. |date=10 January 1969 |title=New concepts of kingdoms or organisms. Evolutionary relations are better represented by new classifications than by the traditional two kingdoms |journal=Science |volume=163 |issue=3863 |pages=150\u2013160 |bibcode=1969Sci...163..150W|doi=10.1126/science.163.3863.150 |pmid=5762760|citeseerx=10.1.1.403.5430 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Margulis |first=Lynn |authorlink=Lynn Margulis |date=1974 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-1-4615-6946-6 |editor-last=Dobzhansky|editor-first=Theodosius |pages=45\u201378 |editor-last2=Hecht |editor-first2=Max K.|editor-last3=Steere |editor-first3=William C. |doi=10.1007/978-1-4615-6944-2_2 |chapter=Five-Kingdom Classification and the Origin and Evolution of Cells |title=Evolutionary Biology}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Cavalier-Smith, Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=August 1998 |title=A revised six-kingdom system of life |journal=Biological Reviews |volume=73 |issue=3 |pages=203\u2013266 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-185X.1998.tb00030.x |pmid=9809012}}</ref>\n\nWhile many taxonomists have abandoned Protozoa as a high-level group, Thomas Cavalier-Smith has retained it as a kingdom in the various classifications he has proposed. As of 2015, Cavalier-Smith's Protozoa excludes several major groups of organisms traditionally placed among the protozoa, including the ciliates, [[dinoflagellate]]s and [[foraminifera]] (all members of the [[SAR supergroup]]). In its current form, his kingdom Protozoa is a [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] group which includes a common ancestor and most of its descendants, but excludes two important clades that branch within it: the animals and fungi.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Ruggiero |first=Michael A. |last2=Gordon |first2=Dennis P. |last3=Orrell |first3=Thomas M. |last4=Bailly |first4=Nicolas |last5=Bourgoin |first5=Thierry |last6=Brusca |first6=Richard C. |last7=Cavalier-Smith |first7=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |last8=Guiry |first8=Michael D. |last9=Kirk |first9=Paul M. |date=29 April 2015 |title=A Higher Level Classification of All Living Organisms |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=10 |issue=4 |pages=e0119248 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1019248R|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0119248 |pmc=4418965 |pmid=25923521}}</ref>\n\nSince the protozoa, as traditionally defined, can no longer be regarded as \"primitive animals\" the terms \"protists\", \"Protista\" or \"Protoctista\" are sometimes preferred. In 2005, members of the Society of [[Protozoologist]]s voted to change its name to the International Society of [[Protistologist]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://protozoa.uga.edu/artman/publish/article_37.shtml |title=New President's Address|website=protozoa.uga.edu |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n=== Size ===\n\nProtozoa, as traditionally defined, range in size from as little as 1 [[micrometers|micrometre]] to several [[millimetre]]s, or more.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pddpAAAAMAAJ|title=Dictionary of microbiology and molecular biology|last=Singleton|first=Paul|last2=Sainsbury|first2=Diana|date=2001|publisher=Wiley|isbn=9780471941507|language=en}}</ref> Among the largest are the deep-sea\u2013dwelling [[xenophyophores]], single-celled foraminifera whose shells can reach 20&nbsp;cm in diameter.<ref name=\"Gooday2011\">{{cite journal |last=Gooday |first=A.J. |last2=Aranda da Silva |first2=A. P. |last3=Pawlowski |first3=J. |title=Xenophyophores (Rhizaria, Foraminifera) from the Nazar\u00e9 Canyon (Portuguese margin, NE Atlantic) |journal=Deep-Sea Research Part II: Topical Studies in Oceanography|date=1 December 2011 |volume=58 |issue=24\u201325 |pages=2401\u20132419 |bibcode=2011DSRII..58.2401G |doi=10.1016/j.dsr2.2011.04.005 }}</ref> \n[[File:Spirostomum.jpeg|thumb|The ciliate ''Spirostomum ambiguum'' can attain 3 mm in length]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Species \n!Cell type\n!Size in micrometres\n|-\n|''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'' || [[malaria]] [[parasite]], trophozoite phase<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microbiologybook.org/parasitology/blood-malaria.htm|title=Blood and Tissue Protozoa|last=Ghaffar|first=Abdul|website=Microbiology and Immunology On-Line|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|1-2\n|-\n|''[[Massisteria|Massisteria voersi]]'' || free-living [[cercozoa]]n amoeboid<ref name=\"Mylnikov\">{{Cite journal|last=Mylnikov|first=Alexander P.|last2=Weber|first2=Felix|last3=J\u00fcrgens|first3=Klaus|last4=Wylezich|first4=Claudia|date=August 2015|title=''Massisteria marina'' has a sister: ''Massisteria voersi'' sp. nov., a rare species isolated from coastal waters of the Baltic Sea|journal=European Journal of Protistology |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=299\u2013310|doi=10.1016/j.ejop.2015.05.002|pmid=26163290}}</ref> \n|2.3\u20133\n|-\n|''[[Bodo saltans]]'' || free living [[Kinetoplastida|kinetoplastid]] flagellate<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mitchell|first=Gary C.|last2=Baker|first2=J. H.|last3=Sleigh |first3=M. A. |date=1 May 1988|title=Feeding of a freshwater flagellate, ''Bodo saltans'', on diverse bacteria |journal=The Journal of Protozoology |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=219\u2013222 |doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.1988.tb04327.x}}</ref>\n|5-8\n|-\n|''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'' || [[malaria]] parasite, gametocyte phase<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microbiologybook.org/parasitology/blood-malaria.htm|title=Blood and tissue Protozoa|last=Ghaffar|first=Abdul |website=Microbiology and Immunology On-Line |accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|7-14\n|-\n|''[[Trypanosoma cruzi]]'' || parasitic kinetoplastid, [[Chagas disease]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parasite.org.au/para-site/text/brucei-text.html |title=''Trypanosoma brucei'' |website=parasite.org.au |access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|14-24\n|-\n|''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' || parasitic [[amoebozoa]]n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://msu.edu/course/zol/316/ehisscope.htm |title=Microscopy of ''Entamoeba histolytica''|website=msu.edu|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n|15\u201360\n|-\n|''[[Balantidium coli]]'' || parasitic ciliate<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.udel.edu/mls/dlehman/medt372/B-coli.html |title=Diagnostic parasitology |last=Lehman |first=Don |website=University of Delaware|accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|50-100\n|-\n|''[[Paramecium caudatum]]'' || free-living ciliate<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eol.org/pages/484358/overview|title=''Paramecium caudatum''|last=Taylor|first=Bruce|website=Encyclopedia of Life|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|120-330\n|-\n|''[[Amoeba proteus]]'' || free-living amoebozoan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arcella.nl/amoeba-proteus|title=''Amoeba proteus'' {{!}} Microworld|website=www.arcella.nl|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n|220\u2013760\n|-\n|''[[Noctiluca scintillans]]'' || free-living [[dinoflagellate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imas.utas.edu.au/zooplankton/image-key/noctiluca-scintillans|title=''Noctiluca scintillans''|date=2011-11-30|website=University of Tasmania, Australia|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|700\u20132000\n|-\n|''[[Syringammina fragilissima]]'' || [[foraminifera]]n amoeboid<ref name=\"Gooday2011\"/>\n|up to {{val|200000}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Habitat ===\nFree-living protozoans are common and often abundant in fresh, brackish and salt water, as well as other moist environments, such as soils and mosses. Some species thrive in extreme environments such as hot springs<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mJAxvgAACAAJ&dq=yellowstone+microorganisms|title=Seen and Unseen: Discovering the Microbes of Yellowstone|last=Sheehan|first=Kathy B.|date=2005|publisher=Falcon|isbn=9780762730933|language=en}}</ref> and hypersaline lakes and lagoons.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Post|first=F. J.|last2=Borowitzka|first2=L. J.|last3=Borowitzka|first3=M. A.|last4=Mackay|first4=B.|last5=Moulton|first5=T.|date=1983-09-01|title=The protozoa of a Western Australian hypersaline lagoon|journal=Hydrobiologia|language=en|volume=105|issue=1|pages=95\u2013113|doi=10.1007/BF00025180|issn=0018-8158|bibcode=2004HyBio.524..167W}}</ref>   All protozoa require a moist habitat; however, some can survive for long periods of time in dry environments, by forming [[Microbial cyst|resting cysts]] which enable them to remain dormant until conditions improve.\n\n[[Parasitism|Parasitic]] and [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] protozoa live on or within other organisms, including [[vertebrate]]s and [[invertebrate]]s, as well as plants and other single-celled organisms. Some are harmless or beneficial to their host organisms; others may be significant causes of diseases, such as [[babesia]], [[malaria]] and [[toxoplasmosis]].\n[[File:Isotricha intestinalis.jpg|thumb|''[[Isotricha intestinalis]]'', a ciliate present in the rumen of sheep.]]\nAssociation between protozoan symbionts and their host organisms can be mutually beneficial. Flagellated protozoans such as ''[[Trichonympha]]'' and ''[[Pyrsonympha]]'' inhabit the guts of termites, where they enable their insect host to digest wood by helping to break down complex [[sugar]]s into smaller, more easily digested molecules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kennethnoll.uconn.edu/nsf-termite-project/termite-gut-microbes.html|title=Termite gut microbes {{!}} NOLL LAB|website=www.kennethnoll.uconn.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> A wide range of protozoans live [[Commensalism|commensally]] in the rumens of ruminant animals, such as cattle and sheep. These include flagellates, such as ''[[Trichomonas]]'', and ciliated protozoa, such as ''[[Isotricha]]'' and ''[[Entodinium]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Rumen Microbial Ecosystem|last=Williams|first=A. G.|last2=Coleman|first2=G. S.|date=1997|publisher=Springer, Dordrecht|isbn=9789401071499|pages=73\u2013139|doi=10.1007/978-94-009-1453-7_3}}</ref>  The ciliate subclass Astomatia is composed entirely of mouthless symbionts adapted for life in the guts of annelid worms.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hY0WAQAAIAAJ|title=An illustrated guide to the protozoa: organisms traditionally referred to as protozoa, or newly discovered groups|last=Lee|first=John J.|last2=Leedale|first2=Gordon F.|last3=Bradbury|first3=Phyllis Clarke|date=25 May 2000|publisher=Society of Protozoologists|isbn=|location=|pages=634|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Feeding ===\n\nAll protozoans are [[heterotroph]]ic, deriving nutrients from other organisms, either by ingesting them whole or consuming their organic remains and waste-products. Some protozoans take in food by [[phagocytosis]], engulfing organic particles with [[pseudopodia]] (as [[amoeba]]e do), or taking in food through a specialized mouth-like aperture called a [[cytostome]]. Others take in food by [[osmotrophy]], absorbing dissolved nutrients through their [[cell membrane]]s.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nParasitic protozoans use a wide variety of feeding strategies, and some may change methods of feeding in different phases of their life cycle. For instance, the malaria parasite ''[[Plasmodium]]'' feeds by [[pinocytosis]] during its immature [[Apicomplexan life cycle|trophozoite]] stage of life (ring phase), but develops a dedicated feeding [[organelle]] (cytostome) as it matures within a host's red blood cell.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tulane.edu/~wiser/malaria/fv.html |title=Biochemistry of Plasmodium |last=Wiser |first=Mark F. |website=The Wiser Page |access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ameba_001.jpg|thumb|''[[Paramecium bursaria]]'', a ciliate which derives some of its nutrients from algal [[endosymbiont]]s in the genus ''[[Chlorella]]'']]\n\nProtozoa may also live as [[mixotroph]]s, supplementing a heterotrophic diet with some form of [[autotroph]]y. Some protozoa form close associations with symbiotic photosynthetic algae, which live and grow within the membranes of the larger cell and provide nutrients to the host. Others practice [[kleptoplasty]], stealing [[chloroplast]]s from prey organisms and maintaining them within their own cell bodies as they continue to produce nutrients through photosynthesis. The ciliate ''[[Mesodinium rubrum]]'' retains functioning [[plastid]]s from the cryptophyte algae on which it feeds, using them to nourish themselves by autotrophy. These, in turn, may be passed along to dinoflagellates of the genus [[Dinophysis]] , which prey on ''Mesodinium rubrum'' but keep the enslaved plastids for themselves. Within Dinophysis, these plastids can continue to function for months.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Nishitani |first=Goh |last2=Nagai |first2=Satoshi |last3=Baba|first3=Katsuhisa |last4=Kiyokawa |first4=Susumu |last5=Kosaka|first5=Yuki |last6=Miyamura |first6=Kazuyoshi |last7=Nishikawa |first7=Tetsuya |last8=Sakurada |first8=Kiyonari |last9=Shinada |first9=Akiyoshi |date=May 2010 |title=High-Level Congruence of Myrionecta rubra Prey and Dinophysis Species Plastid Identities as Revealed by Genetic Analyses of Isolates from Japanese Coastal Waters |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |volume=76|issue=9 |pages=2791\u20132798 |doi=10.1128/AEM.02566-09 |pmc=2863437 |pmid=20305031}}</ref>\n\n=== Motility ===\n\nOrganisms traditionally classified as protozoa are abundant in [[aqueous]] environments and [[soil]], occupying a range of [[trophic level]]s. The group includes [[flagellate]]s (which move with the help of whip-like structures called [[flagella]]), [[ciliate]]s (which move by using hair-like structures called [[cilia]]) and [[amoeba]]e (which move by the use of foot-like structures called [[pseudopodia]]). Some protozoa are [[Sessility (zoology)|sessile]], and do not move at all.\n\n=== Pellicle ===\nUnlike plants, fungi and most types of algae, protozoans do not typically have a rigid [[cell wall]], but are usually enveloped by elastic structures of membranes that permit movement of the cell. In some protozoans, such as the ciliates and [[euglenozoa]]ns, the cell is supported by a composite membranous envelope called the \"pellicle\". The pellicle gives some shape to the cell, especially during locomotion. Pellicles of protozoan organisms vary from flexible and elastic to fairly rigid.  In [[ciliate]]s and [[Apicomplexa]], the pellicle is supported by closely packed vesicles called alveoli. In [[euglenid]]s, it is formed from [[protein]] strips arranged spirally along the length of the body. Familiar examples of protists with a pellicle are the [[euglenoids]] and the ciliate ''[[Paramecium]]''. In some protozoa, the pellicle hosts [[Epibiont|epibiotic]] bacteria that adhere to the surface by their [[Pilus#fimbriae|fimbriae]] (attachment pili).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/protozoainbiolog00calk#page/1008/mode/2up Protozoa in biological research<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[File:Dileptus_viridis_cyst.jpg|thumb|Resting cyst of ciliated protozoan ''Dileptus viridis''.]]\n\n=== Life cycle ===\n[[File:Toxoplasmosis life cycle en.svg|thumb|Life cycle of parasitic protozoan, ''Toxoplasma gondii'']]\nSome protozoa have two-phase life cycles, alternating between proliferative stages (e.g., [[trophozoite]]s) and dormant [[Microbial cyst|cysts]]. As cysts, protozoa can survive harsh conditions, such as exposure to extreme temperatures or harmful chemicals, or long periods without access to nutrients, water, or oxygen for periods of time. Being a cyst enables parasitic species to survive outside of a host, and allows their transmission from one host to another. When protozoa are in the form of [[trophozoite]]s (Greek ''tropho'' = to nourish), they actively feed. The conversion of a trophozoite to cyst form is known as encystation, while the process of transforming back into a trophozoite is known as excystation.\n\nAll protozoans reproduce (not all) asexually by [[binary fission]] or multiple fission. Many protozoan species exchange genetic material by sexual means (typically, through [[Isogamy#Conjugation|conjugation]]); however, sexuality is generally decoupled from the process of reproduction, and does not immediately result in increased population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/ca/academic/subjects/life-sciences/evolutionary-biology/sex-and-death-protozoa-history-obsession|title=Sex and Death in Protozoa|website=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Origin and function of meiosis|meiotic sex]] is widespread among present day [[eukaryote]]s, it has, until recently, been unclear whether or not eukaryotes were sexual early in their evolution.  Due to recent advances in [[gene]] detection and other techniques, evidence has been found for some form of meiotic sex in an increasing number of protozoans of ancient lineage that diverged early in eukaryotic evolution.<ref>Bernstein H, Bernstein C (2013). Bernstein C, Bernstein H eds. ''Evolutionary Origin and Adaptive Function of Meiosis'. Meiosis. InTech. {{ISBN|978-953-51-1197-9}}''</ref>  (See [[Eukaryote#Reproduction|eukaryote reproduction]].)  Thus, such findings suggest that meiotic sex arose early in eukaryotic evolution. Examples of protozoan meiotic sexuality are described in the articles ''[[Amoebozoa]]'', ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'', ''[[Leishmania]]'', ''[[Plasmodium falciparum biology]]'', ''[[Paramecium]]'', ''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'', ''[[Trichomonas vaginalis]]'' and ''[[Trypanosoma brucei]]''.\n\n== Classification ==\n{{Further|wikispecies:Protozoa}}Historically, the Protozoa were classified as \"unicellular animals\", as distinct from the Protophyta, single-celled photosynthetic organisms (algae) which were considered primitive plants. Both groups were commonly given the rank of phylum, under the kingdom Protista.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/protozoology1954kudo|title=Protozoology|last=Kudo|first=Richard R. (Richard Roksabro)|date=1954|publisher=Springfield, Ill., C. C. Thomas|others=MBLWHOI Library}}</ref> In older systems of classification, the phylum Protozoa was commonly divided into several sub-groups, reflecting the means of locomotion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Honigberg|first=B. M.|author2=W. Balamuth|author3=E. C. Bovee|author4=J. O. Corliss|author5=M. Gojdics|author6=R. P. Hall|author7=R. R. Kudo|author8=N. D. Levine|author9=A. R. Lobblich|date=February 1964|title=A Revised Classification of the Phylum Protozoa|journal=Journal of Eukaryotic Microbiology|volume=11|issue=1|pages=7\u201320|doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.1964.tb01715.x|pmid=14119564|author10=J. Weiser}}</ref> Classification schemes differed, but throughout much of the 20th century the major groups of Protozoa included:\n\n* [[Flagellate]]s, or [[Flagellate|Mastigophora]] (motile cells equipped with whiplike organelles of locomotion, e.g., ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'')\n* [[Amoeba|Amoebae or Sarcodina]] (cells that move by extending [[pseudopodia]] or [[Lamellipodium|lamellipodia]], e.g., ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'')\n* [[Sporozoans]], or Sporozoa (parasitic, spore-producing cells, whose adult form lacks organs of motility, e.g., ''[[Plasmodium knowlesi]]'')\n** [[Apicomplexa]] (now in [[Alveolata]])\n** [[Microsporidia]] (now in [[Fungi]])\n** [[Ascetosporea]] (now in [[Rhizaria]])\n** [[Myxosporidia]] (now in [[Cnidaria]])\n* [[Ciliate]]s, or Ciliophora (cells equipped with large numbers of short hairlike organs of locomotion, e.g., ''[[Balantidium coli]]''\nWith the emergence of [[molecular phylogenetics]] and tools enabling researchers to directly compare the DNA of different organisms, it became evident that, of the main sub-groups of Protozoa, only the ciliates (Ciliophora) formed a natural group, or [[Monophyly|monophyletic]] [[clade]] (that is, a distinct lineage of organisms sharing common ancestry). The other classes or subphyla of Protozoa were all [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]] groups composed of organisms that, despite similarities of appearance or way of life, were not necessarily closely related to one another. In the system of [[eukaryote]] classification currently endorsed by the International Society of Protistologists, members of the old phylum Protozoa have been distributed among a variety of supergroups.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Adl|first=Sina M. |last2=Simpson |first2=Alastair G. B. |last3=Lane |first3=Christopher E. |last4=Luke\u0161 |first4=Julius |last5=Bass |first5=David |last6=Bowser |first6=Samuel S. |last7=Brown |first7=Matthew W. |last8=Burki |first8=Fabien |last9=Dunthorn |first9=Micah |date=2012-09-01 |title=The Revised Classification of Eukaryotes |journal=Journal of Eukaryotic Microbiology |volume=59 |issue=5 |pages=429\u2013514 |doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.2012.00644.x |pmid=23020233 |pmc=3483872}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\nAs components of the [[Fauna (animals)#Microfauna|micro-]] and [[Fauna (animals)#Meiofauna|meiofauna]], protozoa are an important food source for [[microinvertebrate]]s. Thus, the ecological role of protozoa in the transfer of bacterial and algal production to successive [[Trophic pyramid|trophic levels]] is important. As predators, they prey upon [[unicellular]] or [[filamentous algae]], [[bacteria]], and [[microfungi]]. Protozoan species include both [[herbivore]]s and [[Heterotroph|consumers]] in the decomposer link of the [[food chain]]. They also control bacteria populations and [[biomass]] to some extent.\n\n=== Disease ===\n\n[[File:Trophozoites_of_Entamoeba_histolytica_with_ingested_erythrocytes.JPG|thumb|Trophozoites of the [[amoebic dysentery]] pathogen ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' with ingested human [[red blood cell]]s (dark circles)]]\n{{Main|Protozoan infection}}A number of protozoan [[pathogen]]s are [[human parasite]]s, causing diseases such as [[malaria]] (by ''[[Plasmodium]]''), [[amoebiasis]], [[giardiasis]], [[toxoplasmosis]], [[cryptosporidiosis]], [[trichomoniasis]], [[Chagas disease]], [[leishmaniasis]], [[African trypanosomiasis]] (sleeping sickness), [[Acanthamoeba keratitis|''Acanthamoeba'' keratitis]], and [[primary amoebic meningoencephalitis]] (naegleriasis).\n\nThe protozoan ''[[Ophryocystis elektroscirrha]]'' is a parasite of [[butterfly]] [[larva]]e, passed from [[Vertical transmission|female to caterpillar]]. Severely infected individuals are weak, unable to expand their wings, or unable to [[Eclosion|eclose]], and have shortened lifespans, but parasite levels vary in populations. Infection creates a [[culling]] effect, whereby infected migrating animals are less likely to complete the migration.  This results in populations with lower parasite loads at the end of the migration.<ref name=\"Bartel Ober\">{{cite journal|last1=Bartel |first1=Rebecca|last2=Oberhauser |first2=Karen |authorlink2=Karen Oberhauser |last3=De Roode |first3=Jacob|last4=Atizer|first4=Sonya |date=February 2011|title=Monarch butterfly migration and parasite transmission in eastern North America |journal=Ecology|volume=92|issue=2 |pages=342\u2013351 |doi=10.1890/10-0489.1|pmid=21618914}}</ref> This is not the case in laboratory or commercial rearing, where after a few generations, all individuals can be infected.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Leong |first=K. L. H. |author2=M. A. Yoshimura |author3=H. K. Kaya|author4=H. Williams|date=January 1997|title=Instar Susceptibility of the Monarch Butterfly (''Danaus plexippus'') to the Neogregarine Parasite, ''Ophryocystis elektroscirrha''|journal=Journal of Invertebrate Pathology |volume=69|issue=1 |pages=79\u201383|doi=10.1006/jipa.1996.4634|pmid=9028932 |lay-url=|citeseerx=10.1.1.494.9827 }}</ref>\n\n'''List of protozoan diseases in humans:'''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Life science fundamental and practice part I|last=Usha mina|first=Pranav kumar|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Disease\n!Causative agent\n!Source of Transmission\n|-\n|[[Amoebiasis]]\n|''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' ([[Amoebozoa]])\n|Water, food\n|-\n|[[Acanthamoeba keratitis]]\n|''[[Acanthamoeba]]'' ([[Amoebozoa]])\n|Water, contaminated contact lens solution\n|-\n|[[Giardiasis]]\n|''[[Giardia lamblia]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Water, Contact\n|-\n|[[Trichomoniasis]]\n|''[[Trichomonas vaginalis]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Sexual contact\n|-\n|[[Dientamoebiasis]] \n|''[[Dientamoeba fragilis]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Uncertain\n|-\n|[[African sleeping sickness]] (African trypanosomiasis)\n|''[[Trypanosoma brucei]]'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|[[Tsetse fly]] ([[Glossina]])\n|-\n|[[Chagas disease]] (American sleeping sickness)\n|''[[Trypanosoma cruzi]]'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|Triatomine bug ([[Triatominae]])\n|-\n|[[Leishmaniasis]]\n|''[[Leishmania]] spp.'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|Phlebotomine [[Sandfly]] ([[Phlebotominae]])\n|-\n|[[Balantidiasis]]\n|''[[Balantidium coli]]'' ([[Ciliate]])\n|Food, water\n|-\n|[[Malaria]]\n|''[[Plasmodium]] spp.'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Mosquito ([[Anopheles]])\n|-\n|[[Toxoplasmosis]]\n|''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Undercooked meat, cat feces, fetal infection in pregnancy\n|-\n|[[Babesiosis]]\n|''[[Babesia]]'' spp. ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Deer tick (''[[Ixodes scapularis]]'')\n|-\n|''[[Cryptosporidiosis]]'' \n|''[[Cryptosporidium]]'' spp. ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Fecal contamination of food or water\n|-\n|''[[Cyclosporiasis]]'' \n|''[[Cyclospora cayetanensis]]'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Fecal contamination of food or water\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|28em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n; General\n* Dogiel, V. A., revised by J.I. Poljanskij and E. M. Chejsin. ''General Protozoology'', 2nd ed., Oxford University Press, 1965.\n* Hausmann, K., N. Hulsmann. ''Protozoology''. Thieme Verlag; New York, 1996.\n* Kudo, R.R. ''[[iarchive:protozoology1954kudo|Protozoology]]''. Springfield, Illinois: C.C. Thomas, 1954; 4th ed.\n* Manwell, R.D. ''Introduction to Protozoology'', second revised edition, Dover Publications Inc., New York, 1968.\n* Roger Anderson, O. ''Comparative protozoology: ecology, physiology, life history''. Berlin [etc.]: Springer-Verlag, 1988.\n* Sleigh, M. ''The Biology of Protozoa''. E. Arnold: London, 1981.\n; Identification\n* Jahn,T.L.- Bovee, E.C. & Jahn, F.F.  ''How to Know the Protozoa''. Wm. C. Brown Publishers, Div. of McGraw Hill, Dubuque, Iowa, 1979; 2nd ed.\n* Lee, J.J., Leedale, G.F. & Bradbury, P. ''An Illustrated Guide to the Protozoa''. Lawrence, Kansas, U.S.A: Society of Protozoologists, 2000; 2nd ed.\n* Patterson, D.J. ''Free-Living Freshwater Protozoa. A Colour Guide''. Manson Publishing; London, 1996.\n* Patterson, D.J., M.A. Burford. ''A Guide to the Protozoa of Marine Aquaculture Ponds''. CSIRO Publishing, 2001.\n; Morphology\n* Harrison, F.W., Corliss, J.O. (ed.). 1991. ''Microscopic Anatomy of Invertebrates'', vol. 1, Protozoa. New York: Wiley-Liss, 512 pp.\n* Pitelka, D. R. 1963. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/7050#/summary ''Electron-Microscopic Structure of Protozoa'']. Pergamon Press, Oxford.\n; Physiology and biochemistry\n* Nisbet, B. 1984. ''Nutrition and feeding strategies in Protozoa.'' Croom Helm Publ., London, 280 pp.\n* Coombs, G.H. & North, M. 1991. ''Biochemical protozoology''. Taylor & Francis, London, Washington.\n* Laybourn-Parry J. 1984. ''A Functional Biology of Free-Living Protozoa''. Berkeley, California: University of California Press.\n* Levandowski, M., S.H. Hutner (eds). 1979. ''Biochemistry and physiology of protozoa''. Volumes 1, 2, and 3. Academic Press: New York, NY; 2nd ed.\n* Sukhareva-Buell, N.N. 2003. ''Biologically active substances of protozoa''. Dordrecht: Kluwer.\n; Ecology\n* Capriulo, G.M. (ed.). 1990. ''Ecology of Marine Protozoa.'' Oxford Univ. Press, New York.\n* Darbyshire, J.F. (ed.). 1994. ''Soil Protozoa.'' CAB International: Wallingford, U.K. 2009 pp.\n* Laybourn-Parry, J. 1992. ''Protozoan plankton ecology.'' Chapman & Hall, New York. 213 pp.\n* Fenchel, T. 1987. ''Ecology of protozoan: The biology of free-living phagotrophic protists.'' Springer-Verlag, Berlin. 197 pp.\n; Parasitology\n* Kreier, J.P. (ed.). 1991\u20131995. ''Parasitic Protozoa'', 2nd ed. 10 vols (1-3 coedited by Baker, J.R.). Academic Press, San Diego, California, [https://books.google.com/books/about/Parasitic_Protozoa.html?id=6OFTrgEACAAJ].\n; Methods\n* Lee, J. J., & Soldo, A. T. (1992). ''Protocols in protozoology''. Kansas, USA: Society of Protozoologists, Lawrence, [http://protozoa.uga.edu/pub/Protocols_in_protozoology.pdf].\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies|Protozoa}}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Protozoa}}\n\n{{Infectious disease}}{{Eukaryota classification}}{{Protozoa protist}}{{Taxonbar|from=Q101274}}{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1670s in science]]\n[[Category:Obsolete eukaryote taxa]]\n[[Category:Paraphyletic groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Diverse motile unicellular heterotrophic eukaryotic organisms}}\n[[File:Protozoa collage 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|Clockwise from top left: ''[[Blepharisma japonicum]]'', a [[ciliate]]; ''[[Giardia|Giardia muris]]'', a parasitic [[flagellate]]; ''[[Centropyxis aculeata]]'', a testate (shelled) [[amoeba]]; ''[[Peridinium willei]]'', a dinoflagellate; ''[[Chaos carolinense]]'', a naked amoebozoan; ''[[Desmerella moniliformis]]'', a [[choanoflagellate]] ]]\n\n'''Protozoa''' (also '''protozoan''', plural '''protozoans''') is an informal term for single-celled [[eukaryotes]], either free-living or [[Parasitism|parasitic]], which feed on organic matter such as other [[microorganism]]s or organic tissues and debris.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sYgKY6zz20YC&pg=PA130&lpg=PA130&dq=panno+the+cell#v=onepage&q=panno%20the%20cell&f=false|title=The Cell: Evolution of the First Organism|last=Panno|first=Joseph|date=14 May 2014|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9780816067367|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2zVqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&dq=bertrand+microbiology#v=snippet&q=endocytosis&f=false|title=Environmental Microbiology: Fundamentals and Applications: Microbial Ecology|last=Bertrand|first=Jean-Claude|last2=Caumette|first2=Pierre|last3=Lebaron|first3=Philippe|last4=Matheron|first4=Robert|last5=Normand|first5=Philippe|last6=Sime-Ngando|first6=T\u00e9lesphore|date=2015-01-26|publisher=Springer|isbn=9789401791182|language=en}}</ref> Historically, the protozoa were regarded as \"one-celled animals\", because they often possess [[animal]]-like behaviors, such as [[motility]] and [[predation]], and lack a [[cell wall]], as found in plants and many [[algae]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RawZTwEACAAJ&dq=brock+biology+of+microorganisms+13th|title=Brock Biology of Microorganisms |last=Madigan |first=Michael T. |date=2012 |publisher=Benjamin Cummings |isbn=9780321649638}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK8325/ |title=Protozoa: Structure, Classification, Growth, and Development |last=Yaeger |first=Robert G. |date=1996 |publisher=NCBI|pmid=21413323 |access-date=2018-03-23|isbn=9780963117212 }}</ref>  Although the traditional practice of grouping protozoa with animals is no longer considered valid, the term continues to be used in a loose way to identify single-celled organisms that can move independently and feed by [[heterotroph]]y.\n\nIn some systems of biological classification, '''Protozoa''' is a high-level [[Taxon|taxonomic group]]. When first introduced in 1818, Protozoa was erected as a [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] [[Class (biology)|class]],<ref name = \"Goldfu\u00df\"/> but in later classification schemes it was elevated to a variety of higher ranks, including [[Phylum (biology)|phylum]], [[Subkingdom (biology)|subkingdom]] and [[Kingdom (biology)|kingdom]]. In a series of classifications proposed by [[Thomas Cavalier-Smith]] and his collaborators since 1981, Protozoa has been ranked as a [[Kingdom (biology)|kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=1981 |title=Eukaryote kingdoms: seven or nine? |journal=Bio Systems |volume=14 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=461\u2013481 |doi=10.1016/0303-2647(81)90050-2 |pmid=7337818}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=December 1993 |title=Kingdom protozoa and its 18 phyla |journal=Microbiological Reviews |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=953\u2013994 |pmc=372943 |pmid=8302218 |doi=10.1128/mmbr.57.4.953-994.1993}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cavalier-Smith |first=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=23 June 2010 |title=Kingdoms Protozoa and Chromista and the eozoan root of the eukaryotic tree |journal=Biology Letters |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=342\u2013345 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2009.0948 |pmc=2880060 |pmid=20031978}}</ref> The seven-kingdom scheme presented by Ruggiero et al. in 2015, places eight phyla under Kingdom Protozoa: [[Euglenozoa]], [[Amoebozoa]], [[Metamonada]], [[Choanozoa]] ''sensu'' Cavalier-Smith, [[Loukozoa]], [[Percolozoa]], [[Microsporidia]] and [[Sulcozoa]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Notably, this kingdom excludes several major groups of organisms traditionally placed among the protozoa, including the ciliates, [[dinoflagellate]]s, [[foraminifera]], and the parasitic [[apicomplexa]]ns, all of which are classified under Kingdom [[Chromista]]. Kingdom Protozoa, as defined in this scheme, does not form a natural group or [[clade]], but a [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] group or [[evolutionary grade]], within which the members of [[Fungi]], [[Animalia]] and Chromista are thought to have evolved.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Georg_August_Goldfuss_Protozoa_Infusoria_Monades.jpg|left|thumb|upright=1.35|Class Protozoa, order [[Infusoria]], family Monades by [[Georg August Goldfuss]], c. 1844]]\n\nThe word \"protozoa\" (singular ''protozoon'' or ''protozoan'') was coined in 1818 by [[zoologist]] [[Georg August Goldfuss]], as the Greek equivalent of the German ''{{lang|de|Urthiere}}'', meaning \"primitive, or original animals\" (''{{lang|de|{{linktext|ur-}}}}'' \u2018proto-\u2019 + ''{{lang|de|{{linktext|Thier}}}}'' \u2018animal\u2019).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rothschild|first=Lynn J.|date=1989|title=Protozoa, Protista, Protoctista: What's in a Name?|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/4331095|journal=Journal of the History of Biology|volume=22|issue=2|pages=277\u2013305|issn=0022-5010}}</ref> Goldfuss created Protozoa as a [[Class (biology)|class]] containing what he believed to be the simplest animals.<ref name = \"Goldfu\u00df\">{{cite journal |last1=Goldfu\u00df |title=Ueber die Classification der Zoophyten |journal=Isis, Oder, Encyclop\u00e4dische Zeitung von Oken |date=1818 |volume=2 |issue=6 |pages=1008\u20131019 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/47614#page/530/mode/1up |trans-title=On the classification of zoophytes |language=German}} From p. 1008:  ''\"Erste Klasse.  Urthiere.  Protozoa.\"''  (First class.  Primordial animals.  Protozoa.) [Note:  each column of each page of this journal is numbered; there are two columns per page.]</ref> Originally, the group included not only single-celled [[microorganism]]s but also some \"lower\" [[Multicellular organism|multicellular]] animals, such as [[rotifer]]s, [[coral]]s, [[sponge]]s, [[jellyfish]], [[bryozoa]] and [[Polychaete|polychaete worms]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goldfu\u00df |first1=Georg August |title=Handbuch der Zoologie. Erste Abtheilung. |trans-title=Handbook of Zoology. First Part. |date=1820 |publisher=Johann Leonhard Schrag |location=N\u00fcrnberg, (Germany) |pages=XI\u2013XIV |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015070878148;view=1up;seq=11 |language=German}}</ref> The term ''Protozoa'' is formed from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] words {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03c0\u03c1\u1ff6\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}} ({{grc-transl|\u03c0\u03c1\u1ff6\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}}), meaning \"first\", and {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03b1}} ({{grc-transl|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03b1}}), plural of {{wikt-lang|grc|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03bf\u03bd}} ({{grc-transl|\u03b6\u1ff6\u03bf\u03bd}}), meaning \"animal\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Abr\u00e9g\u00e9 du dictionnaire grec fran\u00e7ais|last=Bailly|first=Anatole|date=1981-01-01|publisher=Hachette|isbn=978-2010035289|location=Paris|oclc=461974285}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tabularium.be/bailly/|title=Greek-french dictionary online|last=Bailly|first=Anatole|date=|website=www.tabularium.be|publisher=|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref> The use of Protozoa as a formal [[taxon]] has been discouraged by some researchers, mainly because the term implies kinship with animals (Metazoa)<ref name=\"Hogg\">{{Cite journal |last=Hogg |first=John |authorlink=John Hogg |date=1860 |title=On the distinctions of a plant and an animal, and on a fourth kingdom of nature |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044089575245;view=1up;seq=232 |journal=Edinburgh New Philosophical Journal | series=2nd series | volume=12 | pages=216\u2013225 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Scamardella |first=J. M. |date=December 1999 |title=Not plants or animals: a brief history of the origin of Kingdoms Protozoa, Protista and Protoctista |journal=International Microbiology |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=207\u2013216 |pmid=10943416}}</ref> and promotes an arbitrary separation of \"animal-like\" from \"plant-like\" organisms.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Copeland |first=Herbert F. |date=September\u2013October 1947 |title=Progress Report on Basic Classification |journal=The American Naturalist |volume=81 |issue=800 |pages=340\u2013361 |doi=10.1086/281531 |jstor=2458229|pmid=20267535 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1848, as a result of advancements in [[cell theory]] pioneered by [[Theodor Schwann]] and [[Matthias Jakob Schleiden|Matthias Schleiden]], the anatomist and zoologist [[Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold|C. T. von Siebold]] proposed that the bodies of protozoans such as [[ciliate]]s and [[amoeba]]e consisted of single cells, similar to those from which the [[Multicellular organism|multicellular]] tissues of plants and animals were constructed. Von Siebold redefined Protozoa to include only such [[Unicellular organism|unicellular]] forms, to the exclusion of all [[Animal|metazoa]] (animals).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Siebold (vol. 1) |last2=Stannius (vol. 2) |title=Lehrbuch der vergleichenden Anatomie [Textbook of Comparative Anatomy] |date=1848 |publisher=Veit & Co. |location=Berlin, (Germany) |volume= vol. 1: ''Wirbellose Thiere'' (Invertebrate animals) |page=3 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/41783#page/21/mode/1up |language=German}}  From p. 3:  ''\"Erste Hauptgruppe.  Protozoa.  Thiere, in welchen die verschiedenen Systeme der Organe nicht scharf ausgeschieden sind, und deren unregelm\u00e4ssige Form und einfache Organisation sich auf eine Zelle reduziren lassen.\"''  (First principal group.  Protozoa.  Animals, in which the different systems of organs are not sharply separated, and whose irregular form and simple organization can be reduced to one cell.)</ref> At the same time, he raised the group to the level of a [[phylum]] containing two broad classes of microorganisms: [[Infusoria]] (mostly ciliates and flagellated [[algae]]), and Rhizopoda ([[Amoeba|amoeboid organisms]]). The definition of Protozoa as a phylum or sub-kingdom composed of \"unicellular animals\" was adopted by the zoologist [[Otto B\u00fctschli]]\u2014celebrated at his centenary as the \"architect of protozoology\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dobell|first=C.|date=April 1951|title=In memoriam Otto B\u00fctschli (1848-1920) \"architect of protozoology\"|journal=Isis; an International Review Devoted to the History of Science and Its Cultural Influences|volume=42|issue=127|pages=20\u201322 |pmid=14831973|doi=10.1086/349230}}</ref>\u2014and the term came into wide use.\n\n[[File:John_Hogg_--_Primigenum_or_Protoctista.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|[[John Hogg (biologist)|John Hogg]]'s illustration of the Four Kingdoms of Nature, showing \"Primigenal\" as a greenish haze at the base of the Animals and Plants, 1860]]\n\nAs a phylum under Animalia, the Protozoa were firmly rooted in the old \"two-kingdom\" classification of life, according to which all living beings were classified as either animals or plants. As long as this scheme remained dominant, the protozoa were understood to be animals and studied in departments of Zoology, while photosynthetic microorganisms and microscopic fungi\u2014the so-called Protophyta\u2014were assigned to the Plants, and studied in departments of Botany.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Taylor |first=F. J. R. 'Max' |date=11 January 2003 |title=The collapse of the two-kingdom system, the rise of protistology and the founding of the International Society for Evolutionary Protistology (ISEP) |url=http://ijs.sgmjournals.org/content/53/6/1707 |journal=International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology |volume=53 |issue=6 |pages=1707\u20131714 |doi=10.1099/ijs.0.02587-0 |pmid=14657097}}</ref>\n\nCriticism of this system began in the latter half of the 19th century, with the realization that many organisms met the criteria for inclusion among both plants and animals. For example, the algae ''[[Euglena]]'' and ''[[Dinobryon]]'' have [[chloroplast]]s for [[photosynthesis]], but can also feed on organic matter and are [[Motility|motile]]. In 1860, [[John Hogg (biologist)|John Hogg]] argued against the use of \"protozoa\", on the grounds that \"naturalists are divided in opinion\u2014and probably some will ever continue so\u2014whether many of these organisms, or living beings, are animals or plants.\"<ref name=\"Hogg\" /> As an alternative, he proposed a new kingdom called Primigenum, consisting of both the protozoa and unicellular algae (protophyta), which he combined together under the name \"Protoctista\". In Hoggs's conception, the animal and plant kingdoms were likened to two great \"pyramids\" blending at their bases in the Kingdom Primigenum.\n\nSix years later, [[Ernst Haeckel]] also proposed a third kingdom of life, which he named [[Protista]]. At first, Haeckel included a few multicellular organisms in this kingdom, but in later work he restricted the Protista to single-celled organisms, or simple colonies whose individual cells are not differentiated into different kinds of [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]].\n\nDespite these proposals, Protozoa emerged as the preferred taxonomic placement for [[Heterotrophic nutrition|heterotrophic]] microorganisms such as amoebae and ciliates, and remained so for more than a century. In the course of the 20th century, however, the old \"two kingdom\" system began to weaken, with the growing awareness that fungi did not belong among the plants, and that most of the unicellular protozoa were no more closely related to the animals than they were to the plants. By mid-century, some biologists, such as [[Herbert Copeland]], [[Robert H. Whittaker]] and [[Lynn Margulis]], advocated the revival of Haeckel's Protista or Hogg's Protoctista as a kingdom-level eukaryotic group, alongside Plants, Animals and Fungi.<ref name=\":0\" /> A variety of [[Kingdom (biology)|multi-kingdom systems]] were proposed, and Kingdoms Protista and Protoctista became well established in biology texts and curricula.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Whittaker |first=R. H. |date=10 January 1969 |title=New concepts of kingdoms or organisms. Evolutionary relations are better represented by new classifications than by the traditional two kingdoms |journal=Science |volume=163 |issue=3863 |pages=150\u2013160 |bibcode=1969Sci...163..150W|doi=10.1126/science.163.3863.150 |pmid=5762760|citeseerx=10.1.1.403.5430 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Margulis |first=Lynn |authorlink=Lynn Margulis |date=1974 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-1-4615-6946-6 |editor-last=Dobzhansky|editor-first=Theodosius |pages=45\u201378 |editor-last2=Hecht |editor-first2=Max K.|editor-last3=Steere |editor-first3=William C. |doi=10.1007/978-1-4615-6944-2_2 |chapter=Five-Kingdom Classification and the Origin and Evolution of Cells |title=Evolutionary Biology}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Cavalier-Smith, Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |date=August 1998 |title=A revised six-kingdom system of life |journal=Biological Reviews |volume=73 |issue=3 |pages=203\u2013266 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-185X.1998.tb00030.x |pmid=9809012}}</ref>\n\nWhile many taxonomists have abandoned Protozoa as a high-level group, Thomas Cavalier-Smith has retained it as a kingdom in the various classifications he has proposed. As of 2015, Cavalier-Smith's Protozoa excludes several major groups of organisms traditionally placed among the protozoa, including the ciliates, [[dinoflagellate]]s and [[foraminifera]] (all members of the [[SAR supergroup]]). In its current form, his kingdom Protozoa is a [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] group which includes a common ancestor and most of its descendants, but excludes two important clades that branch within it: the animals and fungi.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Ruggiero |first=Michael A. |last2=Gordon |first2=Dennis P. |last3=Orrell |first3=Thomas M. |last4=Bailly |first4=Nicolas |last5=Bourgoin |first5=Thierry |last6=Brusca |first6=Richard C. |last7=Cavalier-Smith |first7=Thomas |authorlink=Tom Cavalier-Smith |last8=Guiry |first8=Michael D. |last9=Kirk |first9=Paul M. |date=29 April 2015 |title=A Higher Level Classification of All Living Organisms |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=10 |issue=4 |pages=e0119248 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1019248R|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0119248 |pmc=4418965 |pmid=25923521}}</ref>\n\nSince the protozoa, as traditionally defined, can no longer be regarded as \"primitive animals\" the terms \"protists\", \"Protista\" or \"Protoctista\" are sometimes preferred. In 2005, members of the Society of [[Protozoologist]]s voted to change its name to the International Society of [[Protistologist]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://protozoa.uga.edu/artman/publish/article_37.shtml |title=New President's Address|website=protozoa.uga.edu |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n=== Size ===\n\nProtozoa, as traditionally defined, range in size from as little as 1 [[micrometers|micrometre]] to several [[millimetre]]s, or more.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pddpAAAAMAAJ|title=Dictionary of microbiology and molecular biology|last=Singleton|first=Paul|last2=Sainsbury|first2=Diana|date=2001|publisher=Wiley|isbn=9780471941507|language=en}}</ref> Among the largest are the deep-sea\u2013dwelling [[xenophyophores]], single-celled foraminifera whose shells can reach 20&nbsp;cm in diameter.<ref name=\"Gooday2011\">{{cite journal |last=Gooday |first=A.J. |last2=Aranda da Silva |first2=A. P. |last3=Pawlowski |first3=J. |title=Xenophyophores (Rhizaria, Foraminifera) from the Nazar\u00e9 Canyon (Portuguese margin, NE Atlantic) |journal=Deep-Sea Research Part II: Topical Studies in Oceanography|date=1 December 2011 |volume=58 |issue=24\u201325 |pages=2401\u20132419 |bibcode=2011DSRII..58.2401G |doi=10.1016/j.dsr2.2011.04.005 }}</ref> \n[[File:Spirostomum.jpeg|thumb|The ciliate ''Spirostomum ambiguum'' can attain 3 mm in length]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Species \n!Cell type\n!Size in micrometres\n|-\n|''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'' || [[malaria]] [[parasite]], trophozoite phase<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microbiologybook.org/parasitology/blood-malaria.htm|title=Blood and Tissue Protozoa|last=Ghaffar|first=Abdul|website=Microbiology and Immunology On-Line|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|1-2\n|-\n|''[[Massisteria|Massisteria voersi]]'' || free-living [[cercozoa]]n amoeboid<ref name=\"Mylnikov\">{{Cite journal|last=Mylnikov|first=Alexander P.|last2=Weber|first2=Felix|last3=J\u00fcrgens|first3=Klaus|last4=Wylezich|first4=Claudia|date=August 2015|title=''Massisteria marina'' has a sister: ''Massisteria voersi'' sp. nov., a rare species isolated from coastal waters of the Baltic Sea|journal=European Journal of Protistology |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=299\u2013310|doi=10.1016/j.ejop.2015.05.002|pmid=26163290}}</ref> \n|2.3\u20133\n|-\n|''[[Bodo saltans]]'' || free living [[Kinetoplastida|kinetoplastid]] flagellate<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mitchell|first=Gary C.|last2=Baker|first2=J. H.|last3=Sleigh |first3=M. A. |date=1 May 1988|title=Feeding of a freshwater flagellate, ''Bodo saltans'', on diverse bacteria |journal=The Journal of Protozoology |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=219\u2013222 |doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.1988.tb04327.x}}</ref>\n|5-8\n|-\n|''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'' || [[malaria]] parasite, gametocyte phase<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microbiologybook.org/parasitology/blood-malaria.htm|title=Blood and tissue Protozoa|last=Ghaffar|first=Abdul |website=Microbiology and Immunology On-Line |accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|7-14\n|-\n|''[[Trypanosoma cruzi]]'' || parasitic kinetoplastid, [[Chagas disease]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parasite.org.au/para-site/text/brucei-text.html |title=''Trypanosoma brucei'' |website=parasite.org.au |access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|14-24\n|-\n|''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' || parasitic [[amoebozoa]]n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://msu.edu/course/zol/316/ehisscope.htm |title=Microscopy of ''Entamoeba histolytica''|website=msu.edu|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n|15\u201360\n|-\n|''[[Balantidium coli]]'' || parasitic ciliate<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.udel.edu/mls/dlehman/medt372/B-coli.html |title=Diagnostic parasitology |last=Lehman |first=Don |website=University of Delaware|accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|50-100\n|-\n|''[[Paramecium caudatum]]'' || free-living ciliate<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eol.org/pages/484358/overview|title=''Paramecium caudatum''|last=Taylor|first=Bruce|website=Encyclopedia of Life|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|120-330\n|-\n|''[[Amoeba proteus]]'' || free-living amoebozoan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arcella.nl/amoeba-proteus|title=''Amoeba proteus'' {{!}} Microworld|website=www.arcella.nl|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n|220\u2013760\n|-\n|''[[Noctiluca scintillans]]'' || free-living [[dinoflagellate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imas.utas.edu.au/zooplankton/image-key/noctiluca-scintillans|title=''Noctiluca scintillans''|date=2011-11-30|website=University of Tasmania, Australia|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n|700\u20132000\n|-\n|''[[Syringammina fragilissima]]'' || [[foraminifera]]n amoeboid<ref name=\"Gooday2011\"/>\n|up to {{val|200000}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Habitat ===\nFree-living protozoans are common and often abundant in fresh, brackish and salt water, as well as other moist environments, such as soils and mosses. Some species thrive in extreme environments such as hot springs<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mJAxvgAACAAJ&dq=yellowstone+microorganisms|title=Seen and Unseen: Discovering the Microbes of Yellowstone|last=Sheehan|first=Kathy B.|date=2005|publisher=Falcon|isbn=9780762730933|language=en}}</ref> and hypersaline lakes and lagoons.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Post|first=F. J.|last2=Borowitzka|first2=L. J.|last3=Borowitzka|first3=M. A.|last4=Mackay|first4=B.|last5=Moulton|first5=T.|date=1983-09-01|title=The protozoa of a Western Australian hypersaline lagoon|journal=Hydrobiologia|language=en|volume=105|issue=1|pages=95\u2013113|doi=10.1007/BF00025180|issn=0018-8158|bibcode=2004HyBio.524..167W}}</ref>   All protozoa require a moist habitat; however, some can survive for long periods of time in dry environments, by forming [[Microbial cyst|resting cysts]] which enable them to remain dormant until conditions improve.\n\n[[Parasitism|Parasitic]] and [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] protozoa live on or within other organisms, including [[vertebrate]]s and [[invertebrate]]s, as well as plants and other single-celled organisms. Some are harmless or beneficial to their host organisms; others may be significant causes of diseases, such as [[babesia]], [[malaria]] and [[toxoplasmosis]].\n[[File:Isotricha intestinalis.jpg|thumb|''[[Isotricha intestinalis]]'', a ciliate present in the rumen of sheep.]]\nAssociation between protozoan symbionts and their host organisms can be mutually beneficial. Flagellated protozoans such as ''[[Trichonympha]]'' and ''[[Pyrsonympha]]'' inhabit the guts of termites, where they enable their insect host to digest wood by helping to break down complex [[sugar]]s into smaller, more easily digested molecules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kennethnoll.uconn.edu/nsf-termite-project/termite-gut-microbes.html|title=Termite gut microbes {{!}} NOLL LAB|website=www.kennethnoll.uconn.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> A wide range of protozoans live [[Commensalism|commensally]] in the rumens of ruminant animals, such as cattle and sheep. These include flagellates, such as ''[[Trichomonas]]'', and ciliated protozoa, such as ''[[Isotricha]]'' and ''[[Entodinium]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Rumen Microbial Ecosystem|last=Williams|first=A. G.|last2=Coleman|first2=G. S.|date=1997|publisher=Springer, Dordrecht|isbn=9789401071499|pages=73\u2013139|doi=10.1007/978-94-009-1453-7_3}}</ref>  The ciliate subclass Astomatia is composed entirely of mouthless symbionts adapted for life in the guts of annelid worms.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hY0WAQAAIAAJ|title=An illustrated guide to the protozoa: organisms traditionally referred to as protozoa, or newly discovered groups|last=Lee|first=John J.|last2=Leedale|first2=Gordon F.|last3=Bradbury|first3=Phyllis Clarke|date=25 May 2000|publisher=Society of Protozoologists|isbn=|location=|pages=634|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Feeding ===\n\nAll protozoans are [[heterotroph]]ic, deriving nutrients from other organisms, either by ingesting them whole or consuming their organic remains and waste-products. Some protozoans take in food by [[phagocytosis]], engulfing organic particles with [[pseudopodia]] (as [[amoeba]]e do), or taking in food through a specialized mouth-like aperture called a [[cytostome]]. Others take in food by [[osmotrophy]], absorbing dissolved nutrients through their [[cell membrane]]s.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nParasitic protozoans use a wide variety of feeding strategies, and some may change methods of feeding in different phases of their life cycle. For instance, the malaria parasite ''[[Plasmodium]]'' feeds by [[pinocytosis]] during its immature [[Apicomplexan life cycle|trophozoite]] stage of life (ring phase), but develops a dedicated feeding [[organelle]] (cytostome) as it matures within a host's red blood cell.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tulane.edu/~wiser/malaria/fv.html |title=Biochemistry of Plasmodium |last=Wiser |first=Mark F. |website=The Wiser Page |access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ameba_001.jpg|thumb|''[[Paramecium bursaria]]'', a ciliate which derives some of its nutrients from algal [[endosymbiont]]s in the genus ''[[Chlorella]]'']]\n\nProtozoa may also live as [[mixotroph]]s, supplementing a heterotrophic diet with some form of [[autotroph]]y. Some protozoa form close associations with symbiotic photosynthetic algae, which live and grow within the membranes of the larger cell and provide nutrients to the host. Others practice [[kleptoplasty]], stealing [[chloroplast]]s from prey organisms and maintaining them within their own cell bodies as they continue to produce nutrients through photosynthesis. The ciliate ''[[Mesodinium rubrum]]'' retains functioning [[plastid]]s from the cryptophyte algae on which it feeds, using them to nourish themselves by autotrophy. These, in turn, may be passed along to dinoflagellates of the genus [[Dinophysis]] , which prey on ''Mesodinium rubrum'' but keep the enslaved plastids for themselves. Within Dinophysis, these plastids can continue to function for months.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Nishitani |first=Goh |last2=Nagai |first2=Satoshi |last3=Baba|first3=Katsuhisa |last4=Kiyokawa |first4=Susumu |last5=Kosaka|first5=Yuki |last6=Miyamura |first6=Kazuyoshi |last7=Nishikawa |first7=Tetsuya |last8=Sakurada |first8=Kiyonari |last9=Shinada |first9=Akiyoshi |date=May 2010 |title=High-Level Congruence of Myrionecta rubra Prey and Dinophysis Species Plastid Identities as Revealed by Genetic Analyses of Isolates from Japanese Coastal Waters |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |volume=76|issue=9 |pages=2791\u20132798 |doi=10.1128/AEM.02566-09 |pmc=2863437 |pmid=20305031}}</ref>\n\n=== Motility ===\n\nOrganisms traditionally classified as protozoa are abundant in [[aqueous]] environments and [[soil]], occupying a range of [[trophic level]]s. The group includes [[flagellate]]s (which move with the help of whip-like structures called [[flagella]]), [[ciliate]]s (which move by using hair-like structures called [[cilia]]) and [[amoeba]]e (which move by the use of foot-like structures called [[pseudopodia]]). Some protozoa are [[Sessility (zoology)|sessile]], and do not move at all.\n\n=== Pellicle ===\nUnlike plants, fungi and most types of algae, protozoans do not typically have a rigid [[cell wall]], but are usually enveloped by elastic structures of membranes that permit movement of the cell. In some protozoans, such as the ciliates and [[euglenozoa]]ns, the cell is supported by a composite membranous envelope called the \"pellicle\". The pellicle gives some shape to the cell, especially during locomotion. Pellicles of protozoan organisms vary from flexible and elastic to fairly rigid.  In [[ciliate]]s and [[Apicomplexa]], the pellicle is supported by closely packed vesicles called alveoli. In [[euglenid]]s, it is formed from [[protein]] strips arranged spirally along the length of the body. Familiar examples of protists with a pellicle are the [[euglenoids]] and the ciliate ''[[Paramecium]]''. In some protozoa, the pellicle hosts [[Epibiont|epibiotic]] bacteria that adhere to the surface by their [[Pilus#fimbriae|fimbriae]] (attachment pili).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/protozoainbiolog00calk#page/1008/mode/2up Protozoa in biological research<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[File:Dileptus_viridis_cyst.jpg|thumb|Resting cyst of ciliated protozoan ''Dileptus viridis''.]]\n\n=== Life cycle ===\n[[File:Toxoplasmosis life cycle en.svg|thumb|Life cycle of parasitic protozoan, ''Toxoplasma gondii'']]\nSome protozoa have two-phase life cycles, alternating between proliferative stages (e.g., [[trophozoite]]s) and dormant [[Microbial cyst|cysts]]. As cysts, protozoa can survive harsh conditions, such as exposure to extreme temperatures or harmful chemicals, or long periods without access to nutrients, water, or oxygen for periods of time. Being a cyst enables parasitic species to survive outside of a host, and allows their transmission from one host to another. When protozoa are in the form of [[trophozoite]]s (Greek ''tropho'' = to nourish), they actively feed. The conversion of a trophozoite to cyst form is known as encystation, while the process of transforming back into a trophozoite is known as excystation.\n\nAll protozoans reproduce (not all) asexually by [[binary fission]] or multiple fission. Many protozoan species exchange genetic material by sexual means (typically, through [[Isogamy#Conjugation|conjugation]]); however, sexuality is generally decoupled from the process of reproduction, and does not immediately result in increased population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/ca/academic/subjects/life-sciences/evolutionary-biology/sex-and-death-protozoa-history-obsession|title=Sex and Death in Protozoa|website=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Origin and function of meiosis|meiotic sex]] is widespread among present day [[eukaryote]]s, it has, until recently, been unclear whether or not eukaryotes were sexual early in their evolution.  Due to recent advances in [[gene]] detection and other techniques, evidence has been found for some form of meiotic sex in an increasing number of protozoans of ancient lineage that diverged early in eukaryotic evolution.<ref>Bernstein H, Bernstein C (2013). Bernstein C, Bernstein H eds. ''Evolutionary Origin and Adaptive Function of Meiosis'. Meiosis. InTech. {{ISBN|978-953-51-1197-9}}''</ref>  (See [[Eukaryote#Reproduction|eukaryote reproduction]].)  Thus, such findings suggest that meiotic sex arose early in eukaryotic evolution. Examples of protozoan meiotic sexuality are described in the articles ''[[Amoebozoa]]'', ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'', ''[[Leishmania]]'', ''[[Plasmodium falciparum biology]]'', ''[[Paramecium]]'', ''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'', ''[[Trichomonas vaginalis]]'' and ''[[Trypanosoma brucei]]''.\n\n== Classification ==\n{{Further|wikispecies:Protozoa}}Historically, the Protozoa were classified as \"unicellular animals\", as distinct from the Protophyta, single-celled photosynthetic organisms (algae) which were considered primitive plants. Both groups were commonly given the rank of phylum, under the kingdom Protista.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/protozoology1954kudo|title=Protozoology|last=Kudo|first=Richard R. (Richard Roksabro)|date=1954|publisher=Springfield, Ill., C. C. Thomas|others=MBLWHOI Library}}</ref> In older systems of classification, the phylum Protozoa was commonly divided into several sub-groups, reflecting the means of locomotion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Honigberg|first=B. M.|author2=W. Balamuth|author3=E. C. Bovee|author4=J. O. Corliss|author5=M. Gojdics|author6=R. P. Hall|author7=R. R. Kudo|author8=N. D. Levine|author9=A. R. Lobblich|date=February 1964|title=A Revised Classification of the Phylum Protozoa|journal=Journal of Eukaryotic Microbiology|volume=11|issue=1|pages=7\u201320|doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.1964.tb01715.x|pmid=14119564|author10=J. Weiser}}</ref> Classification schemes differed, but throughout much of the 20th century the major groups of Protozoa included:\n\n* [[Flagellate]]s, or [[Flagellate|Mastigophora]] (motile cells equipped with whiplike organelles of locomotion, e.g., ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'')\n* [[Amoeba|Amoebae or Sarcodina]] (cells that move by extending [[pseudopodia]] or [[Lamellipodium|lamellipodia]], e.g., ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'')\n* [[Sporozoans]], or Sporozoa (parasitic, spore-producing cells, whose adult form lacks organs of motility, e.g., ''[[Plasmodium knowlesi]]'')\n** [[Apicomplexa]] (now in [[Alveolata]])\n** [[Microsporidia]] (now in [[Fungi]])\n** [[Ascetosporea]] (now in [[Rhizaria]])\n** [[Myxosporidia]] (now in [[Cnidaria]])\n* [[Ciliate]]s, or Ciliophora (cells equipped with large numbers of short hairlike organs of locomotion, e.g., ''[[Balantidium coli]]''\nWith the emergence of [[molecular phylogenetics]] and tools enabling researchers to directly compare the DNA of different organisms, it became evident that, of the main sub-groups of Protozoa, only the ciliates (Ciliophora) formed a natural group, or [[Monophyly|monophyletic]] [[clade]] (that is, a distinct lineage of organisms sharing common ancestry). The other classes or subphyla of Protozoa were all [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]] groups composed of organisms that, despite similarities of appearance or way of life, were not necessarily closely related to one another. In the system of [[eukaryote]] classification currently endorsed by the International Society of Protistologists, members of the old phylum Protozoa have been distributed among a variety of supergroups.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Adl|first=Sina M. |last2=Simpson |first2=Alastair G. B. |last3=Lane |first3=Christopher E. |last4=Luke\u0161 |first4=Julius |last5=Bass |first5=David |last6=Bowser |first6=Samuel S. |last7=Brown |first7=Matthew W. |last8=Burki |first8=Fabien |last9=Dunthorn |first9=Micah |date=2012-09-01 |title=The Revised Classification of Eukaryotes |journal=Journal of Eukaryotic Microbiology |volume=59 |issue=5 |pages=429\u2013514 |doi=10.1111/j.1550-7408.2012.00644.x |pmid=23020233 |pmc=3483872}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\nAs components of the [[Fauna (animals)#Microfauna|micro-]] and [[Fauna (animals)#Meiofauna|meiofauna]], protozoa are an important food source for [[microinvertebrate]]s. Thus, the ecological role of protozoa in the transfer of bacterial and algal production to successive [[Trophic pyramid|trophic levels]] is important. As predators, they prey upon [[unicellular]] or [[filamentous algae]], [[bacteria]], and [[microfungi]]. Protozoan species include both [[herbivore]]s and [[Heterotroph|consumers]] in the decomposer link of the [[food chain]]. They also control bacteria populations and [[biomass]] to some extent.\n\n=== Disease ===\n\n[[File:Trophozoites_of_Entamoeba_histolytica_with_ingested_erythrocytes.JPG|thumb|Trophozoites of the [[amoebic dysentery]] pathogen ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' with ingested human [[red blood cell]]s (dark circles)]]\n{{Main|Protozoan infection}}A number of protozoan [[pathogen]]s are [[human parasite]]s, causing diseases such as [[malaria]] (by ''[[Plasmodium]]''), [[amoebiasis]], [[giardiasis]], [[toxoplasmosis]], [[cryptosporidiosis]], [[trichomoniasis]], [[Chagas disease]], [[leishmaniasis]], [[African trypanosomiasis]] (sleeping sickness), [[acanthamoeba keratitis]], and [[primary amoebic meningoencephalitis]] (naegleriasis).\n\nThe protozoan ''[[Ophryocystis elektroscirrha]]'' is a parasite of [[butterfly]] [[larva]]e, passed from [[Vertical transmission|female to caterpillar]]. Severely infected individuals are weak, unable to expand their wings, or unable to [[Eclosion|eclose]], and have shortened lifespans, but parasite levels vary in populations. Infection creates a [[culling]] effect, whereby infected migrating animals are less likely to complete the migration.  This results in populations with lower parasite loads at the end of the migration.<ref name=\"Bartel Ober\">{{cite journal|last1=Bartel |first1=Rebecca|last2=Oberhauser |first2=Karen |authorlink2=Karen Oberhauser |last3=De Roode |first3=Jacob|last4=Atizer|first4=Sonya |date=February 2011|title=Monarch butterfly migration and parasite transmission in eastern North America |journal=Ecology|volume=92|issue=2 |pages=342\u2013351 |doi=10.1890/10-0489.1|pmid=21618914}}</ref> This is not the case in laboratory or commercial rearing, where after a few generations, all individuals can be infected.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Leong |first=K. L. H. |author2=M. A. Yoshimura |author3=H. K. Kaya|author4=H. Williams|date=January 1997|title=Instar Susceptibility of the Monarch Butterfly (''Danaus plexippus'') to the Neogregarine Parasite, ''Ophryocystis elektroscirrha''|journal=Journal of Invertebrate Pathology |volume=69|issue=1 |pages=79\u201383|doi=10.1006/jipa.1996.4634|pmid=9028932 |lay-url=|citeseerx=10.1.1.494.9827 }}</ref>\n\n'''List of protozoan diseases in humans:'''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Life science fundamental and practice part I|last=Usha mina|first=Pranav kumar|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Disease\n!Causative agent\n!Source of Transmission\n|-\n|[[Amoebiasis]]\n|''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' ([[Amoebozoa]])\n|Water, food\n|-\n|[[Acanthamoeba keratitis]]\n|''[[Acanthamoeba]]'' ([[Amoebozoa]])\n|Water, contaminated contact lens solution\n|-\n|[[Giardiasis]]\n|''[[Giardia lamblia]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Water, Contact\n|-\n|[[Trichomoniasis]]\n|''[[Trichomonas vaginalis]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Sexual contact\n|-\n|[[Dientamoebiasis]] \n|''[[Dientamoeba fragilis]]'' ([[Metamonada]])\n|Uncertain\n|-\n|[[African sleeping sickness]] (African trypanosomiasis)\n|''[[Trypanosoma brucei]]'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|[[Tsetse fly]] ([[Glossina]])\n|-\n|[[Chagas disease]] (American sleeping sickness)\n|''[[Trypanosoma cruzi]]'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|Triatomine bug ([[Triatominae]])\n|-\n|[[Leishmaniasis]]\n|''[[Leishmania]] spp.'' ([[Kinetoplastida]])\n|Phlebotomine [[Sandfly]] ([[Phlebotominae]])\n|-\n|[[Balantidiasis]]\n|''[[Balantidium coli]]'' ([[Ciliate]])\n|Food, water\n|-\n|[[Malaria]]\n|''[[Plasmodium]] spp.'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Mosquito ([[Anopheles]])\n|-\n|[[Toxoplasmosis]]\n|''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Undercooked meat, cat feces, fetal infection in pregnancy\n|-\n|[[Babesiosis]]\n|''[[Babesia]]'' spp. ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Deer tick (''[[Ixodes scapularis]]'')\n|-\n|''[[Cryptosporidiosis]]'' \n|''[[Cryptosporidium]]'' spp. ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Fecal contamination of food or water\n|-\n|''[[Cyclosporiasis]]'' \n|''[[Cyclospora cayetanensis]]'' ([[Apicomplexa]])\n|Fecal contamination of food or water\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|28em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n; General\n* Dogiel, V. A., revised by J.I. Poljanskij and E. M. Chejsin. ''General Protozoology'', 2nd ed., Oxford University Press, 1965.\n* Hausmann, K., N. Hulsmann. ''Protozoology''. Thieme Verlag; New York, 1996.\n* Kudo, R.R. ''[[iarchive:protozoology1954kudo|Protozoology]]''. Springfield, Illinois: C.C. Thomas, 1954; 4th ed.\n* Manwell, R.D. ''Introduction to Protozoology'', second revised edition, Dover Publications Inc., New York, 1968.\n* Roger Anderson, O. ''Comparative protozoology: ecology, physiology, life history''. Berlin [etc.]: Springer-Verlag, 1988.\n* Sleigh, M. ''The Biology of Protozoa''. E. Arnold: London, 1981.\n; Identification\n* Jahn,T.L.- Bovee, E.C. & Jahn, F.F.  ''How to Know the Protozoa''. Wm. C. Brown Publishers, Div. of McGraw Hill, Dubuque, Iowa, 1979; 2nd ed.\n* Lee, J.J., Leedale, G.F. & Bradbury, P. ''An Illustrated Guide to the Protozoa''. Lawrence, Kansas, U.S.A: Society of Protozoologists, 2000; 2nd ed.\n* Patterson, D.J. ''Free-Living Freshwater Protozoa. A Colour Guide''. Manson Publishing; London, 1996.\n* Patterson, D.J., M.A. Burford. ''A Guide to the Protozoa of Marine Aquaculture Ponds''. CSIRO Publishing, 2001.\n; Morphology\n* Harrison, F.W., Corliss, J.O. (ed.). 1991. ''Microscopic Anatomy of Invertebrates'', vol. 1, Protozoa. New York: Wiley-Liss, 512 pp.\n* Pitelka, D. R. 1963. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/7050#/summary ''Electron-Microscopic Structure of Protozoa'']. Pergamon Press, Oxford.\n; Physiology and biochemistry\