2103\n| 118\n| 1081\n| 164\n| 3545\n| 1778\n| 1327\n| 3600\n| 1296\n| 223\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":29\" group=\"note\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 9\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |444\n| 304\n| 994\n| 18\n| 2336\n| 128\n| 1276\n| 177\n| 4045\n| 2007\n| 1507\n| 4041\n| 1461\n| 203\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":30\" group=\"note\" />\n|-\n ! style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | Date\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |Source\n|-\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | <strong>County <br /> pop <br /> (2020)</strong>\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n|\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.massachusetts-demographics.com/counties_by_population |access-date = April 6, 2020 | title = Massachusetts Counties by Population | website= Massachusetts Demographics}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:ASM show at BCEC.agr.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Boston Convention and Exposition Center]], which will be converted to a [[field hospital]]]]\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center, with multiple state departments working with contact with one another, Baker also promised an expansion of statewide lab testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/|title=State figures on testing raise questions about efforts to contain outbreak \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K-12 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | work = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original length by 3 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author= Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced his stay-at-home advisory effective March 24 until April 7, which was extended to May 4 on March 31.<ref name=\"Feuer\" /> Starting March 31 extension, hotels, motels and online rentals like [[AirBNB]] were ordered to close to recreational travelers, being reserved for essential workers and displaced residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-extends-non-essential-business-closures-and-executive-branch|title=Baker-Polito Administration Extends Non-Essential Business Closures and Executive Branch Employee Guidance|website=Mass.gov}}</ref>  The [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] is being set up as a 1,000 bed field hospital for COVID-19 patients, including 500 beds for infected homeless patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/02/1000-beds-planned-for-boston-convention-center-to-treat-coronavirus-patients|title=1,000 Beds Planned For Boston Convention Center To Treat Coronavirus Patients|date=April 2, 2020|first=Ally|last=Jarmanning|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[DCU Center]] in Worcester was set up as a field hospital for recovering COVID-19 patients, overseen by [[UMass Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/dcu-arena-covid-19-field-hospital|title=Worcester's DCU Center Will Become 250-Bed Field Hospital For Stable COVID-19 Patients|website=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Governor Baker asked travelers from out of state to avoid Massachusetts or to self-quarantine upon arrival for 14 days. Electronic highway signs were activated, and arrivals at [[Logan International Airport]], [[Worcester Regional Airport]], and [[South Station]] Boston were given flyers.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks \u2014 Or Not Come At All|website=www.wbur.org}}</ref> Medical students were graduated early, and emergency orders were issued giving some nurses with more than two years of experience to write prescriptions, and granting incoming medical residents and interns 90-day medical licenses.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\" />\n\n== Economic and social effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9, led to many organizations ordering workers to work from home and closures of museums and libraries, leading to a noticeable decline of Boston's notorious rush hour traffic. In some cases, drive times for major highways during Boston's rush hour dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref> [[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of various products, with many shoppers and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00&nbsp;a.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets |newspaper= The Boston Globe | access-date = April 6, 2020 | date= March 13, 2020 | first= Steve |last=Annear |first2=Janelle |last2=Nanos}}</ref> In response, some grocery retailers such as Stop & Shop adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a separate time where they can shop separately, but reminded shoppers to practice distancing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/ |title=Stop & Shop Creates Hours Only For Customers 60 And Older During Coronavirus Pandemic |date=March 16, 2020 |website=CBS Boston}}</ref> Later on, grocery stores would implement more strict measures, including limiting the amount of people inside the store at a given time, and marking queues to maintain social distancing. <!--- https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-market-basket-social-distance/ ---> Parks would later come under scrutiny after people were not following social distancing, which resulted in the shutdown of many parks and playgrounds. Some cities as far as to remove, barricade, and block off basketball hoops and other amenities. <!--- https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/29/marty-walsh-boston-parks-coronavirus ---> Beaches and their respective parking lots were also ordered closed to reduce the amount of people congregating. <!--- https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/parking-lots-state-beaches-are-closing/ ---> On Sunday, April 5, 2020, Boston's mayor, [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]], issued a stay at home order for the city of Boston. All residents that are not essential workers were ordered to stay home from 9:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;a.m., starting Monday, April 6, elderly can commute to grocery stores for their limited hours at 6:00&nbsp;a.m. Anyone that needed to be outside can make their own mask but medical masks are to be left for essential workers. All baseball, tennis, and hockey fields in parks would be closed. Residents were instructed not to visit family or fields outside of their households. Walsh warned that if people did not follow these guidelines, that the advisory would not be lifted sooner and they would not have a summer. People can also be issued violations and fines if they do not comply with the new orders.<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\" />\n\nAs of April 1, six deaths have been reported at Jack Satter House in [[Revere, Massachusetts|Revere]], a nursing home run by [[Hebrew Senior Life]]. Other nursing homes are also reporting confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boston-area senior housing community with Jewish ties reports 6 coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/boston-area-senior-housing-community-under-jewish-auspices-reports-6-coronavirus-deaths |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases at senior centers and nursing homes in Massachusetts are rising: 'It's a hot zone' - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/nation/covid-deaths-senior-centers-nursing-homes-rise/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== School closures ===\nSchool closures began in early March, starting on March 9, when MIT announced it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\" /> Also, on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> School districts began closing on March 11. Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\" /><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\" />\n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\" /> On March 25, Governor Baker extended the order with schools to open no sooner than May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season would be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Boston Bruins season|Boston Bruins]].<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Boston Marathon]], which was originally scheduled to take place on April 20, was postponed to September 14. This was the first postponement of the Boston Marathon since it was first held in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28897435/boston-marathon-postponed-sept-14-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title = Boston Marathon postponed until Sept. 14 amid coronavirus concerns|website = ESPN|date = March 13, 2020|accessdate = March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus 